<HEAD>Imad Mughniyeh Pegged As Mastermind Of Kuwait Airways Hijacking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with one hijacker wanted in
United States in 1985 TWA hijacking. Pickup 3rd graf pvs ``Western
intelligence...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The alleged mastermind behind the hijacking of <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> Flight 422 is a longtime fugitive from justice linked to two earlier hijacks. <PERSON> Imad </PERSON> <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON>, 36, is one of four suspects wanted by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in the hijacking of a <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> airliner on June 14, 1985, by Shiite Moslem extremists. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days before being freed after Syrian intervention. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, a <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration official said another man wanted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> hijacking was believed to be a hijacker on the Kuwaiti plane. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the man, <PERSON> Hasan </PERSON> <PERSON> Izz-Al-Din </PERSON>, was named in a 1987 federal indictment charging him and three others with conspiracy to commit air piracy, murder and assault in the hijacking. Western intelligence agencies also believe <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON> was involved in the December 1984 hijacking of a Kuwaiti airliner to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> that left two Americans dead. Iranian security forces stormed the plane after five days. The hijackers disappeared and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> has issued no word about them. Western sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON> is the leader of a clan, one of several in the <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> of eastern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> that control the drug trade in there. He also is chief of security for the pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> is considered by Western and Lebanese intelligence agencies to be the umbrella organization for groups holding foreigners hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON>'s cousin and brother-in-law is one of the three Shiites among the 17 imprisoned in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> who have been sentenced to death. Western observers have said it is this family connection that has fueled <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON>'s mission to free the 17 terrorists. The Kuwaitis have identified the condemned man as <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Saab </PERSON>, but his real name is <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Badreddin </PERSON>. He entered <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> on a forged Iraqi passport, Western intelligence authorities said. Ever since <PERSON> Badreddin </PERSON> was arrested in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON> has tried to free him. <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON> dropped out of sight in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> several weeks ago, according to well-informed sources who asked not to be identified. One of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>'s factions is the Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, the <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> group holding foreigners hostage in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. It has said it would free the Americans they hold if <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> frees the 17 terrorists. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> has refused and the hijacking of the Kuwaiti airliner, which was taken first to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, then to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and finally to <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>, has not changed that stance. At one point during talks in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> negotiators said the hijackers offered to release half their hostages if <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> freed the three among the 17 who had been sentenced to death. <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON>'s cousin is among the three. The Cypriots, acting on Kuwaiti advice, rejected the offer. But it underlined <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON>'s suspected role in the hijacking. Western intelligence sources believe that <PERSON> Mughniyeh </PERSON> joined the hijacked Kuwaiti airliner in <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION>, northeastern <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, when it landed there after it was seized during a flight from <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>.
