roup of about 42 intruders almost constantly in view with a night-vision device, `` I did n't see a weapon on them I ca n't say why. We could see them clearly.'' He said of the shooting: `` We received the first three rounds and our -LRB- return fire -RRB- lasted about 15 minutes. What I could identify was three or four -LRB- muzzle -RRB- flashes coming from a certain area.'' `` At that time I immediately went to my machine gunner and tapped him on the shoulder and told him to return fire,'' <PERSON> Nevglovski </PERSON> said. `` He returned fire, approximately 10 or 15 rounds, and I tapped him again and told him to cease fire.'' <PERSON> Nevglovski </PERSON> said another Marine opened fire at the same time with a second machine gun, but `` none of the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> used their weapons or pistols because the word had n't been given to open fire.'' <PERSON> Nevglovski </PERSON> said that while he and about 90 other Marines were engaged with more than 40 intruders, another group of nine <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> servicemen were surrounded by `` about 10 other intruders'' on a hill half a mile away. The two groups were in radio contact, <PERSON> Nevglovski </PERSON> said, and at least three 80mm mortar rounds were fired at the intruders' positions
