<HEAD>US, Allies Try To Put Best Face On Dollar's Tumble</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs bgng, `In Europe' to UPDATE
with dollar opening lower but then stabilizing in Tokyo early
Friday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar plunged on world currency markets Thursday in reaction to bad news on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit despite a massive coordinated effort on the part of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its economic allies to halt the slide. The dollar's steep dive served served as an ominous reminder to the world's economic powers that their best-laid plans to steady the global economy can be quickly disrupted by events. Just as it had done several times last year, the weakness in the dollar quickly spread to other financial markets, sending interest rates up sharply and pushing the Dow Jones Industrial Average down by more than 100 points, its second three-digit loss this year. The market turmoil came only a day after the world's seven major industrial countries had issued a glowing communique bragging about their ability to hold the dollar stable for the past four months. Finance ministers and central bank presidents of the seven nations _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britian </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> _ reaffirmed on Wednesday their commitment to keep the dollar stable. They pledged to back up the commitment with coordinated intervention, the process by which governments dump other currencies in exchange for dollars as a way of supporting the greenback. Participants in the day-long Wednesday meeting said they had not been told in advance by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> that the February trade deficit would be an unexpectedly large $ 13.8 billion, triggering the need for intervention. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> is briefed a day in advance on government economic reports. The finance ministers professed satisfaction with the way their cooridnation effort had worked Thursday, but the dollar still closed sharply lower against other currencies. In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the dollar fell to 123.60 yen, breaking through a 125-yen barrier which has been considered the lower level for the greenback over the past four months. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Friday, the dollar opened a sharp 1.7 percent lower against the yen but stabilized later at that level on reports of heavy dollar-buying by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>. While the global recession which some predicted following last October's market collapse has not materialized, the turmoil Thursday served as an chilling reminder of the continued fragility of world economy. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and finance ministers from other countries tried to put the best face on the dollar's tumble Thursday, contending that the speed with which the countries intervened to support the dollar showed that the drive for international cooperation was working. Currency traders reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the central banks of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> were among those intervening to brake the dollar's fall. `` I think what you see today is a very good example of international cooperation because there has been concerted intervention in support of the dollar involving a very large number of countries,'' <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, the British chancellor of the exchequer, said in a briefing for reporters. The surge in the trade deficit and the dollar's tumble were among the items discussed by the world finance leaders as they continued their talks Thursday. <PERSON> Baker </PER