ar at 125 yen. After it fell below that level Thursday, West German Finance Minister <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON>, was asked whether the countries would have to accept a new level for the dollar. `` That is a very good question, a thousand-dollar question,'' he answered. The dollar turmoil also raised the possibility that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> would be forced to tighten interest rates further in this country to defend the dollar. Higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates, while slowing the American economy, are seen as a positive for the greenback because foreign investors are able to earn more on their dollar-denominated investments. <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>, head of the West German central bank, sidestepped questions about whether the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> should tighten up during a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>. With <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> looking on, <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said, `` I do n't want to comment on <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> monetary and fiscal policies.'' He said he believed that his country had done its part to stimulate world growth by lowering <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> interest rates. `` As far as -LRB- our -RRB- monetary policy is concerned, we could n't have done more. We have the lowest interest rates in the world ... and it would be irresponsible to pursue more expansionary monetary policies,'' <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said. It was a heated dispute between <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> and the West Germans last year over interest rates which has been cited as one of the contributing factors to Oct. 19 stock market plunge. Since that time, world