<HEAD>Senate Votes Aid Sanctions On Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `During more,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with Mexican foreign ministry reax</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted overwhelmingly Thursday to slap aid and trade sanctions on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for failing to do enough in the war on drugs, ignoring a plea from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and warnings that sanctions would do more harm than good. The move, on a 63 to 27 vote, came after backers of the legislation said it would shock <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> into doing more to combat the growing drug flow coming across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' southwestern border. Earlier, the lawmakers had voted voted 54 to 40 against taking the same action against the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. Similar bills were pending in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but the measures were given little chance of being finally enacted into law because of remaining procedural hurdles in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and a threat that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto any such measure to reach his desk. Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., sponsor of the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> resolution, conceded that point, but said passage in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would `` send a message to the government of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'' and added, `` We are compelled to face reality. Opponents of the anti-drug sanctions protested that both <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, while they can be faulted for shortcomings, are making good-faith efforts to halt the flow of drugs through their countries into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. And <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders, had argued that imposition of sanctions against <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> because would `` adversely affect every aspect'' of U.S.-Mexican relations. The Mexican <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> released a statement Thursday night rejecting the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote as `` foreign interference.'' `` It is a profound conviction rooted in our history and in our laws that it only falls to one's own people to define without foreign interference their institutions and that at all time only they have the inalienable right to conduct their destiny,'' the statement said. In addition, the statement said, `` No one has the right to impose from abroad conduct, ideas, political or economic systems on other peoples.'' During more than five hours of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate, several lawmakers suggested that backers of the sanctions were jeopardizing bilateral relations in response to election-year political pressure. `` It's a great opportunity to show them we're tough, show them who's boss, and that we're against drugs,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, R-R. But he noted that the <LOCATION> Bahamian </LOCATION> government has won praise from drug authorities for its cooperation. Penalizing the islands `` just does n't make much sense,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, noted that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is the third largest customer for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports and that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> gets 14 percent of its petroleum imports from its southern neighbor. `` This is likely to have a serious negative impact'' on that relationship, he said. Under a 1986 law, countries identified as production or transit points for illegal drugs must lose half their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid unless the president certifies that they are `` fully cooperating'' with the war on drugs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> made such a certification on March 1 for 17 of the 24 countries on the drug-trafficking list, including the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. After that certification, several lawmakers in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> began efforts to undo it. `` The purpose of this resolution is not to bash <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, but to defend the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, sponsor of the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> resolution along with Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, R-N. But one colleague suggested that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has little room to criticize its southern neighbor. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, R-Ariz., noted that marijuana is one of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s largest cash crops and that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> streets are unsafe because of drug-related crime `` I wonder if we should n't decertify those states'' and cut off federal aid, <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> asked. While neither the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION> nor <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> receives substantial <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic aid, losing the administration's drug certification could lead to loss of other benefits, including lucrative sugar-import quotas, airline landing rights and trade preferences. Of particular concern to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was a requirement that if certification is lost, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representatives to international development banks must vote against future loans to the affected country. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has a weighted vote on the banks, but not a majority. Loans from the banks have been crucial to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, which is laboring under a mammoth foreign debt. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> had sent private diplomatic signals that if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> persists in publicly embarrassing it through resolutions of non-cooperation, it is likely to evict <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drug agents and wage the anti-narcotics fight without outside aid, according to congressional and diplomatic sources. In other action, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved, on a voice vote, a non-binding resolution to place <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> on the list of drug producing and transit countries, subjecting it to greater scrutiny and to possible similar sanctions next year. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in his letter, said the impact of the legislation `` would almost certainly be an increase in the flow of drugs to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> had said earlier that the administration was aware of congressional concerns about the international drug trafficking problem. But he said that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s advisers were prepared to recommend that he veto any legislation imposing sanctions on <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> He said it was necessary to `` keep in mind the broader national security interests of our two countries and other interests such as trade, immigration and so forth.''
