<HEAD>Bush Upstaged by Giggling Toddlers Chanting `Jesse Jackson'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A visit by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to a government day care center turned into a pint-sized political rally when about a dozen toddlers began chanting `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'' over and over. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s name was mentioned when a reporter shouted out a question about the Democratic contender while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was winding up his visit Thursday to a day care center at the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Upon hearing <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s name, one child after another began repeating it. Soon, the entire class of about a dozen pre-schoolers was chanting `` <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'' in unison. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> grinned, then the Republican nominee-to-be responded: `` I'm not going to get into the Democratic side of the equation, particularly in a day care center. The kids were not about to let <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> off easy. `` Are you the president?'' one asked him. `` No, I'm the vice president,'' he said. `` Are you <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>?'' another asked. `` Yes, I'm <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' came the answer. He was asked if he saw the president. Yes, just that morning. `` Did you see the Easter bunny?'' he was asked. Yes, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, at the recent White House Easter egg hunt. One child asked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> if they should be afraid of him. `` I've got 10 grandchildren,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I would n't hurt a flea.''
