<FIRST>r w PM-TaxTime Bjt   04-15 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Time, Bjt,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tax Deadline Today but `Tax Freedom' Still 20 Days Away</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first return-filing season under the broadest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> income tax overhaul in history closes out at midnight. But the average American will have to work 20 more days to keep federal, state and local tax collectors at bay for another year. `` Tax Freedom Day'' will come May 5, the latest date since the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> began counting a half-century ago. If the government took every penny you earned until your share of the total tax burden were paid, the foundation reckons, you would have to work the first 126 days of 1988 just to meet those obligations. Thirty years ago, Tax Freedom Day fell on April 10. Several million Americans did n't have time to fret about such fanciful calculations. They were working up to the eleventh hour on their 1987 returns, and many were sure to be standing in line in front of mail drops as the midnight filing deadline approached. Any return not postmarked by midnight _ and carrying the correct postage _ could be subject to a late filing penalty. The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> cautioned taxpayers not to ignore the deadline, even if they ca n't afford to pay all the taxes they owe. Although failure to pay on time can result in one penalty, failure to file can bring an additional one. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> estimated that about 6.2 million couples and individuals would apply for an automatic four-month extension of the filing deadline by mailing Form 4868 with a check for their estimated taxes. That is up about 20 percent from last year _ due in large part to all the tax-law changes that must be reflected on returns being filed this year. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' 1986 overhaul of the tax law changed more than 2,700 provisions and led the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> to create 48 new forms. But the typical individual was unaffected by the great majority of those changes and has to use few if any of the new forms. Nevertheless, taxpayers have been sufficiently confused about the new law to telephone more than 17 million questions to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and to order record numbers of explanatory publications from the agency. The new law reduced tax rates significantly and nearly doubled the personal exemption to $ 1,900. But it reduced or eliminated a number of deductions and exemptions, including those for sales taxes, medical expenses, moving, consumer interest and <ORGANIZATION> Individual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retirement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounts </ORGANIZATION>. One of the biggest sources of confusion was the requirement that every employee file a revised W-4 form so that the amount of tax withheld could be adjusted to mirror the new law. Many workers found the new form so complex that the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> had to revise it again. Eventually the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> announced it would not penalize any worker for failing to pay enough tax in advance on 1987 wages. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> itself is having trouble keeping up with the new law. As recently as Thursday, it was issuing advice to taxpayers on how they might avoid penalties that were caused by getting the wrong answer to a tax question from an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> telephone `` assistor.'' About 28 of every 100 callers are getting wrong answers, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> concedes. Economists for the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> say benefits of the across-the-board tax cut enacted in 1981 have been wiped out by tax increases voted in 1982, 1983, 1984 and 1987. `` Like the <LOCATION> Cheshire </LOCATION> Cat in ` Alice in Wonderland,' nothing remains but the smile,'' the foundation said. Tax Freedom Day calculations by the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> research organization, assume that individuals pay all taxes _ including those collected from corporations. The economists simply divide all federal, state and local tax collections among taxpayers and assume that every penny earned each year goes to government until tax obligations are satisfied. Last year, Tax Freedom Day was May 4; this year's May 5 date is two days later because 1988 is a leap year. If taxes were viewed on the basis of an eight-hour work day, the foundation said, the average taxpayer would have to work 1 hour and 50 minutes a day to pay federal taxes, and another 55 minutes for state and local taxes. That's two minutes longer for federal taxes than in 1987 but the same as last year for state and local taxes.
</TEXT>
