<HEAD>PCB Contamination of People a Six-Generation Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For children born in the 22nd century, the adage `` You are what you eat'' may need to be rewritten to read: `` You are what your great-great-great grandmother ate.'' PCB contamination of people who eat tainted food is a problem than can span six generations, a researcher told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Thursday. A 20-year-old woman giving birth to a child passes on sufficient PCBs so that even if all exposure to the substance were stopped, `` I would still measure PCB in the body fat ... six generations in the future,'' said <PERSON> Wayland </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swain </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Eco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Swain </PERSON>'s figures suggest that at 30 years to a generation, children born in the year 2138 would still suffer contamination from PCBs ingested in 1988, inherited through the female line PCB production has been banned for years, but the substance, believed to cause cancer, continues to enter the environment through such sources as old electric transformers. Using earlier research into the transmission of polychlorinated biphenyls _ PCBs for short _ <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> calculated the amounts of the substance passed to an infant through nursing and retained in the infant's body. He said an infant nursed by a mother who regularly consumed <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> fish, which have been found to contain small amounts of PCBs, would be exposed to 6.2 milligrams of <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> by the end of 12 months, and 5.3 milligrams would be retained in the infant's body. `` It is clear that infants nursed by mothers who have consumed <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> fish exceed recommended consumption guidelines -LRB- for adults -RRB- for their entire breast-feeding experience,'' he told the subcommittee on investigations and oversight. The level of PCBs retained by such infants, in terms of body weight, was more than seven times the maximum consumption level recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. A mother passes PCBs to a child not only through beast feeding but through the placenta before birth, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. Infants exposed to excessive PCB levels tend to be shorter, have smaller heads, be more likely to catch infectious diseases, and exhibit an inability to focus on their surroundings, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. A recent decline in <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> levels in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> has slowed, recent research suggests, with the substance circulating from the sediment into the water and back into the sediment again in a cycle of continuing contamination of the food chain.
