<HEAD>Another Bad Trade Deficit Report Roils the Markets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, `In Tokyo ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with end of morning session in Japan.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Deficit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Dow Jones industrial average plunged more than 100 points, the dollar sank and interest rates jumped Thursday after the government announced a $ 13.8 billion trade deficit in February, the biggest since last October. The Dow Jones average of 30 stocks skidded 101.46 points to 2,005.64, a 4.8 percent decline. It was the year's second worst drop after a 140.58-point slide Jan. 8. The value of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks fell $ 99.7 billion, or 3.7 percent, according to <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monica </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The White House and most economists said the trade deficit was still improving in spite of the setback, but the markets took the news badly anyway. Most traders had convinced themselves the imbalance between imports and exports would be less than $ 12 billion, and they bailed out when the disappointing report hit at 8:30 a.m. EDT. `` There was a lot of wishing-makes-it-so -LRB- attitude -RRB-. People wanted to see a good number,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, chief economist of High Frequency Economics. He had predicted a $ 14 billion gap. The decline in the Dow triggered a ban on a form of computerized program trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. It was the first time the ban has been prompted by a decline of more than 50 points. Last week, it was triggered by an increase of more than 50 points. The Dow had climbed nearly 130 points from April 5 through Tuesday, largely on anticipation of favorable trade news. The news killed that rally as declining issues outnumbered advancing ones nearly 11 to 1 on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>. The trade deficit report also battered major foreign markets. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-stock index fell 1.3 percent. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, stocks fell sharply from their record highs at the opening of trading today but later recovered much of their losses. The key Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues, down more than 250 points at one time, finished the morning session at 26,967.83, down 143.52 from Thursday's record close. The dollar opened a sharp 1.7 percent lower against the Japanese yen but later stabilized at that level on reports of heavy dollar-buying by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> activity, the dollar had lost roughly 2 percent of its value against the yen, British pound and West German mark in spite of heavy intervention by virtually all the major central banks. Big trade deficits tend to push the dollar down by giving trading partners an oversupply of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. Interest rates leaped as pessimism swamped the bond market. The trade deficit signaled to some investors that an overly strong domestic economy was sucking in too many imports. Traders also feared a weak dollar could push up import prices, causing inflation and hurting fixed-income securities. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond recovered about halfway late in the day as stocks were sinking, but still finished with a decline of roughly $ 11 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to the price, rose to roughly 8.87 percent, a three-month high.
