<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Always interesting, the <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> was not trying for `` pretty'' with its premiere of `` Counterswarm'' at the City Center Thursday night. Consider <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s 1986 `` A Musical Offering,'' danced in caveman costumes to <PERSON> Bach </PERSON>. Or his 1985 `` Last Look,'' danced by apparently insane spastics. In `` Counterswarm,'' dancers proved they were up to <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>'s choreographed speed and athleticism Music for the 25-minute `` Counterswarm'' is from the Hungarian composer <PERSON> Gyorgy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligeti </PERSON> and contains droning and shimmering tones. The two swarms were eight dancers in purple and eight dancers in red. The purple swarm dances first, with elbows bent and close to the body and hands cupped like cobra heads. They dart their arms out and back, looking like snakes striking. One couple dances, with cupped hands together behind their backs. They strut, giving the appearance of peacocks. A couple in red enters and dances briefly, the man seeming to be subservient, lifting the woman, who maintains a regal posture. The red swarm dances about, with shoulders shrugging, looking like chickens. Suddenly the red swarm turns futuristic, arms shooting up and back like antennae on robots. The purple swarm enters doing backward sommersaults, then walks around with knees bent, arms dangling like those of monkeys. A woman in red and two men in purple dance, looking like insects. After a blackout, a short final section has everybody on stage for a not very serious war. One person in red and one in purple rush together and bump stomachs. One couple grappled arms in an unfriendly stance as the curtain fell. We do n't know what `` Counterswarm'' represented. But it did n't represent either the lyrical or humorous, more fun side, of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> The company dances at the City Center through May 1.
</TEXT>
