<FIRST>r p PM-NewYorkPolls     04-15 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New York Polls,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polls Show Dukakis Continues To Lead Among NY Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polls in the last week before the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary show <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> well ahead of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the race for the Democratic presidential nomination, and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> mired in single digits. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had the highest measure of support, at 49 percent, in an <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll released Thursday. The poll also gave <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> his highest numbers, at 34 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> led <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by 45 percent to 28 percent in a <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll and 46 percent to 34 percent in a <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> poll, also released Thursday. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> had only 8 percent support in the first two polls and 7 percent in the third. `` Certainly nothing much moved this week except for solidity to the front-runners,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> pollster <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Miringoff </PERSON>. A <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> poll last week had <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at 47 percent, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> at 31 percent and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> at 6 percent _ virtually the same results as the new <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> survey, conducted by telephone Monday and Tuesday among 359 likely Democratic voters. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' strong support went from 53 percent to 67 percent. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s became nearly unshakeable, moving from 67 percent to 82 percent strong. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s strength remained at about 40 percent despite the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator's aggressive campaign style and a television advertising budget that aides hope will reach $ 1 million. In another bad sign for <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, the Jewish voters surveyed by <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> still supported <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> overwhelmingly, despite efforts by the <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> campaign to win them over by taking a hard pro-Israel line on <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> issues. Seventy percent of the Jews in the <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> poll backed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, just 12 percent chose <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and 6 percent favored <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Jews account for up to a quarter of the Democratic primary vote in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> poll found <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with his customary overwhelming black support and support from about 16 percent of white voters. `` The number really needs to reach into the 20s in order for him to overtake <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Miringoff </PERSON> said. The polls did indicate some room for movement: 5 percent were uncommitted and 8 percent undecided in <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION>'s poll, 8 percent uncommitted and 11 percent undecided in the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> survey. The ABC-Post poll had 6 percent favoring some other candidate and 2 percent undecided. The <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> poll was conducted by telephone Monday through Wednesday among 581 likely Democratic voters and has a margin of error of 4 percentage points. The ABC-Post poll was conducted by telephone Wednesday among 176 likely voters, and has a margin of error of 9 points. The <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> poll has a margin of error of 5 percentage points.
