<HEAD>Costa Rican President Concerned about Soviet Arms Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Costa Rican President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> is urging President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to tell Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at their summit meeting that continuing Soviet weapons shipments to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> are undermining peace efforts in the region. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> rejected Soviet denials that they are supporting rebels in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and said a stable peace in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> may be beyond reach if the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> does not change its policy. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said Thursday that Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> should prepare for the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit next month by meeting with the five Central American foreign ministers, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s included. Such an encounter would end a three-year freeze on substantive diplomatic contacts between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, insisting on anonymity, said there is no prospect for a meeting along the lines proposed by <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> unless the Sandinista government demonstrates a clear will to negotiate seriously with the Contra rebels when talks on a permanent settlement are held. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> special envoy <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Busby </PERSON> sounded out leaders from four Central American countries friendly to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last week and they generally agreed the time was not ripe for a regional consultation that would include the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the officials said. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> himself had expressed that view last week and one <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official expressed surprise that the <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> leader had made the proposal Thursday without reference to the qualifications he had made in his talks with <PERSON> Busby </PERSON>. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, author of the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> peace plan, talked about his proposal during a luncheon appearance before the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION> and later discussed it with Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. At the luncheon, he was sharply critical of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Following the congressional cutoff of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the Nicaraguan rebels in February, <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> sent an open letter to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> appealing for similar Soviet restraint. He said he received a response from the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> that contained a `` lot of cynicism.'' The Soviets denied sending aid to leftist rebels in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and also said they were supporting <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist government militarily because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was supplying its allies in the region, <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said He said it is `` quite obvious'' that both <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are supporting the leftist insurgencies in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> in violation of the peace plan the five Central American president signed last August. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has accused <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> of sending weapons to leftist forces in the region but has not made the same allegation recently about the Soviets. Cuban President <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> said recently that his country provides `` political and moral support'' to the Salvadoran rebels but that there is no need to send them weapons because they are self-sufficient. <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said he decided to write to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and not to <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> because the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader would not be sending weapons to Central American insurgents without the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s consent. In his prepared remarks, <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> said the Soviets send military supplies `` worth millions'' to Central America. `` We ought to obligate the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to rectify its policy about <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and we need for it the political backing of all friendly nations,'' he said. `` The coming withdrawal of Russian troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> provides hope for the political rectification needed in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has said the Soviets sent about $ 450 million in military supplies to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> last year and that shipments over the first two months this year were above the comparable period in 1987.
