<SECOND>PM-Tax Night,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Service Preparing for Tax Onslaught</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tax Time Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dreaded income-tax deadline is here, but some folks headed for the midnight mail will also be given a chance to bash a used car, gobble headache powder, sip coffee or nibble frozen yogurt. Some communities have decided to brighten the typically somber undertaking by making it into an `` event.'' Those frustrated by the new tax forms, for example, may want to do their mailing in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, Ark. Radio station KZOU-FM will broadcast from a parking lot where the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has set up a special mail box, to be collected at midnight. The station will offer last-minute taxpayers a chance to vent their feelings by taking a sledgehammer to a used car. A small charge for taking part will be used for charity. Things will be a little more festive in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has set up special collection points at shopping centers. Frozen yogurt bars will be offered to taxpayers by radio station KOOL-FM, while at another location KESZ-FM will give out fast food coupons, said postal service spokeswoman <PERSON> Margot </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>. Tax night in her city has become `` quite an event,'' she remarked. The nation's capital is n't exempt, either, with the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for the Performing Arts joining in. The Center is using the rite of last-minute tax filing to promote the performance of `` The Rite of Spring.'' A postal clerk will set up shop at the Center from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. for patrons of the arts to buy stamps and mail their taxes en route to their dose of culture. For Arkansans who have been too busy completing their taxes to consider going to a concert, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> radio station KSSN-FM is setting up a `` tax aid'' station to give out coffee, donuts and headache powders at the general mail facility there, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reports. Those who prefer Alka-Seltzer with their coffee, donuts and taxes can head north to <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, where station <ORGANIZATION> WIBA </ORGANIZATION> will offer succor to the late filers. Postal Service consumer advocate <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said she could n't be specific about the last day, but that the post office expects to handle 30 million tax returns nationwide in the `` last couple of days.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> reminded taxpayers to use the correct postage _ under this month's rate hike, it now costs a quarter for the first ounce and 20 cents for each added ounce. She also encouraged use of the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> envelopes because they make the mail easier for postal workers to handle. Taxpayers seeking last-minute postmarks annually flock to post offices, and service until midnight will be available in many communities to accommodate them, she reported. Indeed, streetcorner collection for people driving by will be available in dozens of cities. In <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, the move this year is to decentralize the postal rush. `` Traditionally we have quite a bit of congestion at the main office on that night, so we're trying to solve that,'' explained spokeswoman <ORGANIZATION> Gloria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cheek </ORGANIZATION>. Special pickups have been scheduled for mail deposit boxes in front of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>'s 33 postal stations. That mail will be collected at 11:30 p.m., and postmarked April 15, she said. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> WCXR </ORGANIZATION> is offering contest winners free stamps and a limousine ride to the post office. Volunteer or government tax preparers will be on hand to help late filers in many locations including <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Postal workers will collect tax returns from motorists at all four corners of the <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> main post office and a clerk will be stationed inside to weigh items and sell stamps until midnight. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, the Terminal Annex and Worldway Postal centers will be open until midnight, and a hotline to the main post office will give information on other late collection points in <LOCATION> Van </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nuys </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. An Express Mail van manned with two clerks will be parked in front of the Denver Main post office to collect tax forms until midnight. And in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, two-ton collection trucks will loom at three locations around the main post office.
