<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     04-15 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>House, Senate Will Spar Over `Creative Accounting' In Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passage of a $ 1.1 trillion fiscal 1989 budget sets up a battle with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> over domestic spending and how far <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can stray from its deficit-reduction pact with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. This year's budget debate is framed by the bipartisan agreement with the president, which sets out limits for taxes and major spending categories. Both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have now passed budgets obeying the pact's spending caps of $ 294 billion for the military and $ 16.1 billion in foreign aid. And neither chamber included tax increases beyond the $ 14 billion enacted last December. So when the two sides begin meeting next week to resolve their differences, the focus will be on domestic programs. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan, approved Thursday by a 69-26 vote, is similar to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan in supporting large increases in spending on AIDS research, education, and aviation safety. Both also reject <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s request to terminate several domestic programs But the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan is closer to the president's in several areas. It contains sharp increases for the space program and science. The House last month opted for more modest boosts in those areas in order to better protect mass transit, housing and development programs. Both plans fudge the numbers in order to claim they stay within the domestic spending limits, but they do it in different ways. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted to use what <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., called `` creative accounting'' _ simply declaring that some expenses were not covered by the agreement The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, eager to make room for a new $ 2.6 billion anti-drug program but unwilling to make cuts elsewhere in the budget, at the last minute set up a special fund. Declaring the money would n't be tapped unless a `` dire emergency'' were declared, the budget simply does n't count that spending yet. Still, budget leaders from the two chambers said they hoped to reach agreement quickly. `` There are obvious differences,'' <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, D-Pa., said in a written statement `` With good will, I am sure these differences can be resolved.'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said the talks between the two chambers would begin next week and, he hoped, go quickly. But Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the senior Republican on the budget committee, said, `` It is a more formidable challenge than I thought it would be'' in the wake of the deficit agreement. The budget is a congressional resolution which does not require the president's signature, but it guides lawmakers as they pass their annual fiscal legislation. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has a self-imposed deadline of April 15 for finishing the budget. It has failed to meet the deadline again, but things are closer to being resolved at this date than they have been in recent years. There was no expression of concern in either the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> about the tardiness. While millions of taxpayers must file their returns by midnight tonight or face a penalty, there's no punishment for the lawmakers if they do n't figure out on time how to spend the tax dollars. Those tax dollars still do n't cover government expenses in either the administration's or <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' budgets. But they all claim to meet the $ 136 billion deficit target of the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., said even those deficit numbers were based on too-optimistic White House estimates of a growing economy `` The wreckage of our fiscal policy will haunt the next president and presidents to come,'' he said.
</TEXT>
