<HEAD>Judge Stays Enforcement of Allegedly Cumbersome, Costly Devices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shrimpers nationwide have been granted a reprieve from federal regulations requiring them to outfit their vessels with devices to exclude turtles from their nets. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> told the government Tuesday to stop enforcing the regulations until the 5th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rules on a lawsuit filed by the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> attorney general's office and Concerned Shrimpers of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. Shrimpers contend the devices are expensive, cumbersome, and would drastically cut the size of their catch. Environmentalists say they are necessary to protect endangered and threatened species of turtles. <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> upheld the regulations as lawful in a Feb. 29 ruling but decided this week to prohibit enforcement while his earlier ruling is appealed. `` We're pleased that Judge <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> agreed with the state's argument that little harm, if any, would be done to sea turtles if shrimpers continue to trawl without TEDs -LRB- turtle excluder devices -RRB- until the case is finally adjudicated,'' <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Guste </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said on learning of the ruling Thursday. `` We argued that shrimpers would have to go to great trouble and expense to equip their nets with TEDs,'' he said. `` The possibility remains that the appeals court will reverse <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>'s -LRB- earlier -RRB- ruling and not require shrimpers to use TEDs.'' <PERSON> Guste </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> shrimpers could lose up to 15 percent of their catches if they have to use the devices, meaning less tax revenue for the state. In his order this week, <PERSON> Carr </PERSON> said shrimpers have had trouble obtaining the TEDs and getting adequate training in their use. `` We still maintain the regulations are valid and lawful and necessary to protect turtles,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` We're preparing the papers to seek a cancellation of his order and an expedited ruling from the court of appeals.'' <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> drafted the regulations to protect endangered and threatened turtles, most notably the `` critically endangered'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s ridley sea turtle, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` I'm thrilled with Judge <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>'s ruling. This is the first major victory in the shrimpers' battle to stop TED regulations, and it is important recognition that the TED regulations are impractical,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> and the environmentalists will probably ask that the court of appeals to overturn this decision, but I believe that the evidence is overwhelming that shrimper compliance is impossible,'' said <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> was phasing in the regulations depending on location _ they took effect March 1 along the <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION>, on Jan. 1 in <LOCATION> southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> near the Keys, and in October near <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. The regulations were to take effect for the rest of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast May 1. `` We know they do n't work,'' Tee <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mialjevich </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, president and executive director of Concerned Shrimpers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, said of the TEDs. More than 100 shrimping vessels converged on the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION> in February to protest the regulations, <PERSON> Mialjevich </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Megginson </PERSON>, an assistant state attorney general in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, said the devices would create enormous problems for shrimpers and the state, which would have to help enforce the law. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> has 32,000 commercial and recreational shrimpers, and there were n't enough of the devices on the market to go around, she said.
