<FIRST>r a PM-DonorDilemma     04-15 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Donor Dilemma,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Discuss Ethics of Harvesting Donor Organs from Doomed
Infants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The immediate harvesting of organs from infants born with most of their brains missing could threaten entire groups of patients who have lost the capacity for thought, two medical ethicists say. Such a policy of taking the organs for transplant before the infants are declared brain dead also violates medical ethics, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Arras </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Shlomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON>, writing in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Because these infants, called anencephalic, inevitably die within days or weeks and many children require organ transplants, a debate has begun over the appropriateness of using anencephalics as donors _ and how soon. `` These arguments are by no means unique to anencephalic newborns,'' <LOCATION> Arras </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> wrote in their commentary. `` They are equally applicable to other severely damaged infants as well as adults in permanent vegetative states. We do not believe society is willing to harvest organs from living patients who have permanently lost the capacity for intelligent thought.'' Anencephalic infants have a brain stem, enabling them to breathe. They have no cerebral cortex, the part of the brain allowing thought and voluntary movement. Between 2,000 and 3,000 anencephalic infants are among the 3 million children born in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> estimates. `` Organ donation is very laudable, and people say these kids will inevitably die,'' Shinnar, a pediatric neurologist at <ORGANIZATION> Montefiore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> Albert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But he added, `` What if there are not enough anencephalics and the transplant needs are greater two years from now? Who do we look at next?'' The debate intensified in October following newspaper reports that organs had been harvested from anencephalic infants and transplanted into other children in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` In the West German case, they took a baby from delivery, put a tube -LRB- of oxygen -RRB- in its mouth, took it to the operating room, harvested the organs and buried it,'' <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said. `` And in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, although it did not pass, there was a bill in the legislature in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to have these children declared ` brain-dead' at birth,'' he said. Legal definitions of brain death used in making medical determinations require an end of all brain functions, including those of the brain stem, <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said. In December, the <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> developed a medical protocol under which anencephalic babies are to be used for transplants only after brain death occurs. Six anencephalic infants were kept alive by respirator for a week under those guidelines, though none ultimately became an organ donor, said <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON>. `` We wrote our article before the protocol was developed,'' <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said, `` and this certainly lessens the magnitude of the ethical debate.'' But, he said, `` this protocol is not without its problems as well. What about extending the tragedy for the parents of an anencephalic child?'' Anencephaly can be detected before birth with ultrasound, the commentary said, and some doctors consider abortion appropriate as late as the final three months of pregnancy. `` Should we be encouraging pregnant women, in essence, to carry these children to term to provide spare parts?'' <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
