<HEAD>Afghans in Camps Greet Accord with Skepticism, Indifference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for item listed as PM-Afghan-World Reax on digest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There was no signs of celebration in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>'s hot and dusty streets, no shots fired into the air as people do in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> when they are happy about something. The Soviets had just signed the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s ticket home from neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, but the prevailing mood among Afghan refugees encamped here for years was skepticism and indifference. <PERSON> Tanvir </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>, a taxi driver, said: `` Agreement? What agreement? ... It will make no difference. The war will end when the refugees go home.'' In Camp No. 6 of the nearby border town of <LOCATION> Munda </LOCATION> sat 34-year-old <PERSON> Israyal </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghairad </PERSON>, a school teacher from <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION> province in northeastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> `` We're not concerned with this agreement,'' <PERSON> Ghairad </PERSON> said of the accords signed Thursday in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. The Afghan Moslem guerrillas were not invited to the negotiations that produced the withdrawal settlement. The accord was signed by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ghairad </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> are not `` the real parties to this war.'' The Afghan rebels say the conflict is with the Soviets and not the government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the Afghan capital, which they consider a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> puppet. The guerrillas say no agreement is valid without their participation. The seven-party guerrilla alliance did not issue a statement after the signing Thursday, but said a resolution would be read Saturday at a public rally outside <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, the Pakistani border city that serves as its headquarters. The statement is expected to repeat the guerrillas' position that they will continue fighting until the last Soviet soldier leaves Afghan soil. The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement calls for the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops who began arriving in 1979 to begin leaving May 15 and be out within nine months. <PERSON> Ghairad </PERSON> said: `` We will wait and see if there is entire peace in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the Communists are no longer in power.'' He said his family of five will not return home until he feels it is safe there, and predicted the 5 million other Afghan refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would do the same. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Land </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees representative in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, said it was too early to prepare for a return home by the refugees. Countries in both the East and West hailed the troop withdrawal accord as a vital first step toward peace, and some offered to help Afghan refugees. But skepticism remained over some aspects of the agreement, particularly continued aid to combatants. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION>, an independent English-language daily, said in an editorial titled `` Meaningless Agreement'': `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will be able to withdraw its troops without having to acknowledge the plain fact that it has failed to pacify <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in the face of resistance by U.S.-backed mujahedeen -LRB- guerrillas -RRB-. But on the face of it, the agreement will be pretty meaningless otherwise. `` For it will stipulate that the Americans and the Russians will continue to be entitled to provide arms to their respective clients. And while <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will formally agree not to interfere in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s internal affairs, it will in reality continue to do so inasmuch as it will still serve as a conduit for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms supplies to the mujahedeen.''
