<HEAD>Early Results Show 0.3 Percent of Hospital Patients AIDS-Infected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three patients in 1,000 were infected with the AIDS virus, according to anonymous blood tests at four Midwestern hospitals, but researchers say that rate of infection does n't necessarily apply to the nation The national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, attempting to gauge the prevalence of AIDS infection of the virus that causes AIDS, tested blind blood samples from non-AIDS patients at 40 `` sentinel'' hospitals in 30 cities. In results from the first four hospitals enrolled in the program, all in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 0.3 percent of the 12,000 tested patients showed signs of AIDS virus infection, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said in a report made public Thursday. The early data, however, may not be representative of the nation, said Dr. <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON>, a CDC AIDS researcher. `` You ca n't do a national estimate based on four spots,'' he said. Federal health officials continue to estimate that between 1 million and 1.5 million Americans are infected with AIDS virus. `` No new data have become available to prompt a change of this estimate,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said, adding, `` accurate estimates of the prevalence ... of -LRB- AIDS virus -RRB- infection in the entire <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> population are not possible at this time.'' The agency expects to enroll all 40 hospitals in its testing program by September. If 1.5 million of the nation's estimated 240 million population were infected, the rate would be about 0.6 percent, about twice as high as the early <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> results. One million Americans would be about 0.4 percent. The four hospitals reported that antibodies indicating AIDS infection were more common among adults 25 to 44. Rates also were higher for blacks and Hispanics than for whites, and higher for men than for women, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. Those rates are comparable to national AIDS statistics, <PERSON> Dondero </PERSON> noted, adding, `` The data look right.'' As of this week, 59,287 cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome itself have been reported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. The disease has so far killed 33,060, or 56 percent of those patients. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>'s report summarized the agency quarterly presentation on AIDS to the Domestic Policy Council last month. The report also reviewed tests among prisoners and among childbearing women. Out of 29,193 federal inmates tested by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION> since last June, 843, or 2.9 percent, have tested positive for AIDS virus infection. That is little changed from a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announcement last fall, when 3 percent of the first inmates tested were positive. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said it hopes to contract with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> and with a `` major university'' for AIDS testing of 10,000 inmates at 10 state prisons beginning this June. In 52,326 tests of childbearing women in the state of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, researchers found an AIDS virus infection rate of 0.8 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, one woman in 61 showed antibodies against the AIDS virus, and 40 percent of those women passed the infections on to their newborn children, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> added.
