<HEAD>Inmate Who Escaped from Death Row Is Executed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> had pleaded for his life and even escaped once from death row, but in the end he walked wide-eyed and silent to his death in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s electric chair for the 1980 killing of a librarian. Rebuffed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> after his lawyers made a frantic plea, <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON>, 33, was administered two jolts of electricity late Thursday night and pronounced dead at 11:07 p.m. Outside the prison, about 50 opponents of capital punishment conducted a vigil and prayer service. They were interrupted by a single supporter of the death penalty who shouted, `` Pray for the woman that died.'' <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> had been on death row since 1981 for the robbery and strangling of <PERSON> Wilhemina </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> school librarian who lived in his apartment building. On Tuesday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> granted <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> a stay to review evidence of childhood abuse that the condemned man said he suffered. Attorneys for <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> said he had suppressed memories of the abuse and thus was incompetent to help his trial lawyer in offering mitigating evidence at the sentencing hearing. A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> overturned <PERSON> Merhige </PERSON> on Thursday afternoon, prompting a hurried effort by <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON>'s lawyers to stop the execution. The federal appeals court said that <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON>'s case had been given least 10 reviews in state and federal courts and that his sentencing had been found constitutional. On Thursday night, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused a stay in a 7-2 decision, with Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> dissenting, and Gov. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> turned down a petition for clemency. <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> was visited by his mother, sister, two aunts and his lawyers as the execution hour approached, said <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, the prison's operations officer. He also was visited by <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, the 1960s child television star of `` <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> the Menace.'' North has been working on a movie about the 1984 escape of <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> and five other <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> death row inmates. `` We became extremely close friends,'' said <PERSON> North </PERSON>, who opposes the death penalty. `` We've been in contant communication, wrote and called. We became like brothers.'' Witnesses to the execution said <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> was wide-eyed and impassive and appeared only a little nervous as he was led into the death chamber. In an interview Monday with the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> Virginian-Pilot and The Ledger-Star, <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> complained about pressure being exerted by the state to have him executed at the scheduled time. `` Why kill me today and be wrong in just a few months later?'' he said. `` What is the urgency? Why such an urgency to take such a life.'' In May 1984, <PERSON> Clanton </PERSON> was one of six death row inmates who escaped from the <ORGANIZATION> Mecklenburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. He was recaptured the next day at a coin laundry in <LOCATION> Warrenton </LOCATI