<HEAD>Simon Says It's Time to Slow Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 40 years as one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most successful playwrights, <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> says he's thinking about taking things a little easier. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, 60, was just 31 when his first play, `` Come Blow Your Horn,'' opened on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. Prior to that, he was a television reporter for 10 years. `` That's 40 years of writing,'' he said in a recent interview. `` I do n't anticipate grazing on a farm someplace, but this pace I do n't need anymore. `` Maybe I'll just write plays for regional theaters an not think about going to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. Maybe I'll stop in a couple of years and just do watercolors. I do n't know. I ca n't think beyond these two plays. I only think in the present,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, who has had 22 plays on Broadway. The two plays that are currently occupying his thoughts are numbers 23 and 24. His 23rd Broadway production is `` <PERSON> Jake </PERSON>'s Women,'' which is already finished. The story of a writer and the ladies in his life is scheduled to open in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> next year. Number 24 is a farce he is rewriting called `` Rumors,'' scheduled to make its world premiere at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>'s Old Globe Theatre in September before becoming his 24th play for the Broadway stage. `` There's nothing safe in ` Rumors,''' he said. `` It's a farce _ a style of comedy I've never written before. It's the most complicated thing I've ever written ... I doubt if I'll ever do another farce, because it's exhausting.''
