<HEAD>Workers Going Hungry Waiting For Berry-Picking Season to Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As many as 25,000 migrant workers have arrived in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> more than a month before the strawberry crop is ready to pick, and thousands are without food or shelter, relief agencies say. Last year, there were n't enough workers to pick an early harvest of strawberries, and 20 percent of the state's crop rotted in the fields. Growers complained that Mexican pickers were confused over the Immigration Reform Act of 1986 and refused to cross the border. This year, social service agencies are stretching to help an estimated 18,000 to 25,000 early arrivals. `` Word got out that there were a lot of jobs and everybody was afraid there would be such a rush that when they showed up it would be too late,'' said <PERSON> Titus </PERSON> <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Marta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, who operates the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zion </ORGANIZATION> emergency shelter in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said she often sees 50 or 60 people living in one room when they deliver food to migrant camps. `` We have people in the backyard in tents. We even have people staying in the camper of our pickup because there's no place else to go,'' she said. `` Everywhere you see that. They have no water, no facilities. Many come here to take baths.'' A <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> grower who asked not to be identified said many workers are asking farmers to sign papers saying they worked for them at least 90 days each year from 1984 to 1986, as required by the new law. `` A lot of them ca n't get legalized, but hope people will fill out the forms for them,'' he said. The illegal workers are `` just hoping and praying they wo n't get asked for papers, that farmers will be lenient toward them,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. `` We bring