<HEAD>World's Largest Toad Dies of `Biological Accident'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 5-pound, 1 -LCB- - ounce South American toad recognized as the world's largest has died apparently of old age, but zoo officials said they're not sure just how old she was `` She was not obese, just a very healthy specimen,'' <ORGANIZATION> Blank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said Thursday of Toad A, known as `` Toad'' to her keepers. Terming the death a `` biological accident,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said pathology tests are being conducted on Toad A to confirm the cause of her April 8 death. Toad A, stretching to 9 -LCB- inches, was accepted late last year into the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> as the largest toad on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> animal dealer sold the South American toad to the zoo in 1983. At that time she was estimated to be 2 years old, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said, but zoo keepers believe she may have been older than 8 when she died. `` Toad's notoriety was an attraction for the zoo and we're very disappointed at the loss,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` A lot of people planned on seeing <LOCATION> Toad </LOCATION> on exhibit at the zoo this summer.'' Many may still get a chance. Toad A might be freeze-dried so she can be displayed, zoo officials said.
