<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0893,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Mail,' A New Musical, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS four grafs with other critics; No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Mail'' is a little musical out of place on a big Broadway stage. The show, which opened Thursday at the Music Box Theater, examines the anxieties of a sensitive, 29-year-old, would-be novelist named <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> who is having a mid-life crisis 10 years too soon. Not exactly a novel idea for a musical, but for much of the time, the evening is fun in an obvious, good-natured sort of way. Seekers of <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON> significance and solemnity should look elsewhere. The problem with `` Mail'' is that the production relies on a gimmick to keep the story going, and that gimmick falters during the second act, no matter how busy director <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardiff </PERSON> keeps his actors and set designers. The hook, created by author <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Colker </PERSON>, is simple. An angst-ridden <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> -RRB- disappears for four months, and when he returns to his dingy <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> apartment, there is a pile of mail to open. When he does, the letters leap to life. So does the complicated set, designed by <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hariton </PERSON> and <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Baral </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON>'s letter writers jump out from behind doors, walls and windows and pop out of the desk and bathtub. One even makes an entrance through the refrigerator. There's his bewildered girlfriend <PERSON> Dana </PERSON>, dumped just when she and <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> were going to get married, and <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alex </PERSON>'s best friend, an idealist turned entrepreneur. Other correspondents include <PERSON> Alex </PERSON>'s gruff, obnoxious father who wants his son to come back to the carburetor business in <LOCATION> Mineola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, and the writer's vixenish literary agent who wants to get her client into bed before she gets him on the best-seller list. Their increasingly frantic missives are interrupted by overdue bills, junk mail, high school reunion letters and even sweepstakes announcements that sing and dance. These interludes are among the best in the show. It's hard not to laugh when a contingent of <ORGANIZATION> Con </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> workers, dressed in hard hats, T-shirts and short pants, bully <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> in time to a disco ditty called `` We're Gon na Turn Off Your Juice.'' <PERSON> Colker </PERSON> also wrote the lyrics for `` Mail,'' and <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> supplied the music. With this large score _ nearly 30 numbers in all _ the duo makes good on the promise they demonstrated in `` 3 Guys Naked From the Waist Down,'' an off-beat contemporary musical about the world of stand-up comics. <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON>'s music for `` Mail'' is eclectic, ranging from pop to soul to ragtime to country-western. The songs have a brash Broadway sound, the result of <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>'s first-rate orchestrations. At least one number, a lament by the rejected girlfriend entitled, `` It's Getting Harder to Love You,'' would seem to have potential for a life outside of the show. <PERSON> Colker </PERSON>'s amusing lyrics are more enticing than his slender story. The tale starts to evaporate at the beginning of Act 2 when <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> has a momentous revelation. He decides to see others as they see him. That decision forces the letter writers to recapitulate their feelings about our hero. It's only a matter of time before <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> neatly resolves his problems with each of them and with himself. Fortunately, the show has been blessed with a fine cast. <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> is a consumate, hard-working musical comedy performer and he makes <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> an ingratiating character we can care about. <PERSON> Mara </PERSON> <PERSON> Getz </PERSON> as the lovesick <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> possesses the show's best voice while <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, the opportunistic best friend, struts and swings with style. Only <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandan </PERSON> as the insensitive father with problems of his own seems uncomfortable in the musical. The show always seems to be in motion, even when the story is n't. Most of the recent Broadway musicals move, but they do n't dance <PERSON> Grover </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> has come up with some snappy if abbreviated dance routines recalling a style of musical comedy choreography that has gone out of fashion. `` Mail'' makes for a reasonably diverting entertainment, especially if you do n't think too hard about the well-worn message it delivers. In other reviews: <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissel </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> writes: `` This is a revue sketch idea that might have been amusing for 12 minutes. ... the music is as facile and vapid as the characters who sing it. ... `` But maybe someone should point out to young American writers that the world has many more appealing subjects than their not very interesting lives.'' In The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> asks: `` Is it possible that ` Mail' is a surreptitious advertisement for Federal Express?''
</TEXT>
