<HEAD>Mexico Rejects Senate Vote on Drug Certification</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Mexican government rejected as meddling in its domestic affairs a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote revoking President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s certification that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was doing its part to combat drug trafficking. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a resolution Thursday that also would slap trade and economic aid sanctions against <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. But the measure stands little chance of passage in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> and is almost certain to be vetoed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In a brief statement Thursday night, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> rejected the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action as `` foreign interference'' in <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> affairs. `` No power can claim for itself the right to certify the conduct of other societies or governments. No one has the right to impose from abroad conduct, ideas, political or economic systems on other peoples,'' the statement said. Under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> would stand to lose American support in international lending institutions for new loans to the country if the resolution became binding. The federal attorney general's office, which is responsible for overseeing <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s narcotics efforts to find and destroy drugs, issued its own strongly-worded statement late Thursday night insisting that `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is undertaking a plain effort of international cooperation in the campaign against drug trafficking.'' It expressed `` profound astonishment and its great displeasure with the resolution taken by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, in that -LRB- the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- does not recognize the enormous effort of the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> people to combat a problem whose causes are not, certainly, attributable to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.'' The statement cited `` the vast consumer market'' for drugs, in a clear reference to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> demand, as sustaining the illicit narcotics trade. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> receives little economic aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. But officials here are concerned about a requirement under 1986 law that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representatives in multilateral lending institutions must vote against future loans to countries whose certification is revoked. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has a $ 105 billion foreign debt, and depends heavily on its relationship with foreign lenders. Officials point out that about one-quarter of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s 100,000-member armed forces is permanently assigned to narcotics interdiction and eradication operations Mexican officials also have insisted they could use more financial assistance from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in fighting drugs. As recently as 1986, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> anti-drug assistance to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was about half that provided for eliminating the screwworm in Mexican cattle. More than 100 army troops and federal judicial policemen have been killed over the past 10 years during drug operations, according to Mexican army figures. Relations between the two countries have been soured by mutual accusations surrounding the Feb. 7, 1985 kidnapping of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> agent <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON>. The bodies of <PERSON> Camarena </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Zavala </PERSON> <PERSON> Avelar </PERSON>, a Mexican pilot who worked with him in anti-narcotics programs from their base in <LOCATION> Guadalajara </LOCATION>, were found on March 5, 1985. American officials charged that Mexican authorities were slow in seeking out and arresting several drug barons who allegedly ordered the killings. Attorney General <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> has called for an end to mutual recriminations between <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over their contributions to the fight against the drug trade. `` We find it difficult to accept the opinion held in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of what really goes on in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said. `` The border is not a border between black and white, good and evil. It is a border between countries.''
