<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Says Goodbye To Anti-Drug Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> made her last appearance as first lady before an anti-drug group's conference, telling students, youth leaders and teachers she will be with them `` in spirit'' after her husband leaves office in January. `` These past eight years of work against drugs have brought new meaning to my life, and I will not abandon what we are accomplishing,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Thursday in remarks to the PRIDE International Conference on Youth and Drugs. Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, making her fifth annual appearence, drew frequent cheers from the crowd of 3,000 amid a pep-rally atmosphere. The conference was the 11th sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>. The first lady told the young people that they pose `` a threat to the dealers and the traffickers ... a danger to the drug attitudes that have ruled this country for the past two decades.'' `` It's the young people who will solve the drug crisis in this country,'' she said. `` We could have parents following their children's every move. We could have drug agents on every corner, treatment centers on every block, jails in every neighborhood, and still there would be a demand for drugs. `` What will win the battle against drugs is a change in attitudes, and that's exactly what you're accomplishing,'' she said. `` While I wo n't be able to come here every year as I have in the past, I'll be with you in spirit.'' Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> also spoke to the group Thursday.
