<HEAD>Highest Court Turns Down ``Birmingham Six'' Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Six Irishmen serving life sentences for the worst terrorist attack in modern British history failed to win permission to appeal their convictions before <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s highest court. The defendants, known as the <ORGANIZATION> Birmingham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Six </ORGANIZATION>, claimed they were beaten into confessing and were wrongly convicted on faulty forensic evidence for two <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> pub bombings that killed 21 people and injured 162 in the central <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> in 1974. The three Law Lords of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION>, members of the unelected upper legislative chamber who have expertise as judges, rejected the men's bid to challenge their murder convictions Thursday. They did not give reasons for their decision. The men's only option now would be to take their case to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. `` At some stage a future Home Secretary is going to have to deal with the ongoing injustice to these men,'' said <PERSON> Gareth </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, a lawyer for the six. The Home Secretary is the Cabinet minister responsible for the administration of law and order. `` They simply ca n't spend the rest of their lives in prison when they have committed no offense,'' <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> said. The men were not present at the 90-minute preliminary hearing at which the Law Lords were deciding whether to hear the case in full. In January, after a five-week court battle, the Court of Appeal upheld their convictions and sent them back to prison. The Irish government believes the six may have been convicted wrongly. The failure of the appeal in January contributed to a severe strain in Anglo-Irish relations. The bombs exploded minutes apart at two pubs in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> on Nov. 21, 1974. Within hours, the six were rounded up among dozens of suspects. Four signed confessions and two were said to have made verbal admissions. In 1975, a court imposed multiple life sentences on <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Callaghan </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> McIlkenny </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Power </PERSON>. Three of the men are in their 50s and three in their 40s. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>, fighting British rule in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, claimed responsibility for the bombings but said none of the six was involved. The almost exclusively <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> wants to join the Protestant-dominated province and set up an all-Ireland socialist state.
