<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinista, Contra Commissions End Technical Talks, Report
Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sandinista and Contra commissions charged with defining <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s cease-fire finished talks early today with both sides reporting progress. High-level government and rebel leaders, meanwhile, planned to meet later today in the capital of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> for the first time to further negotiations toward lasting peace. The Sandinista and Contra commissions, meeting in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> on the Costa Rican border, said they achieved `` considerable progress'' and `` reconciled differences of the earlier meeting,'' according to an official statement issued by both sides. They remaining differences were not known, but both sides said they would take them up in the high-level meeting today. The two sides held six technical meetings since March 28 and managed only to agree on seven zones in which the Contra combatants are to gather. They failed to define operating conditions within the areas affecting security and resupply. The zones and the technical talks were outlined in the March 23 cease-fire pact signed by the Soviet-supplied <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> and the U.S.-backed Contras after three days of unprecedented direct negotiations at the <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> border post, 90 miles south of the capital. The goal is to end more than six years of war that have killed more than 40,000 Nicaraguans. The commissions were defining the mechanics of the cease-fire, which formally went into effect April 1. Under the plan, the Contra evacuation into the zones was to have been completed by today. In return, the Sandinistas were to have released 700 political prisoners, allowed humanitarian aid for the rebels and permitted the insurgents to send representatives to take part in internal political discussions. Two points contained in a <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> proposal had been termed `` non-negotiable'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. It would allow the combatants to receive replacements of arms and ammunition inside the zones while prohibiting the government from accepting military aid, which comes from the Soviet bloc. The cease-fire pact allows only humanitarian aid to be distributed by a neutral organization to the rebels. It does not mention government supplies. The Contra delegation was to be headed by its Miami-based directorate, made up of <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aristides </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON>, <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Azucena </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>. The government's delegation is headed by the nation's highest military leader, Gen. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the brother of President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>. Agreement is needed on a new deadline for the Contras to gather into zones and for the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> to make their concessions, such as the prisoner release. The pact now calls for a 60-day cease-fire, which ends June 1. The Sandinistas and Contras still stand far apart on the issue of laying down weapons, which is not mentioned in the cease-fire plan. They do agree the rebel combatants can enter the zones with their weapons. The Contras argue that they will never put down their arms until <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is `` on the irreversible road to democracy.'' The Sandinistas contend that disarmament must occur before reintegration into civilian life.
