<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and three other grim-faced diplomats who signed the Afghan accords studiously avoided the word `` peace'' to describe what they had achieved. The tragic reality behind what <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> called a historic agreement is that the killing will go on in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, as it did in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> for two years after <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> put his signature on a similar accord in 1973. Yes, the Soviets pledged to remove their 115,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15, 1989. Yes, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and the signing ceremony in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> talking about worldwide efforts to help Afghan refugees return to villages no longer threatened by Soviet napalm and helicopter gunships. Yes, the agreement signed Thursday by the foreign ministers of the government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> opens the way for what <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> called `` Afghan control over <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' Although the Soviets have not stated their intentions publicly, the sad expectation is that that the Soviets will continue to arm the Afghan government they have backed for a decade and the Afghan mujahadeen supported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will continue receiving weapons from a <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> pipeline. Today, however, a high administration official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> still hopes that the Soviets may elect to end shipments to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and let that long war wind down. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> tried to get the Soviets to agree to a mutual cutoff of weaponry, but that effort failed so it is likely the Afghan rivals will continue receiving the means to kill each others' adherents. The accords signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> do not end the war; they merely begin the end to Soviet troop participation in it. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> acknowledged the agreement was `` not perfect.'' But he and officials who traveled with him to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> were clearly satisfied with what had been accomplished. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, its allies, the Islamic world and most of the rest of the world have been railing against the Soviets for more than eight years for sending troops to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. To bring that withdrawal about, after the loss of an estimated million Afghan lives, was a major victory, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, prompting him to proclaim, `` History has been made today.'' The agreement also will permit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to step back a bit from deep involvement in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> affairs, the officials said. After all, before the Soviets turned <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> into a superpower sore point, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had little interest in the incessant warfare within Afghan's tribal society. The Soviet decision to withdraw could lead to the restoration of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to that shelf of countries the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> need not worry about and the officials seemed pleased at that prospect. There was a touch of irony to the signing ceremony in that it took place in the same chamber where the superpowers blessed a 1955 <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> accord that eventually failed. The parallels between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in the 1980s and <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, particularly in the 1970s, are inescapable. A superpower bogged down in an unpopular war at home and abroad, realizing its superior firepower can not defeat a tenacious guerrilla force armed by another superpower, signs an agreement permitting disengagement `` with honor.'' In 1973, Secretary of State <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> set the stage in the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> accords for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troop withdrawal, turning the struggle over to the well-stocked South Vietnamese. By April 1975, the North Vietnamese had won. On Thursday, Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, who signed the troop withdrawal pledge, said supplies to the `` legitimate'' government of <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> would continue. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, sounding vaguely like the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials of the 1970s, tried to put the best face on what had happened. How will Soviet generals swallow their defeat, he was asked at a news conference? `` Soviet generals do n't think they lost the war,'' he replied. He feigned ignorance of a well-publicized Soviet academician's assertion that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s initial decision in 1979 to send in the troops was a mistake The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> went into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to help a besieged, legitimate government, he said. Behind the gloss, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said, was a clear Soviet determination to end its involvement _ a determination unthreatened by last-minute finagling over the continuation of superpower assistance. Asked if <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s condemnation of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistance for the rebels could unravel the agreement, one official laughed and declared: `` They are n't looking for a pretext to stay.'' The accepted wisdom at the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has the <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> government collapsing eventually because it has little support among Afghans. Yet there is no consensus in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on how soon that could happen. The most graceful transition to peace could come about through a further mediation effort by <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> official who led the negotiations that resulted in Thursday's accord <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> has agreed to begin talks with the factions on creating an interim government to supplant the Marxist <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> regime. In the meantime, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and his enemies, the mujahadeen, vow to continue the struggle and the killing will continue.
</TEXT>
