<HEAD>Passports Required for Crossing Green Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Turkish Cypriot administration said Friday it has started requiring Cypriots to carry passports if they cross the Green Line that divides this Mediterranean island. The new requirement became known when opposition <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turkish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Ozker </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozgur </PERSON> was turned back from the checkpoint Thursday by Turkish Cypriot officials for not carrying a passport. <PERSON> Rauf </PERSON> <PERSON> Denktash </PERSON>, the Turkish Cypriot leader, said the decision was in response to Greek Cypriot President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Vassiliou </PERSON>'s statement that there are no borders in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. The decision is mainly symbolic since few people make the crossing through the checkpoint near the Ledra Palace Hotel. Diplomats and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peacekeeping forces will be able to cross as in the past, they said. In the past, Cypriots making the crossing required only permission from both administrations. Greek Cypriots carry passports issued by the Republic of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, the only internationally recognized government on the island. Turkish Cypriots have been issued <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> passports by the Turkish Cypriot administration. The Turkish Cypriots make up about 18 percent of the 650,000 population of the island, divided since the Turkish invasion of 1974 into two zones.
