<HEAD>Chambers Sentenced to 5-to-15 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with sentencing today.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, apologizing for the first time to the family of <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, was sentenced today to five to 15 years in jail for strangling the 18-year-old in Central Park. The sentence was agreed to three weeks earlier when <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter, abruptly ending the celebrated `` preppie murder'' trial in the ninth day of jury deliberations after a three-month trial. `` The <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> family has gone through hell because of my actions,'' <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> said in his first public apology for killing Miss <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>. `` Whoever said time heals all wounds is all wrong.'' Chambers stood silently while state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> E. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> handed down the predetermined sentence in a crowded <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> courtroom. As he did while pleading guilty, the defendant shook his head `` no'' several times during the session, including once when <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> repeated his guilty plea to manslaughter. `` <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>'s looking down, looking and wondering why this all happened. I do n't know,'' <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> said later during his brief statement. `` I never wanted any of this to happen. I wish to apologize to her family and all her friends.'' <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> also apologized to his family and friends, and thanked more than 150 supporters for letters he has received since being jailed after his guilty plea. The Chambers case spotlighted the world of wealthy <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> youths and the underaged drinking, drugs and sex of their lifestyles. Among those in the courtroom for the sentencing were several Chambers trial jurors and several members of the <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> family. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, the slain girl's father, was not permitted to speak at the hearing as he had requested. At the time of the plea, the jury was divided after several votes on the charge of second-degree murder, the stiffest Chambers faced, and sent notes to the judge saying they were at an impasse. The sentence followed a hearing before <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> in which Chambers' attorney, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Litman </PERSON>, complained that the probation report on his client was `` slanted'' and asked for an opportunity to answer charges made by the prosecution in the report <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> granted <PERSON> Litman </PERSON>'s request, telling the attorney to put his comments in writing. The sentencing was delayed for about an hour while <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> read <PERSON> Litman </PERSON>'s response to the probation report. <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, 21, agreed to the first-degree manslaughter plea in a deal with the district attorney as a jury deliberated second-degree murder charges against him, abandoning his story of an accidental death during `` rough sex'' in the park. The agreement was reached after two days of deliberations between prosecutors and Chambers' attorneys, and approved by the <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> family. A manslaughter conviction carries a maximum term of eight and one-third to 25 years. By pleading guilty to first-degree manslaughter in Miss <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s strangulation, <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON> admitted he intended to hurt the teen during an encounter in Central Park on Aug. 26, 1986, and ended up killing her Miss <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s bruised and nearly naked body was found beneath a tree behind the Metropolitan Museum of Art early on the morning of Aug. 26. The couple had run into each other earlier at a popular <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION> `` preppie'' bar. Chambers' plea bargain also took care of three burglary charges against him.
