London close, dollar steady. Picks up 13th graf pvs, `In foreign .
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A big jump in wholesale prices dealt another blow today to financial markets still reeling from an unexpected rise in the trade deficit, pushing stocks down further after Thursday's $ 100 billion selloff. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was off 4.31 points at 2,001.33 at 12:30 p.m. EDT. Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones 7 to 2 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier in the session, the average was down by more than 20 points. The average took a 101.46-point plunge Thursday, which was triggered by a report from the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit rose to $ 13.8 billion in February. The rise of 0.6 percent in wholesale prices in March reported by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> today was the biggest in 11 months and heightened concerns that the economy was becoming overheated. `` It's part of the whole inflationary thesis: the weak dollar, rising imports and strengthening prices all spell difficulty for the economy later on,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, an investment strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Oppenheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. But <PERSON> Metz </PERSON>, noting the big decline in the markets on Thursday, said, `` I think that we've paid for this bad news in the last day and a half already.'' Long-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond prices also fell again today, putting interest rates at a three-month high. But the dollar held about even today after falling sharply Thursday. Overnight on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 225 </ORGANIZATION> selected issues lost 217.78 points to end the day at 26,893.57, a decline of less than 1 percent. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, stock prices edged narrowly lower. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index fell 8.6 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,778.6. It had been off 24.1 points at the opening. In today's report, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the March rise in wholesale prices of 0.6 percent followed a 0.2 percent drop in February. Many analysts had been looking for an increase in March on the order of a 0.2 percent rise. If the March rate held for 12 months, the full-year wholesale inflation rate would be 7 percent, compared with 2.2 percent for all of 1987. In midday trading in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> today, the dollar was bid at 123.8 Japanese yen and 1.66 West German marks. The benchmark 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond was off about -LCB- point, or about $ 5 for every $ 1,000 in face value, as its yield edged up to 8.93 percent from 8.86 percent late Thursday. In foreign exchange Thursday, the dollar fell about 2 percent against the Japanese yen and West German mark despite central bank purchases aimed at bolstering the dollar, and bond market interest rates rose to their highest levels since January. The trade report raised concerns that the dollar would remain under pressure despite a months-old agreement by major industrialized nations to support it. That agreement was reaffirmed Wednesday by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> at a meeting in <LOCATION> Washing