ntinuing to spend strongly, sucking up imports, <PERSON> Worseck </PERSON> said. The trade deficit was the highest since the record gap of $ 17.6 billion in October. It was up from January's $ 12.4 billion gap, but was down from a deficit of $ 14.4 billion in February 1987. `` It's just one of those glitches that keep the financial markets interesting. The trend is still for improvement in the trade deficit,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Solloway </PERSON>, director of economic research at <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>.
