<HEAD>American Companies Say Law May Force Some to Close</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American companies here say they're caught in the middle of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s new economic sanctions and may have to close if they're not allowed to resume payments to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s government <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> gave its workforce in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> a 15-day paid furlough because of the problems in doing business, a company spokesman said Friday. Another company has given its employees `` collective vacations'' since <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> froze all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> payments to the Panamian government on April 8, in an attempt to force Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to relinquish power. A source familiar with the company's situation said it would not reopen until conditions are such that it can pay taxes in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> order prohibits direct or indirect payments, including income taxes, by Americans and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations to the Panamanian government. It also applies to Panamanian corporations owned or directed by Americans. Violators can be sentenced to up to 10 years in prison and fined $ 50,000. Companies have been told that until any exemptions are announced, the order is being enforced to its fullest extent _ right down to the $ 30 departure tax charged at the airport to people leaving the country. `` You ca n't move, you ca n't do anything without breaking the law,'' the head of one company said. `` The executive order puts a gun against my head and the -LRB- Panamanian -RRB- government has a gun against my head, and I'm just ducking,'' he said. All the executives spoke on condition of anonymity. Several company representatives said they were complying with the order and continued to operate, but they noted they did not yet have tax or other payments due the government. Commerce and Industries Minister <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Rognoni </PERSON> has said the government will be flexible with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms. But if electricity, water and telephone bills are not paid, the utilities services run by the government will be cut off. `` We were n't ordered to close, but it just does n't make sense to stay open,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaska </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` We are not permitted to pay our utility bill. We ca n't pay the phone bill.'' One executive said the ability of American manufacturers to continue operating also would depend on whether they have enough raw materials in stock, since importing also requires payments to the government. `` We're hoping there will exceptions for essential items,'' a food company executive said. `` We have tax payments to the government but can not pay them,'' he added. `` We're caught in the middle.'' `` Sooner or later, the executive order is going to shut everybody down. The executive order will totally kill <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' he said. He said some companies paid high taxes the first three quarters, but owed less for the year because of the economic crisis and now have credits, allowing them to postpone a payment decision. An American trade association representative said the law was hurting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies more than its target, <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. `` In essence it's closing down <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies and sending Americans home and not affecting Mr. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> at all. I expect some leeway will have to be allowed,'' he said. `` Really you're a hostage here in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' he said, referring to the airport tax. Panamanian residents also may not leave the country without showing what amounts to an income tax receipt. American businesses are worried about the progressive penalties the Panamanian government may charge if it decides to let the companies pay taxes late. Most executives said they would comply with the sanctions, but a number were said to be looking for ways to get around it. <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Psychoyos </PERSON> said he and his father, both American citizens, have taken leaves of absence from the Panamanian-owned supermarket chain they headed. `` Non-Americans will run the company for a while. From all they said, this is all we can do,'' he said. `` I think most companies are evaluating now whether they want to be thrown in jail in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> or in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Psychoyos </PERSON> said the supermarket chain will continue payments to the government. `` We've got to abide by the laws. We've been here 80 years and we hope to be another 80,'' he said. Under the order, companies are to make their normal payments to an escrow account at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> established for <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, who was ousted from the presidency by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on Feb. 26 after trying to fire the general.
