<HEAD>Signs of Cracks In Palestinian Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cracks are appearing in the underground <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> leadership over how to wage a campaign of resistance against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The divisions are emerging at a time when the frequency and size of street clashes is diminishing, and the nature of the confrontation is changing into more of an economic test of wills. There are two basic splits in <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> ranks: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> is at odds with the mainstream <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> factions on the issue of convening an international conference to negotiate peace. _ The Communists, in a dispute over tactics, have pulled out of the PLO-affiliated underground command, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Uprising </ORGANIZATION>. The underground has announced weekly action programs in a series of leaflets. But starting in early March, there have been multiple versions, some making conflicting demands on the 1.5 million residents of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. In the latest handbill, No. 13, one version calls for three days of general strikes to mark `` Prisoners' Day'' while another version, apparently Communist, called for sit-ins at the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> offices and other locations. `` There are differences on how to act, on tactics, `` conceded <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Manasra </PERSON>, a journalist with the daily <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Taalia </PERSON>. As an example, <PERSON> Manasra </PERSON> cited the repeated calls for general strikes, which he said kept workers away from jobs at a time when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was using economic measures in an effort to put an end to the uprising. `` If <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is putting economic pressure on people, and we also put pressure on people, then we are doing what <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> wants,'' said <PERSON> Manasra </PERSON>, who added workers would ignore strike calls if they became excessive. Instead of general strikes that hurt low-income Palestinians, <PERSON> Manasra </PERSON> said the Communists supported a boycott of Israeli products. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>'s government <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, about half the 110,000 Arabs who hold jobs in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> went to work in February and March. Oficials claim the on-the-job figure has risen recently, although statistics were not available. After Palestinians stopped paying taxes, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities imposed financial and trade restrictions and put the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s 8,000 teachers on half-pay for three weeks The army has also ordered stores closed when <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leaflets said they should be open. `` Food is very expensive. People are feeling the seriousness of the economic strikes,'' <PERSON> Farah </PERSON> <PERSON> El-Araj </PERSON>, the pro-Jordanian mayor of <PERSON> Beit </PERSON> <PERSON> Jallah </PERSON>, said on <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>. A second split is between the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> factions and the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, a coalition of fundamentalist groups that has a large following in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. To counter the increasing Islamic influence, the PLO-affiliated factions, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the Islamic Jihad formed a coalition in early January. Called the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Uprising </ORGANIZATION>, it has followed the policies of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> in seeking an international peace conference and in not escalating clashes by using guns and knives. The fundmentalists, however, oppose negotiations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and seek creation of a pan-Islamic, rather than Palestinian, state. `` The first phase of the uprising is winding down, and they -LRB- Palestinians -RRB- disagree about the second phase, about where to go from here,'' said Col. <PERSON> Renaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON>, deputy army spokesman. `` There are feelings of fatigue. The people want to see some results,'' he added. <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON> said another split threatening the unity of the underground was Islamic Jihad's desire to wage armed struggle, a policy opposed by <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> groups. Despite the disputes, <PERSON> Manasra </PERSON> said the resistance would continue because local committees rather than the leaflet writers had the final say on whether to observe calls for strikes and protests. For example, he said he doubted whether local committees would heed the call in the latest leaflet to throw firebombs on April 21, the so-called `` Day of the Palestinian Molotov.'' The army spokesman said the overall level of violence had dropped markedly in recent weeks even though the bloodshed had not ceased altogether. `` The intensity of the clashes is still high, but there are fewer confrontations and the size of demonstrations is smaller, a hundred or so instead of thousands,'' said <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON>. There have been 7,000 clashes between soldiers and demonstrators since Dec. 8, killing 146 Arabs and two Israelis. More than 1,000 Arabs have been wounded by gunfire. `` I think we are now in an ebbing phase of the uprising. We've already reached the peak But when it finally subsides, I do n't think it will go back to the same level it started at four months ago,'' said <PERSON> Sari </PERSON> <PERSON> Nusseibah </PERSON>, a philosophy professor at the <ORGANIZATION> Bir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>
