<HEAD>Welfare and Property Tax Laws Stir Thatcher Rebellion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s controversial social welfare legislation is stirring the fiercest opposition she has encountered since her re-election last June. The resistance is coming not just from the opposition, but from rank-and-file lawmakers within her own <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, who on Thursday night staged their biggest back-bench revolt since June. Twenty-eight of the 376 Tories in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> voted against the government's decision to end free dental checkups and eye examinations. The sums involved _ $ 5.60 for the dental checkup _ are small, but they matter to the poor and they come in the same month as the top income tax rate is being slashed from 60 to 40 percent. And while the number of rebels looks relatively small, any revolt is significant, given Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s strong-willed style of leadership. Customarily, a lawmaker voting against his government almost automatiucally destroys his chances of winning government office. The social welfare moves and a controversial reform of property taxes, another <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> brainchild, have combined to arouse deep unease among sections of the Parliamentary rank-and-file about her radical third term program. `` At the heart of the debate is a fear that the very well-off make substantial gains which are wholly financed by the less well-off,'' said Conservative legislator Sir <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a leading rebel. `` Playing around with rebates for the poor in no way tackles that fundamental inequity.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> remains determined to wean Britons off what she calls the `` dependency culture'' and encourage private enterprise. She points to the economic revival her rigorous policies have wrought, including the fastest growth rate in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the country's first budget surplus in nearly two decades. But there are signs of defensiveness. On Thursday night, the 62-year-old prime minister made a comparatively rare foray into the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> tea room to rally support for the new property tax, popularly called the poll tax. And the government announced an extension of rebates, costing about $ 245 million and affecting 1 million people, in a move to blunt another rebellion when the poll tax comes up for a key vote Monday. That concession appeared aimed at heading off a major revolt Monday in the 650-member Commons, where the Conservatives' hefty 102-seat majority was whittled to 81 and 74 in Thursday's votes. Under the poll tax, families will be rated according to how many adults are living in the home. Estimates are that the tax on some homes will more than double, hitting modest earners hardest. `` It will manifestly be perceived to be unfair,'' complained another <ORGANIZATION> Tory </ORGANIZATION> legislator, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mates </PERSON>, who hopes to get about 50 colleagues to back an amendment that would base the tax on income instead of a flat charge. Like changes in housing subsidies which force everyone, including public housing tenants, to pay at least one-fifth of the property taxes on their homes, the poll tax is fundamental to a Thatcher onslaught on local councils. The local councils, which run local government, are dominated by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s left-wing. They levy and spend property taxes and most of the bigger councils are run by the socialist <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The Guardian newspaper, the nation's foremost liberal daily, argued that <ORGANIZATION> Tory </ORGANIZATION> legislators with narrowly held seats are frightened by Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s measures. `` Where damaging policy changes were unable to provoke a revolt, political survival has succeeded,'' it said. A straw poll among 100 rank-and-file <ORGANIZATION> Tory </ORGANIZATION> legislators by another daily, The Independent, found nearly two-thirds expressing alarm at the social security changes. The government says it is merely refocusing the $ 86 billion welfare budget on the most needy. But opposition and welfare groups estimate that two-thirds of the 8.6 million welfare claimants will lose funds. The government acknowledges 43 percent will receive less. Polls show the Conservative government is losing support. Gallup's March poll showed the Conservatives 5.5 points ahead of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, down from 10 the previous month. Two-thirds of the 1,094 voters questioned said they thought the tax-cutting budget announced March 15 was `` not fair.'' The Conservatives received 42 percent support _ enough for another victory _ with Labor getting 36.5 percent and the rest split among two center parties and minority regional parties
