<HEAD>Industrial Production Posts Tiny Gain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Production at the nation's factories, mines and utilities edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in March, the government said Friday, somewhat counterbalancing signs that inflation is reheating. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said gains in production of autos and business equipment offset declines in construction supplies and consumer goods other than cars. The slight March advance followed no change in February and, according to economists, is an indication that the pickup in wholesale prices may not be sustainable. `` It is n't the type of boom production environment that would support rapid gains in inflation,'' said <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, chief economist at <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in a separate report Friday, said wholesale inflation was running at a 7 percent annual rate in March. That news sent jitters through the financial markets and pushed interest rates higher. `` Ironically, a fairly low growth rate in industrial production is good in one sense ... It may actually allay suspicions that the economy may be on the verge of overheating,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>. Before February, production had been increasing at a steady pace: 0.5 percent in November and December and 0.4 percent in January. The last decline was in September, when production fell 0.2 percent. Production had shot up 1.1 percent in October. Despite two months of lackluster growth, production levels in March were a strong 5.6 percent above levels a year ago. The March rise included a 0.2 percent jump in production at manufacturing plants after a flat performance in February. That included a 2.6 percent increase in auto production, which followed a 0.8 percent drop in February, and a 0.6 percent boost in production of equipment used by businesses, the fourth consecutive gain. Factories making durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, saw output rise 0.3 percent last month; output at plants making non-durable goods was unchanged for the second month in a row. Mining output increased 0.4 percent after a 1.0 percent drop in February. Output at utilities dropped 1.2 percent after a 0.5 percent increase. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, forecasting firm, said the drop at utility companies was caused by warmer-than-usual weather in March. He predicted that industrial production overall would pick up in coming months. `` We ought to see auto production coming up ... Inventories are now down to near-normal levels. The drop in utilities should be over,'' <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. The various changes left industrial production at 134.6 percent of its 1977 base of 100.
