<FIRST>r a AM-CDC-Suicides     04-15 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC-Suicides,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Extraordinary' Community Response To Suicides Can Be Appropriate,
CDC Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The tragedies of multiple suicides by young people can provide lessons for other communities to follow in the future, according to a new report by the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. On March 11, 1987, in <LOCATION> Bergenfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, two young men, 18 and 19, and two young women, 16 and 17, committed suicide by locking themselves in a garage and sitting inside a car with the motor running. Within days, school officials identified other students they felt might be at risk, counseling was provided to young people and a local suicide hotline and a walk-in counseling center were started. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> report, as is the agency's custom, did not name the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> town where the four young people died on that date. But <LOCATION> Bergenfield </LOCATION> has been identified in numerous news reports about the deaths. After an investigation, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted in its weekly report Thursday that `` when a suicide cluster does occur, an extraordinary amount of community effort and resources is temporarily devoted to suicide prevention.'' `` Such a response ... is appropriate,'' the Atlanta-based health agency said. `` It is prudent for a community faced with a suicide cluster to make every effort to anticipate and prevent additional suicides among susceptible individuals.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said communities should consider contingency plans for suicide clusters, and `` may want to consider implementing a suicide response plan before a cluster has begun.'' Many suicide clusters, the agency said, have followed one or more deaths due to injuries among young people. Planning ahead can keep communities from `` reinventing the wheel'' during their own tragedies, said Dr. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Carroll </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's no reason for every single community that runs into this to try to start from scratch. There's experience they can try to take advantage of,'' <PERSON> O'Carroll </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Bergenfield </LOCATION>, a suburban community six miles west of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, had an annual suicide rate of seven per 100,000 during 1980-84, significantly lower than the national rate of 12 per 100,000, <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> researchers found. But in that town and in others where people have died in apparent suicide pacts, there have been similarities, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said: other young people had died unnaturally before the suicides, and the suicides may have had a `` contagious'' effect, prompting others to try to kill themselves. The young <LOCATION> Bergenfield </LOCATION> men had both been friends of an 18-year-old who died in a fall from a cliff six months earlier. And after the four teen-agers killed themselves, two other young people _ a 20-year-old and a 17-year-old _ attempted suicide together in the same garage.
