<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> denied Friday that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's resistance to a labor-backed plant-closing provision in a new trade bill constitutes an anti-worker stance. While renewing President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s threat to veto the legislation if the plant shutdown notification requirement remained intact, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, `` We're trying to keep people's jobs.'' `` We want a trade bill that does n't eliminate jobs through foreign competition,'' he said. `` We want a bill that maximizes the opportunities for companies to stay in business and people can keep their jobs,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters. `` And that's what you're going to hear from us if we have to veto this bill.'' But during his daily <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> news briefing, the spokesman acknowledged that administration negotiators on the sweeping trade bill are stymied in attempts to talk lawmakers into discarding the plant notification provision. `` I think there's still some opportunity for talk,'' he said. But he said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would not accept any version of the trade bill that contained provisions which are `` injurious to a dynamic economy.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> reiterated <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto intentions in the wake of a further deterioration of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trade deficit and as <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members wrangled over the language to be kept in the final version of the 1,000-page trade bill. Conferees are trying to iron out differences between competing <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions of the bill. The plant-closings provision, which was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> but not the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, would require companies with at least 100 employees to give 60-day notice of plant closings or layoffs involving at least 150 positions if that represented one-third of the work force. All layoffs of 500 or more would have to be accompanied by notice, regardless of whether they represented a third of the work force. Business groups oppose the provision, arguing that it could lead to other steps to strip away the prerogatives of company managers. The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> and other organizations in the labor movement maintain the measure is necessary to prepare workers for the need to find new employment. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> made good progress in moving toward such a bill,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Friday. But he said the White House is displeased that the plant-closing provision remains in the bill. `` Our negotiators ... were encouraged to believe the plant closing provision would be eliminated,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` Later, however, we were told that after certain consultations took place, they could not remove that provision. The labor unions apparently would sacrifice the entire trade bill for this provision.'' `` While the administration would be willing to accept a positive trade bill, we can not accept one that includes seriously flawed elements that will hurt <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s competitiveness,'' the spokesman said. `` If the bill reaches the president in its present form, the president will veto it,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The Democratic leadership had seemed close to dropping the plant-closings plan on Wednesday. But overnight lobbying by organized labor led to a chorus of protests Thursday in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> caucus, said sources who spoke only if not quoted by name. Top Democrats announced their support for the plan at midafternoon Thursday. They said new figures from the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> showing a widening <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit and an accompanying 101-point drop in the stock market called for a strong legislative response.
