<FIRST>r w PM-Billig-Ruling 3rdLd-Writethru a0650 04-15 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Billig-Ruling, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0650,730</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 4-5 pvs, Billig automatically, to restore initial
identification of spokeswoman.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A day after his conviction on charges of killing three patients was overturned, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> heart surgeon <PERSON> Donal </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> was allowed today to leave <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Leavenworth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION>, where he had been held prisoner for two years. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy-Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday overturned <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s conviction because, the court said, `` the evidence was simply not sufficient.'' <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>, held at the fort since 1986, was released from the prison itself Thursday, but was held overnite in the base's bachelor officers quarters while administrative paperwork was completed <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> automatically returns to active duty with his previous rank of commander and is eligible for $ 120,000 in back pay, but he can not practice medicine, said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, Lt. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Mescus </PERSON>. She said <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> would probably be assigned to a <ORGANIZATION> Navy-Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> reserve center in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> while the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> makes a decision on appealing the verdict. The service has 20 days to make that decision. The court's 20-page opinion said prosecutors had failed to establish <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s guilt `` beyond a reasonable doubt.'' The appeals court said the prosecutors at <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s 1986 court martial `` lost sight of the fact that coronary artery bypass surgery is an inherently risky business.'' The prosecutors argued that <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> used questionable surgical techniques, the court said, but never really produced the evidence or testimony to demonstrate that <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s work in the operating room was so out of line as to constitute criminal conduct. `` We shall set aside all findings of guilty based on this factual insufficiency of the evidence,'' the court said. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has 20 days to file a formal motion with the appeals court asking it to reconsider the matter. The service said Thursday it had made no decision yet on pursuing an appeal. <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>, 57, was the former chief heart surgeon at the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s flagship <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, and held the military rank of commander He was convicted in early 1986 of two counts of involuntary manslaughter and one count of negligent homicide in the deaths of three patients. He also was convicted on 18 of 24 counts of dereliction of duty stemming from other operations. He was sentenced on March 3, 1986, to four years in prison. Last summer, he was rebuffed in his first bid for parole. <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s case attracted great public attention, in part because of the sensational nature of some of the charges. It also prompted congressional reviews of military health care in general and several large monetary settlements between the government and relatives of <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s patients. Prosecutors described <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> as an egocentric man, nearly blind in one eye, who hid his visual handicap and continued performing complex heart operations despite numerous warnings that he was killing patients. The appeals court, in its opinion, said it was troubled by <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s conviction because his court-martial had involved criminal charges as opposed to civil claims for damages based on negligence. The court quoted from a <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that stated: `` The question is not whether a defendant should absorb the dollar loss of his victim, but whether his conduct justifies stamping him a criminal and sending him to state prison.'' In <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s case, the military court said it appeared the prosecutors `` lost sight of the fact that coronary artery bypass surgery is an inherently risky business ... and that those patients who agree to this elective surgery are quite ill in the first place ...'' `` Given the critical nature of the work and its complexity, these surgeons face a difficult enough task without having to worry about the spectre of the criminal prosecutor, waiting to reduce to a ` charge sheet' honest mistakes which fall far short of the gross, wanton and deliberate misconduct ... that truly deserves punishment. `` We are not convinced beyond a reasonable doubt that the deaths that formed the basis of the appellant's conviction were due to any negligence, simple or otherwise, on his part.'' The court also faulted the presiding military judge at the court-martial for allowing the prosecution to conduct `` a smear campaign'' against <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>. `` The appellant was forced not only to defend against the charges, but also to explain and account for virtually all of his mistakes, professional setbacks or surgical misadventures during the previous 20 years. This ` bad surgeon' theory permeated the trial proceedings and undoubtedly influenced the court members' decisions.
