<HEAD>Officials Warn Against Unofficial Observances Of Anniversary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polish authorities on Friday warned organizers of an unsanctioned ceremony to mark the 45th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Jewish Ghetto Uprising that the gathering would be considered illegal, an organizer said. The warning came on the second day of a weeklong official anniversary to honor the victims of the Nazi Holocaust during World War II. It is the largest such event ever organized in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. On Friday, meanwhile, a Polish scholar told a scientific conference that she is ashamed of anti-Semitic behavior in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1968 and asked why more Polish officials, including some conference organizers, have not come forward to accept responsibility. About 4,500 people from around the world, including 2,000 from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> including <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Itzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON>, have come to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for the Ghetto Uprising Anniversary, honoring the fighters who resisted the final Nazi onslaught against the ghetto for three weeks in April and May of 1943. In addition to the official observances, a group of 46 intellectuals and opposition activists has called for an unofficial ceremony Sunday in front of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Ghetto Fighters' Monument and in the old Jewish Cemetery. The group is led by <PERSON> Marek </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, a longtime opposition activist who is the last surviving commander of the uprising remaining in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> says he is boycotting the official observances because he considers them a cynical attempt by the government to win favor in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, an organizer of the unsanctioned ceremony and an adviser to the outlawed trade union Solidarity, said he was taken to a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> prosecutor's office for the warning talk by plainclothed police. `` I was told that the event which I am co-organizing on Sunday... is illegal ... so the authorities can not assure protection and the -LRB- organizing -RRB- committee will be morally and legally responsible for any possible provocations which might take place,'' <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> said <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON> said the committee intends to proceed with the observances anyway, including a wreath-laying ceremony at the Ghetto Fighters' Monument and the dedication of a memorial in the Jewish Cemetery to two Polish-Jewish socialists executed by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> during World War II The alternative observances have come under heavy attack in the official media, which has charged the organizers with being anti-Soviet `` hyenas'' trying to take advantage of the anniversary to call attention to themselves. Meanwhile, on the second day of a two-day historical and scientific conference on the struggle of Jews and Poles under the Nazi occupation, <PERSON> Irena </PERSON> <PERSON> Maciejewska </PERSON> drew applause at the conference when she referred to the politically inspired anti-Semitic purge that took place in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1968. Mrs. <PERSON> Maciejewska </PERSON>, who was delivering a paper on the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Ghetto Uprising in literature, said that when she cooperates with one official institution co-sponsoring the conference, the <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, she finds herself `` in the company of people who injured the good name of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1968.'' To applause from the audience of several hundred people, she added: `` As a university person I painfully remember that time and as a Pole I should be ashamed of it.'' The Polish <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Party, in a newspaper article last month, said anti-Semitism played a role in 1968 in political purges that caused thousands of Jews to lose jobs in government, journalism, the army and academia. Opposition activists criticized the statement as being too mild and for not identifying individuals involved, some of whom they charged still hold prominent positions in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.
