<HEAD>U.S. Vetoes Resolution on Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> UNITED </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NATIONS </ORGANIZATION> _ The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> today vetoed a <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution urging <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to halt deportations of Palestinians from the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy said the measure was unbalanced. The vote was 14-1. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> envoy, <PERSON> Zehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON>, condemned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> veto as shielding <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from international criticism. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has chosen to single itself out,'' he said. `` There's always a rotten apple in the box.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Okun </PERSON> cast the veto and said the resolution's `` broad and sweeping condemnation of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> contains not a scintilla of balance. It contains no appeal or request for calm.'' <PERSON> Okun </PERSON> said the resolution `` neither contributes to easing tensions in the occupied territories, nor promotes the cause of peace.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy said it was the fifth time since December that the council considered the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> situation. `` We do not regard this recurrent recourse to the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> as befitting its authority and prestige,'' he said. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was engaged in a major diplomatic effort with the parties directly concerned to bring about direct negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and her Arab neighbors. The meeting of the 15-member council was prompted by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s deportation of eight <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> civilians this week Since anti-occupation unrest broke out Dec. 8, 146 Arabs have been killed in the territories <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. The resolution, originally toughly worded, had been watered down in an unsuccessful effort to avert a veto by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which often kills resolutions critical of its ally. The vetoed resolution, supported by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and all other council members, urged <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to halt deportations and condemned violations of human rights in the occupied territories. It called for a U.N.-sponsored settlement of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> problem. Soviet Ambassador <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Belonogov </PERSON> reflected new flexibility by his government on a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> solution, diplomats said. In his speech, criticism of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was not as strident as in earlier speeches and he emphasized the importance of `` balance of interests of all parties concerned, both Arabs, including the Palestinian people, as well as <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' He said a U.N.-sponsored international conference is `` the most effective machinery'' to achieve a political settlement. He indicated that `` interim arrangements'' could be acceptable and said that a conference on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> could be conducted on both a `` bilateral and multilateral basis.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have opposed an international conference that would impose a settlement upon <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and are opposed to participation by the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. They have emphasized the importance of bilateral negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and her neighbors.
