<HEAD>Unions Strike For Raises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About half of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s businesses closed Friday in the first day of a national strike called by a union demanding a 300 percent wage increase. The government of this chaos-ridden nation, which faces a severe economic crisis, has offered an increase of about 75 percent. Police said 50 percent of both Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> areas were closed in response to the strike call issued Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>, or GCLU. Some banks, schools, restaurants, movie theaters, gas stations and other businesses closed in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sectors as well as in other major cities and towns, a police statement said. However, a variety of businesses defied the 300,000-member union and maintained normal activity. The union called for the two-day strike after rejecting as insufficient the 75 percent increase in private - and public-sector wages announced by acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> `` Some employers are clearly defying the <ORGANIZATION> GCLU </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. They called their employees to work, and strangely these employees reported to duty,'' a police spokesman said. `` GCLU teams are touring <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and other cities in an effort to convince violators to abide by the strike,'' said the spokesman. A government source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the 75 percent increase `` is the highest the state treasury and private businesses can afford.'' `` The employees realize this. That's why they are hesitant in abiding by the strike,'' he said. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Srouji </PERSON>, who runs a ready-made clothes factory in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said even a 75 percent raise would be `` difficult to meet.'' `` We will have to raise our prices. In this case, the unions will start nagging again and demand another pay raise,'' <PERSON> Srouji </PERSON> said at his factory, which stayed open Friday. `` If the unions insist on a 300 percent raise, I will close,'' he threatened. `` Closing will strip my 70 employees from their income. Is this what the GCLU wants?'' Some of his employees also appeared convinced that the size of the raise demand was not in their interest. `` The boss will definitely fire most of us if the 300 percent increase was decided,'' said <PERSON> Elie </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Issa </PERSON>, who works at a hairdressing salon in Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. `` There would be less clients if the raise was decided because the fees would be brought up sharply. In such a case, the boss and an assistant will be enough to handle the job, and most of us will be fired,'' <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Issa </PERSON> said. `` I do n't want to be unemployed, especially when prices are soaring,'' he added. The Lebanese pound slipped against foreign currencies following <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>' 75 percent pay increase announcement Thursday and closed at 400 to the dollar. It opened at 380 to the dollar early in the day. <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s economy, once the most flourishing in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, has been hit hard by 13 years of violence. The pound, which rated 2.5 to the dollar before the outbreak of the civil war in 1975, has declined sharply against foreign currencies, pushing prices sky high in a nation that imports more than 85 percent of its needs.
