<HEAD>US Distressed over Danish Anti-Nuclear Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it was `` deeply distressed'' over a resolution approved by the Danish parliament which closes a loophole in a government ban on ships carrying nuclear weapons into Danish ports. The resolution, approved Thursday by a 75-58 vote, requires the government to inform visiting naval vessels of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s anti-nuclear policy <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> has a nuclear ban policy but has not been asking such vessels if they are carrying nuclear weapons. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said implementation of the Danish resolution in a way which is inconsistent with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy of not discussing which ships carry nuclear weapons would undercut <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> security. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has a long-standing policy of neither confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear weapons aboard its ships. `` This policy is central to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ability to fulfill its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> commitments,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` We are not going to change it.'' `` It would have extremely serious consequences for U.S.-Danish defense cooperation,'' he said, adding that the impact of this issue extends beyond bilateral relations. `` It goes to the very heart of the meaning and interlocking nature of our mutual commitments within the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance,'' he said. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said the policy of withholding information about the presence of nuclear weapons is aimed at keeping `` terrorists and saboteurs'' in the dark and makes effective attacks on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces more difficult. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> added that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will review together with the Danish government and other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies the implications of the resolution for the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance and continued defense cooperation with <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>.
