<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleTest     04-15 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Test,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Full-Scale Test-Firing Set Wednesday For Redesigned Shuttle
Booster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The third full-scale test firing of the redesigned space shuttle booster rocket will be conducted Wednesday, <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced. <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said the 1 p.m. horizontal firing of the 126-foot-long rocket will last two minutes. The booster, 12 feet in diameter, contains 1.1 million pounds of propellant. During the second full-scale firing on Dec. 23, the rocket's NASA-designed nozzle boot ring broke apart The boot ring, about two inches thick, protects a flexible bearing that allows the nozzle to swivel and steer the rocket. Company officials said the test will incorporate the nozzle boot ring designed by <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> which performed successfully during the first full-scale test last August. Wednesday's firing, although the third of its kind at the <LOCATION> Wasatch </LOCATION> Operations test site, is the first of three required to qualify the new booster for flight. Subsequent tests are scheduled June 3 and July 6. The August and December tests evaluated primary and alternate elements of solid rocket motor design, <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. He said the center field joint on the motor to be tested next week has been assembled with an `` intentional manufacturing-type flaw'' in the bonded insulation's J-seal. `` This defect may allow hot gases to penetrate the bonded insulation'' and reach an O-ring barrier, but <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> added that short-duration test firings with similar defects have shown that such defects tend to seal under motor pressure, preventing the release of gases. The escape of such super-hot gases from a <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> booster was blamed for the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle Challenger and deaths of its seven crew members. The resumption of shuttle missions is tentatively scheduled for Aug. 4, although <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials have said technical problems could further delay the launch.
