<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Contras     04-15 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Contras,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Returning Rebel Leaders Will Find More Misery in Managua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contra rebel leaders returning to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Friday, some after years in exile, can expect to find considerably more misery but not many tangible changes in their capital. The trip by the directorate of the Miami-based Nicaraguan Resistance was to further work started last month to reach a lasting cease-fire and end more than six years of civil war. Just a few months back such a visit seemed impossible. But haggling and compromise on both sides, coupled with a need to end the grueling war, made the trip a necessity. The Contras 45-member delegation will find that the leftist Sandinistas still maintain a firm control on the day-to-day workings of the government, although their popularity has slipped. The capital still is dusty and hot this time of year, though increased poverty and population are evident. Vast open lots left barren since the 1972 earthquake have not been filled. The walls of homes and buildings bear pro-Sandinista and Marxist grafitti. A steep hillside bears the initials of the Sandinista party. A large black iron statue in a downtown plaza shows a fighter with one fist in the air, the other arm raised and holding a Soviet-designed AK-47 rifle. Red-and-black Sandinista flags fly everywhere. Thousands of people, most from the rural north, flooded into the capital and its environs to escape the ravages of war. <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> is home to about a third of the nation's population of 3 million. Wooden shacks sit in dusty lots. Water has been rationed for the past few years. Some neighborhoods do without for as little as two days a week, while others receive water only a few hours per week. There are shortages of everything from spare parts for cars to the basics of rice and beans. Discontent was on the rise earlier this year because of the economic conditions, the scarcities and the mandatory draft. But attitudes changed last month when the cease-fire talks made it seem that peace could be a reality. The mood in the capital has been one of guarded hope, with most residents acknowledging there never has been a point so close to ending the war. The Contra delegation was headed by the Resistance's board, made up of <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aristides </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Azucena </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON>. All of the directorate members, except for Ms. <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON>, come from upper crust Nicaraguan families. <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> went into exile in 1982 and was the political head of the largest <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> group, the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. He holds a law degree and headed the <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. He opposed the former government of dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>, ousted by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> in 1979. But he later called the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> a group of Marxists. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, where he was responsible for Contra logistics. He is considered a stauch nationalist and a pragmatic and sensible negotiator. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> joined the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 and after the revolution became executive director of the International Construction Fund. He also served as head of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. He left <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in 1982, saying the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> were Marxists, and moved to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. He worked with the government there and later joined the Contras operating on the southern front. <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, whose family owns the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>, went into exile in 1984. His brother, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON>, is editor of the Sandinista newspaper Barricada. One of his sisters is the ambassador to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> was the latest to join the directorate, having stayed in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> until last year. She was staunchly opposed to <ORGANIZATION> Somoza </ORGANIZATION> and reportedly aided some of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> during their guerrilla campaign against him. A member of the <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, she comes from a middle-class family and became a vocal internal Sandinista critic.
