<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInvestment     04-15 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Investment,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businesses Plan to Boost Capital Spending 8 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Businesses plan to increase capital spending by 8 percent this year, the government reported Friday, raising hopes that manufacturers will expand factory capacity enough to ease long-term inflation pressures. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies expect to spend $ 419.9 billion, after adjustments for inflation, on expansion and modernization this year. If realized, that would be the best gain since a 9.6 percent rise in 1985. Businesses spent $ 388.7 billion last year, a 1.7 percent increase over 1986. The new estimate for 1988, based on a survey completed in March, represented an increase over a survey finished in November, when businesses said they planned to spend 7.3 percent more. `` That's good for inflation in the longer term,'' said <PERSON> Maury </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` That added capacity helps meet demand. ... If they were n't increasing their capital spending, I'd worry.'' A separate report by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Friday, showing wholesale prices advancing at a 7 percent annual rate, renewed inflation fears among investors. Adding to the concern is the fact that the operating rate at factories, at 82.4 percent of capacity in February, is the highest in eight years. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> plans to release data for March on Monday. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a Philadelphia-area forecasting firm, said if businesses follow through on their plans, they will be able to produce more. `` Most of the capital spending that companies are involved in is for equipment, a lot of it for replacing older, less-efficient equipment that they had been using for years ... In the long run, it's very positive for improving productivity,'' <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON> said. The capital spending survey also eases fears running in the other direction _ that dampened consumer demand would lead to a recession this year. Economists are looking to manufacturing for export and capital spending to keep the economy growing. The cheaper dollar is creating more demand overseas for U.S.-manufactured goods and capital spending is increasing so factories can meet that demand. In 1986, investment spending fell by 2.6 percent as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> companies battled stiff foreign competition. For 1988, manufacturing firms expected to boost spending by 8.9 percent, after a 1.1 percent increase last year. The anticipated growth this year includes a 6.5 percent boost by firms making durable goods, items expected to last three or more years, and an 11.2 percent advance at companies making non-durable goods. Non-manufacturing industries projected an increase in investment spending of 7.5 percent, with mining, transportation, utility and other commercial firms all expecting gains. Utility companies predicted the smallest increase in 1988, 1.9 percent, after a 0.6 percent drop in spending in 1987.
