<SECOND>AM-Cuban Bonds,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widow Wins Early Round In Battle To Cash In 50-Year-Old Cuban
Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An elderly widow has won the first round in her legal battle against a bank and the government to cash in $ 127,000 worth of half-century-old bonds issued by the Republic of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. The ruling led the woman's lawyer to wonder what happened to the millions of dollars that should have been in a bank account to back the $ 1,000-face-value bonds. It also has fueled speculation in the bonds. The 1937 $ 85 million bond issue matured in 1977. Manufacturers Hanover Trust of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was an indentured trustee for part of the bond issue, meaning the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government contracted to pay a set amount to Manufacturers Hanover, which would pay the bondholders. The government of <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> stopped making payments in 1960. When <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosa </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, 77, of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gardens </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, applied to Manufacturers Hanover in early 1987 to redeem the bonds, which she inherited from her mother, the bank refused. The federal Office of Foreign Assets Control told her the bank was correct in refusing to redeem the bonds, because they were considered frozen under the Trading with the Enemy Act. Mrs. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> filed suit in September, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clyde </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> ruled March 13 that she was entitled to the money because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> unreasonably considered all the bonds, even those held by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> residents, as frozen assets. An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> resident should n't be stopped from seeking payment from an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> institution, the judge decreed. `` This court recognizes the importance of providing the president with flexibility in his negotiations with the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government. However, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may only use those assets that are not property of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> residents,'' he wrote in his order. Attorneys for the government and <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> asked to delay payment to Mrs. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> pending a decision on whether to appeal. Her lawyer, <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Arandia </PERSON>, filed a counter motion asking that they pay immediately. No court date has been set on the motions. `` There's many unidentified holders of these bonds. ... We do n't know who they are,'' <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroeger </PERSON>, an attorney for the bank, told the judge Estimating there are $ 44 million in bonds in circulation in this country, the bank says there is only about $ 1.5 million in the fund to pay off bondholders. <PERSON> Arandia </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>'s lawyer, said he wants a full accounting of the bond fund, arguing that according to the payment schedule, the bank should have received $ 40 million by 1960. Although the bond issue was to mature in 1977, <PERSON> Arandia </PERSON> said that as far as he can determine his client appears to be the first to ever try to redeem any of the bonds, meaning the question of whether they could be redeemed had never been asked before. `` It's very strange,'' he said Friday of the entire case. The federal Office of Foreign Assets Control was not happy with the judge's ruling. `` The court's decision could become a vehicle enabling <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to obtain <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars,'' said agency spokesman <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Newcombe </PERSON>. In the meantime, speculators have been snapping up the old bonds and trading them on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with hopes of a thaw in relations between <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Before <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>' ruling, the bonds traded for $ 200, but a week later they traded for $ 450.
