<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Dali,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Soviet Exhibition of Salvador Dali's Drawings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The artistic freedom fostered by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> brought the work of Spanish surrealist <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Dali </PERSON> out of a `` zone of silence'' to Soviets for the first time Friday, the head of the host museum said. <PERSON> Irina </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonova </PERSON>, the director of the <ORGANIZATION> Pushkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s nightmarish style in sculpture, painting and graphics had been off limits in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` The creative work of the surrealists, including <PERSON> Dali </PERSON> to some extent, belonged to a zone of silence of such themes of art that were closed until recent times,'' said <PERSON> Antonova </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` glasnost'' policy of more openness has encouraged intellectuals and artists to explore previously forbidden themes in their work, and <PERSON> Antonova </PERSON> said the display of <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s work represents a break from conservative policies of Soviet museums. `` Very many blank spots in literature, art and cinematography are being opened for our audiences,'' she said. `` And I would assume that the work of <PERSON> Dali </PERSON> now should be placed in that context.'' Before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, Soviet media blasted <PERSON> Dali </PERSON> as decadent and degenerate and did not publish any reproductions of his work. The Pushkin Museum kicked off its display of 160 Dali graphics and a few sculptures from the collection of Frenchman <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Argillet </PERSON> with private showings for Soviet and foreign journalists and for invited dignitaries such as government officials. The one-month exhibition opens to the public Saturday, but people began lining up Friday during a snowstorm in hopes of getting into the museum, a few blocks from the Kremlin. They were told tickets wo n't go on sale until Saturday. Long lines are common at most cultural events involving foreign artists. <PERSON> Antonova </PERSON> bristled when asked if it would be difficult for people to get tickets. `` They will get tickets just like everywhere, as in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, people will stand at the cashier's booth, buy tickets and go to the exhibit,'' she said, declining to say how many people would be allowed to view the exhibit daily. Argillet, 78, said Soviet officials became interested in his collection of <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s sketches after musicians from the Soviet Conservatory and dancers from the Kirov and Bolshoi ballets saw the works in the Frenchman's home, the <ORGANIZATION> Chateau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vaux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Penil </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Melun </LOCATION>, 24 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. He signed a contract for the <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> exhibition in October with the Soviet Culture Ministry. Argillet, a publisher of <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s works, said the 84-year-old artist is in poor health in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and could n't attend the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> showing, but would be pleased it was taking place. Some Soviets said they regretted that the exhibition was limited to <PERSON> Dali </PERSON>'s etchings and drawings from the 1960s and did not include his better-known and more colorful paintings.
