<HEAD>Students Walk Out When Squad Drops Black Majorette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACCLENNY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 High school administrators have promised to review the way drum majorettes are chosen after 25 to 30 students staged a walkout when the squad's first and only black member was dropped. The students chanted `` We want Mazy'' as they left classes at <ORGANIZATION> Baker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> for about an hour Thursday in the school and were joined at a schoolyard fence by 10 to 15 parents. <PERSON> Mazy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruise </PERSON>, 15, a sophomore, has been a majorette for the past two years, but did not make the squad for the 1988-89 school year. She is the 10-member squad's first and only black member. `` All of the kids in the band felt Mazy was highly qualified to return to the majorette group,'' said <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, a parent. `` I feel I've been treated unfairly,'' said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruise </PERSON>, the only black to try out for the 1988-89 squad. She said she was touched when she saw that parents and students gathered at the fence to protest the decision. The school's enrollment of 1,000 students is 17 percent black. <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a guidance counselor who is serving as acting principal, met with students and parents at the Thursday protest. After complaints that <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruise </PERSON> had been unfairly treated, Ms. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> agreed to review `` the whole situation concerning Mazy'' and the school's policies for majorette selection. The walkout `` did not totally disrupt the school,'' Ms. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. Students returned to school after missing just one class Thursday, and the school day went on normally on Friday, she said. Students who tried out for the majorette squad last month did dance and twirling routines and then were ranked by scores tallied by four judges, all white. Two of the judges were from d