<HEAD>Carrie Hamilton Plays Familiar Character in First Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actress-singer <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, who enjoys dressing up and pretending to be someone else, says she plays someone just like herself in her first movie, `` Toyko Pop.'' `` Wendy is me,'' the 24-year-old daughter of <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> says of the character she portrays, an American rocker who finds fame, love and self-understanding in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` There's nothing she had to go through I did n't know all about,'' <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said in an interview in the May issue of Cosmopolitan magazine. The movie's director saw a photo of Miss Hamilton, with her bleached-white spiked hair, and her mother in People magazine and informed the casting director to judge all aspiring <ORGANIZATION> Wendys </ORGANIZATION> by the photograph. Later, someone suggested sending the script to <ORGANIZATION> Miss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION>. When she read it, she told the magazine, she felt as if she was reading of a kindred spirit. Miss <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> says it was always easier for her daughter `` to be somebody else.'' `` She's like me in that sense,'' the comedian-actress said. `` Rub up against us too close and we turn into somebody else. It gives us courage to hide behind a mask.'' For fun, <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> says she likes to dress up decadently as the late <PERSON> Edie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedgwick </PERSON>, a one-time member of <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s crew, and hit the nightclubs with her boyfriend, a look-alike of the late artist.
