<HEAD>Soviets Buy More Subsidized U.S. Wheat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An additional 325,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat has been sold to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> at subsidized prices, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. The sale, equal to about 11.9 million bushels, was handled by <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 25,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Cargill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 100,000; <ORGANIZATION> Artfer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; <ORGANIZATION> Garnac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000; and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 100,000 <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the grain was sold under terms of the long-term grain agreement between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the subsidies averaged $ 24.70 per ton, or about 67 cents per bushel of wheat. No selling prices were announced, but wheat has been averaging about $ 2.84 per bushel recently, according to the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>. That could mean a farm value of about $ 50 million. The U.S.-Soviet pact, which expires Sept. 30, calls on <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to buy at least 9 million tons of grain annually and specifies that the purchases include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent. If more than 12 million tons are wanted in a year, the Soviets are required to seek <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approval. The Soviets were given approval to exceed the 12 million tons in the final year. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. So far, the Soviets have bought more than 8.8 million tons of subsidized wheat for delivery in the fifth year, as well as 4.1 million tons of non-subsidized corn; 818,400 tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal. Subsidies are provided under the department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP. Private exporters are given surplus commodities owned by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> so they can sell a foreign buyer wheat or other authorized commodity at competitive world prices. The subsidies, or bonuses, have run between less than $ 20 to more than $ 40 per ton, roughly 54 cents to $ 1.09 per bushel. <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the Soviets have more than 185,000 tons remaining in their current <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> authorization. An additional 1 million tons were announced on April 4, plus some left over from earlier authorizations.
