<HEAD>Critics Want Human Rights Attached to Creation of `Zone of Trust'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Czechoslovak human rights group has called on its government to release all political prisoners and allow free travel abroad before a government-proposed `` zone of trust'' is created in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` If trust is not to remain a mere propagandistic slogan, certain basic preconditions must be fulfilled for it to emerge,'' said the appeal from the Charter 77 group. A text was released Friday through the London-based <ORGANIZATION> Palach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> newsletter. The document was signed by three Charter 77 spokesmen and issued in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> on April 11. It welcomed a Czechoslovak government proposal to set up a `` zone of trust and good neighborly relations along the dividing lines of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries'' in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Czechoslovak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> made the proposal in February, but no details have been made public. <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> officials said the buffer zone, to include such countries as West and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, would cover cultural, military, ecological and human relations issues. The Charter 77 appeal calls on the Czechoslovak government to prove its `` trustworthiness and credibility by respecting the fundamental rights and liberties of its citizens while submitting itself to open and public scrutiny.'' A copy was sent to <PERSON> Jakes </PERSON> and to the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> follow-up Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, As reported by <PERSON> Palach </PERSON> <PERSON> Press </PERSON>, signatories <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Hajek </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stanislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Devaty </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bohumir </PERSON> <PERSON> Janat </PERSON> specifically demanded the immediate release of <PERSON> Jiri </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>, who is serving a six-year sentence for publishing information on conditions in Czechoslovak prisons. He was jailed in 1983. They also demanded that priest <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Javorsky </PERSON>, sentenced to eight months in jail last year for celebrating Mass without official permission, be set free. The appeal also demanded freedom to travel abroad, in particular to the couuntries included in the proposed trust zone; an end to discrimination against nonconformist citizens; and a halt to persecuting human rights groups. `` If the government does not take decisive steps in the spirit of the above-mentioned points, its peace proposal will remain a mere empty gesture,'' the signatories of the appeal said, according to <ORGANIZATION> Palach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
