<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cosmetic surgery is as common as palm trees in movieland, but one blemished star on the Walk of Fame took 28 years to fix. <PERSON> Mauritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Stiller </PERSON>, the late Swedish director whose main claim to fame was bringing <PERSON> Greta </PERSON> <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, suffered the indignity of having not just one name misspelled on the famed star-walk, but both. City officials corrected the error Thursday, replacing a star plaque reading <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Diller </PERSON> with one honoring <PERSON> Mauritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Stiller </PERSON>. In 1960, when the first 1,550 bronze plaques were implanted in the sidewalks of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s shopping and theater district to create the hallowed Walk of Fame, someone taking the name over the telephone misheard the caller, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Welsh </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` Well, we got 1,549 stars out of 1,550 correct,'' Welsh said. `` I just hope our Swedish friends will forgive us for taking so long to correct the error.'' The local Swedish consulate had asked Hollywood to correct the misspelling because King <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> XVI </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustav </PERSON> and <PERSON> Queen </PERSON> <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON>, who are touring the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, will be visiting <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> soon, said spokesman <PERSON> Claes </PERSON> <PERSON> Jernaeus </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stiller </PERSON> was lured to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> in 1925 by <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, and came only on condition that he could bring Miss <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON>. She went on to become a star, but <PERSON> Stiller </PERSON> contracted pleurisy and returned to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, where he died in 1928. He directed such films as `` Sir <PERSON> Arne </PERSON>'s Treasure'' and `` The Atonement of <PERSON> Gosta </PERSON> <PERSON> Berling </PERSON>,'' which starred Miss <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON>. Attending the ceremonies were Swedish notables <PERSON> Lasse </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallstrom </PERSON>, the Oscar-nominated director of `` My Life As A Dog,'' and actress <PERSON> Signe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasso </PERSON>. Miss <PERSON> Garbo </PERSON> had been invited to attend, but `` she's very private, as you know And she's over 80 now,'' said <PERSON> Ake </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandler </PERSON>, a local Swedish-born professor.
