<SECOND>AM-Sharpeville Six,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers Request Reopening Trial For Six Blacks On Death Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers on Friday filed an application seeking to reopen the trial of six blacks who were sentenced to hang in a case that drew worldwide protests. The court action came a day after six other blacks were hung at <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> Central Prison, raising to 50 the number of executions in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> this year. The application on behalf of the so-called <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> Six was filed in <ORGANIZATION> Pretoria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. It is not known how soon a decision on the request will be made. The five men and one women were convicted of complicity in the mob killing of a black town councilor during anti-apartheid riots that broke out in <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, in September 1984. The violence touched off two years of nationwide unrest. The six were scheduled to die on March 18, but a stay of execution was granted to allow time for defense lawyers to request the case be reopened. The stay was decreed because of evidence that a state witness committed perjury during the original trial. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> had previously rejected international appeals to grant clemency to the six, saying he did not want to interfere in the judicial process. The six were not accused of contributing physically to the death of <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> councilor <PERSON> Kuzwayo </PERSON> <PERSON> Dhlamini </PERSON>. They were convicted under the doctrine of `` common purpose,'' which held them responsible because they were part of the mob that killed the man. The government has argued that the Sharpville Six are being falsely portrayed abroad as innocent victims of an unjust law. Authorities say evidence in the trial showed that each played an active part in the killing, through such alleged actions as making firebombs to burn <PERSON> Dhlamini </PERSON>'s house or slapping a woman who pleaded for the councilor's life. The six men hung Thursday included two blacks in their 20s described by authorities as `` comrades,'' a term commonly used to describe anti-apartheid militants. They were convicted of killing two other black men by setting fire to oil-soaked tires placed around the victims' necks. One of the executed men was convicted of killing a mixed-race man, while the other three were hung for murdering elderly whites. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
