<HEAD>End of Season Ratings: Bad News and Confusion for Networks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> says it came in second in the television ratings for the season according to the ratings company <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION>, although <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> results used by all three networks have <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> finishing third for the first time ever. No matter whose figures are used, the end of season ratings released by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> Friday show that viewers are no longer enchanted by its new shows and are turning instead to VCRs, cable and independent stations, and perhaps even books, conversation or exercise. CBS apparently suffered most. Except for `` Beauty and the <LOCATION> Beast </LOCATION>,'' it could count no new shows as successes, even though `` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s Place,'' `` Wiseguy'' and `` Tour of Duty'' received critical praise. `` We are not, as some people would expect, going to fall on our swords in defeat,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> vice president for marketing, who briefed reporters on the end-of-season results. `` We are not defeatists.'' The networks' prime-time season does n't officially end until Sunday, but the last week's results are n't expected to change the picture. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> Entertainment President <PERSON> Brandon </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> is to have a session with reporters Monday, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, which will win its third season in a row, is holding an end-of-season briefing Tuesday. CBS held its briefing early perhaps because it is already conceding it will come in third for the first time in the network's history _ according to the <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the ratings service of record since the 1950s Last year, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> signed up with <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> competitor <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, a British company. Although AGB numbers are not bought by the other networks, nor are they used in the real business of television ratings _ negotiating advertising rates _ <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> uses <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION> to back its contention that <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>'s new people-meter audience measurement system is inaccurate. <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> estimates that the networks will lose a combined $ 50 million in advertising revenues because of the lower numbers produced by people meters. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> agree that <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>'s new system is not accurate enough, but they have n't been hurt as much as CBS. In fact, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> has prospered. <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> would n't say how much of the $ 50 million loss was CBS'. According to <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>, the network averages after 29 weeks of the 30-week season were: NBC 16.1, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> 13.7 and CBS 13.5. The rating is a percentage of an estimated 88.6 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> homes equipped with television. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said AGB figures gave <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> 16.2, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> 13.9 and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> 13.2. <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> conceded that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> has little hope of getting advertisers and the other networks to switch to AGB in lieu of <LOCATION> Nielsen </LOCATION>. Despite the ratings system squabble, a general erosion in network audiences is uncontested, <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> said, although the extent of it is unknown. According to <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON>, the three-network average rating dropped 9 percent from 1986-87 to 1987-88. The previous year there was a 3 percent drop. <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON> estimates that roughly half of the percentage drop is real and half is a function of the people meter, a more complex measurement device that requires particiants to actively punch in and punch out when they watch television. The old system was a hands-off attachment on the set. Historically, networks have lost audiences to increasing cable availability, but this season the numbers show all cable channels combined gaining only 1.2 percent in the ratings. The biggest drop in network audiences was in the realm of theatrical movies, indicating increased use of cable or videocassettes. However, audiences are also rejecting new network programming. The highest-rated new show of the season was <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` A Different World,'' which, with an average rating of 25.1, is the only new show to qualify as a bona fide hit. But it has never been tested away from its timeslot that follows the No. 1-rated `` The Cosby Show,'' of which it is a spinoff. Otherwise, new shows performed miserably. Of the 47 this season, only eight exceeded the a 14.4 rating, the average for all network prime-time programming.
