<FIRST>r w AM-BloodPressure     04-15 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blood Pressure,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Updates Guidelines for Treatment of High Blood Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal advisory panel issued updated guidelines on treating high blood pressure Friday, citing the potential value of new classes of drugs but emphasizing the need to prescribe the lowest effective dose of any medication. Intended primarily for physicians, the recommendations were described by the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> panel as `` a sort of Bible or gospel of treatment.'' <PERSON> Abram </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chobanian </PERSON>, incoming dean of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, added that the suggestions were based on an eight-month review of latest research to update the guidelines last issued four years ago. He noted that two new classes of drugs _ so-called calcium antagonists and enzyme inhibitors _ have been approved for treating high blood pressure since the last report. `` For many patients, they may cause fewer symptomatic and biochemical side effects than diuretics and beta blockers,'' he said, referring to the only high blood pressure drugs on the market in 1984. But <PERSON> Chobanian </PERSON> emphasized that the updated guidelines call for `` lower initial doses for most drugs than we did in 1984.'' `` The point here is that smaller doses mean fewer side effects,'' he said at a news conference. `` This a critical advantage because the side effects of traditional antihypertensive drugs have been a major stumbling block to keeping patients on their treatment.'' Among other things, the widely used diuretics can cause impotence and excessive loss of potassium in some patients. `` We recommend that some patients, especially those with mild hypertension, start with nondrug treatments,'' said <PERSON> Chobanian </PERSON>. `` By that I mean reducing weight, limiting sodium and alcohol, stopping smoking, exercising and perhaps using biofeedback and relaxation techniques.'' The report urges physicians to carefully monitor those patients who do need drug treatment with an eye to reducing the dosage or perhaps eliminating such medication. The updated guidelines also say people with high blood pressure should drink no more than the equivalent of two beers a day, down from three in the 1984 report, and emphasizes that lowering blood pressure alone is not a major reducer of heart attacks if the patient does not also control other risk factors _ especially smoking and high blood cholesterol levels.
</TEXT>
