<FIRST>r w AM-AlternativeFuels     04-15 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alternative Fuels,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Bill Encourages Alternative Fuels Such as Coal, Gas, Grain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Friday passed legislation designed to foster use of alternative motor fuels in order to reduce <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependency on foreign petroleum and tap vast <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supplies of coal, natural gas and grain. The bill passed on a voice vote over warnings by Republicans on the <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that it could lead to increased emissions of the `` greenhouse'' gases that some scientists say are overheating the Earth's atmosphere. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> action all but ensures that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will enact alternative fuels legislation in 1988. A similar proposal was passed overwhelmingly by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year. The bills' differences will have to be resolved by negotiators from both chambers Both proposals are geared toward encouraging the automobile industry to mass-produce vehicles that can operate on fuels such as methanol, ethanol and compressed natural gas. Methanol, which powers <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> 500-type race cars at 200 miles an hour, can be manufactured from coal or natural gas. Ethanol is made from grains like corn. The legislation has broad support from coal and agricultural state lawmakers. The proposals would break an impasse that now prevents any widespread switchover from gasoline to alternative fuels, according to Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., a principal sponsor along with Sen. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION> `` Automakers are unwilling to produce -LRB- alternative fuel -RRB- cars for which there is no current demand,'' `` Consumers are unwilling to purchase cars for which there is no readily available fuel supply, and service stations are unwilling to provide fuel for cars that are not on the road.'' <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON> said that besides lessening the growing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> need for imported oil, a conversion of just 10 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vehicle fleet to coal-based methanol would mean jobs for 20,000 miners in the depressed coal industry. The sponsors said automakers would be encouraged to mass-produce vehicles using alternative fuels because the legislation would make it easier to meet the federal requirement that their fleets have an average fuel economy of at least 26 miles per gallon. Under the bill's formula, a 25 mpg vehicle that uses a blend of 85 percent methanol and 15 percent gasoline would get a fuel economy rating of 165 mpg, according to <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>. A 25 mpg vehicle using a 50-50 blend would be rated at 40 mpg, he said. The higher credits for alternative fuels would begin with the vehicle 1993 model year. <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>'s argument that methanol and ethanol would cause fewer environmental and health problems than gasoline was disputed by <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, R-Vt., and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-R.I. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Stafford </LOCATION> said coal-derived methanol would double emissions of carbon dioxide, a major contributor to the greenhouse effect, and bring a tenfold increase in tailpipe emissions of formaldehyde, a cancer-causing chemical He urged the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to proceed cautiously because many scientists warn that the production of greenhouse gases is overloading the atmosphere, trapping heat around the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and threatening major climate changes. `` Once we commit to a program like this, it will be too late,'' said <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, who unsuccessfully tried to add amendments to require alternative vehicles to meet the same emissions standards as gasoline vehicles. <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON> succeeded in adding language putting the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on record as saying that coal-based methanol would boost carbon dioxide levels, contribute to global overheating and should not be used until emissions controls are developed to control carbon dioxide.
</TEXT>
