<HEAD>Piedmont Starts Repairs After NTSB Completes First Part of Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> airlines maintenance crews Friday began making temporary repairs to a crippled jetliner, replacing an engine that exploded in midair and patching holes that ripped through both sides of the cabin. The Fokker F-28 4000, a Dutch-made jet carrying 56 passengers and a crew of four, was forced to land at <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> on Thursday after it lost cabin pressure and plunged partway toward the ground as passengers screamed and fainted. After the workers replace the engine and cover the holes, the plane is to be flown Saturday to a <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> maintenance facility at <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, for further study and repair, said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Bubar </PERSON>, manager of Yeager Airport. The engine mounted on the right side of the fuselage exploded Thursday morning as the plane was at 31,000 feet en route from <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. It was a half-hour out of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, and about 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, when the explosion occurred. A turbine blade and other engine parts cut through the plane's right rear bathroom and a flight attendant work area No one was hit by the debris, but two flight attendants suffered bumps and bruises as the plane plunged. The explosion was the first significant trouble reported with the engines of a Fokker F-28, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> statistics show. <ORGANIZATION> Rolls-Royce </ORGANIZATION> manufactured the engine that exploded Thursday. <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> flies 25 <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28 4000s, which carry 72 people, and 20 <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28 1000s, which carry 62. They've used the <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> planes for about four years, but the model has been in use elsewhere for about 20 years. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> said it was too early to tell whether safety checks will be required for the F-28s in <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION>'s fleet. `` The damage that took place is very apparent,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who handled the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>'s initial investigation of the incident. `` What we have is engine failure ... and the side of the airplane was breached. `` There was only limited work we could to there -LRB- in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' he said from his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, office. `` Our work does n't really begin until we can get the engine and the plane elsewhere.'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said that despite the relatively safe history of the <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> model, the investigation would be needed to check whether the problem could be found in other <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> planes. `` Right now, were going to look at that particular aircraft and that model of aircraft,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` During the course of the investigation, that will all be looked at, but we ca n't make that determination now. `` We want to look at the problem it poses for the future. The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>, in general, is set up to investigate accidents and prevent similar occurrences.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Programs </ORGANIZATION> has only two injury accidents involving <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28s in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> since the early 1980s, one when there was a minor collision on an airport taxiway and the other when a person fell off the boarding stairs when a guardrail gave way, said spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> contended that with such a record, grounding the airline's other Fokkers would not be necessary. `` We'll take a judicious approach to what the next step will be,'' <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> said. The airline, based in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, owns 25 <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28 4000 planes and 20 of the F-28 1,000 series.
