<HEAD>No Accord in Afghanistan Day After Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet withdrawal agreement brought no accord to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Friday: President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> asked the guerrillas to join a coalition government and they demanded he be tried by a Moslem religious court. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> accused the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of trying to ruin the agreement by continuing to supply arms to the Moslem insurgents. `` <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is confirming its policy of neoglobalism, a course of export of counter-revolution,'' it said. The guerrillas were not invited to the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> negotiations and have said they will continue fighting. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, who uses only one name, also sent a message to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> thanking him for his efforts leading to the agreement signed Thursday, under which the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> will begin May 15 to withdraw the 115,000 soldiers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In a statement broadcast by by <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> radio, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> invited the guerrillas to accept his policy of national reconcilittion. `` We are prepared to cooperate with those who are still fighting this honorable policy,'' he said. `` We stress our willingness to meet the leaders of the opposition in order to reach a decision on peace, for the happiness of afflicted people ... for the future of the country's children. We are waiting for the -LRB- naming -RRB- of your candidates for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>.'' Elections for the <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> ended Thursday. The guerrillas, who have been fighting since a Communist coup in April 1978, were offered seats but dismissed the election as a farce. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said 1.5 million people voted, showing their `` confidence, needs and views.'' About 5 million Afghans _ one-third of the population _ have left the country since Soviet soldiers arrived in December 1979. `` Another step has been taken toward ending war and brother-killing ... deepening political dialogue, the expansion of democracy, the establishment of a coalition government with the participation of all forces which represent the Afghan society,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> declared. <PERSON> Gulbaddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, chairman of the seven-party guerrilla alliance based in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, a border city in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and all members of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> must be tried in absentia by religious courts. He said Soviet soldiers held by the guerrillas would be exchanged for Afghan army soldiers, and `` all those POWs will be kept until the <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> regime is toppled and is replaced by an Islamic government so all those criminals who flee with the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> could be brought back ... for trial'' in exchange for the prisoners. `` In my view, all members of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> ... including <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> the puppet must be tried in absentia ... so that after the withdrawal of the Russian forces such criminals be dealt with in accordance with Islamic laws, and those who have been misled and played off against their nation by these criminals be pardoned,'' <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> said. The insurgents have said they will not share power with Communists in a future government, but had not called for trials. They have predicted that <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> would follow the Soviet soldiers to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Guerrilla leaders have not said how many Soviet prisoners they have, but last month <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hezb-i-Islami </ORGANIZATION> party said an agreement had been reached to exchange a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> soldier for 25 guerrilla prisoners. The exchange has not occurred.
