<HEAD>Speakes Liked To Boast He Never Lied to Press</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Speakes Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, the former <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> weekly newspaper editor who rose to be a presidential spokesman and Wall Street executive, often boasted that he never lied to the press during his years at the White House. But in his new book, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> admitted that he fabricated quotes and attributed them to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. He resigned Friday as vice president for communications of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, saying it was `` the best course of action'' in the wake of that admission. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>' successor, <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, would say only, `` I'm sorry for him, personally.'' Earlier, he had called <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>' practice an outrage, said it reflected on the integrity of the White House press office. He promised that he would never do anything similar. <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON>, 48, became the chief <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, was wounded during an assassination attempt on the president on March 30, 1981. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> has continued to hold the title of press secretary although he has been unable to return to his duties. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, who served two years as a deputy to <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> and then became press secretary to Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has been the chief <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman since <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> left the post 14 months ago. <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> grew up in <LOCATION> Merigold </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, which he describes in his book, `` Speaking Out,'' as `` <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the heartland, <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' The words are similar to those <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has often used in speaking of his own home town, <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, Ill. In fact, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> said that when he told <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> of his decision to leave the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and accept the offer from <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>, he told him, `` As a kid growing up in a town in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> of 700, I never expected to meet a president, much less work with one.'' He said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> replied, `` Well, what do you think of a kid growing up in a small town in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> attended the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississipi </ORGANIZATION> for four years, but did not receive a degree because he had not completed his second year of French. While in summer school trying to complete the work, he accepted an offer to be editor of the <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, Eagle, a weekly with a circulation of about 4,000. For a young married man whose wife was expecting their first child, the salary of $ 85 a week was too good in 1961 to turn down. Later he held editorial posts at other <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> weeklies and became co-owner of four such newspapers. In 1968, he came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> as press secretary to <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>'s Democratic Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastland </PERSON>. He was an honorary pallbearer at <LOCATION> Eastland </LOCATION>'s funeral in 1986 and said in his book, `` Not a day goes by even now that I do n't remember him and tell another <LOCATION> Eastland </LOCATION> story.'' <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> first entered the White House in 1974 as an assistant to President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziegler </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> resigned a few months later and <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> stayed on to serve as an assistant in President <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>'s press office. In the 1976 election, he was press secretary to <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. After <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> lost to <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> went to work for the public relations firm of <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Knowlton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Saying that he found the public relations business `` neither as interesting nor as much fun as I had expected it to be,'' he went to work for the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> campaign in 1980 and then returned to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> as a deputy press secretary. After he took over the chief spokesman's job, his relations with the White House press corps were often contentious, with <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> accusing reporters of being out to get the president, and the reporters accusing <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> of not being candid. <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> often said his credibility was his most precious possession and he would not risk losing it by lying to the press. In his book, however, he says that at <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1985 summit meeting with <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> he had an aide `` draft some quotes for the president,'' polished them and then told reporters that they were what the president said to the Soviet leader. `` In restrospect, it was clearly wrong to take such liberties,'' he said in his book. But, he added, `` I had been able to spruce up the president's image by taking a bit of liberty with my P.R. man's license.
