suppliers. Picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: The FBI</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators said Friday they have broken up a Chinese heroin-trafficking ring, arresting 11 people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and nine in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> while seizing 137 pounds of heroin worth over $ 100 million. Five of those arrested in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> were charged with conspiring to supply 1,000 M-16 military rifles to undercover federal agents and to provide false documents so the rifles could be shipped to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. The breakup of the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> ring was the culmination of a two-year investigation called <ORGANIZATION> Operation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bamboo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dragon </ORGANIZATION> that was launched when federal agents learned that a restaurant owner in the <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was buying stolen firearms and distributing cocaine. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firearms </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> conducted the investigation and law enforcement officials announced the arrests at a news conference in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Drug-importing Asian criminal gangs `` are moving in to fill the void'' left by the successful prosecution of Sicilian Mafia members in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON> said in a statement. `` This gang was capable of putting enormous firepower into the hands of terrorists and drug smugglers,'' Customs commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said in a statement. Federal officials said the ring had supplied 600 handguns, mostly to Chinese gangs. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ATF </ORGANIZATION> inserted undercover operatives into the ring, including a Chinese-speaking agent who portrayed himself as a drug dealer. The Cantonese-speaking federal agent, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Yau </PERSON>, met with gang members in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> to negotiate the purchase of heroin from <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The heroin came from <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and was transported to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>. It also was distributed to <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> members of the ring were selling hundreds of stolen or illegally obtained hand - and machine guns and rifles on the streets of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, usually to Chinese gangs Many of the firearms were obtained with fraudulent identification documents from gun shops in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the officials said. The Chinese gangs were buying AR-15 semi-automatic rifles _ the civilian version of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s M-16 rifle _ and converting them into fully automatic M-16s. Customs and <ORGANIZATION> ATF </ORGANIZATION> undercover agents bought 10 weapons from the five people charged in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and ordered 1,000 more M-16s that were to be delivered to <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Such shipments would have violated the Arms Export Control Act, which sets up federal licensing procedures for the sale of weapons to foreign countries.
