<HEAD>Judge Warns Against Unauthorized Disclosure of Classified
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the Iran-Contra trial warned Friday against the unauthorized disclosure of some 300,000 classified documents expected to be turned over to the defense by prosecutor <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON>. In an order detailing procedures for handling the documents by the defense, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> warned that `` unauthorized disclosure of classified information may constitute violations of <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> criminal laws.'' `` Persons subject to this order are advised that direct or indirect unauthorized disclosure, retention or negligent handling of classified documents or information could cause serious damage, and in some cases exceptionally grave damage, to the national security of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or may be used to the advantage of a foreign nation against the interests of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' the judge said. The nine-page order requires that the defendants, their lawyers and any witnesses must obtain approval of the court-designated security officer before gaining access to classified documents. Access will be granted on a `` need-to-know'' basis and the defendants, their lawyers and witnesses must sign an agreement not to make unauthorized disclosures of the information contained in the documents, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. `` Any violation of the terms of this order shall be immediately brought to the attention of the court and may result in a charge of contempt of court and possible reference for criminal prosecution,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. Marine Lt. Col. <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON> and former national security adviser <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> are accused of conspiring with arms dealers <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON> and retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> to divert profits illegally from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels. At a hearing Tuesday, independent counsel <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said that as many as 300,000 classified documents are being reviewed by an interagency government task force. <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> said he expected that 50,000 documents relevant to the case will be ready for defense review by month's end. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> ordered that the defense is entitled to review the rest of the material to determine if it is relevant to their case when the matter goes to trial. The order requires that lawyers can only work with the documents or discuss them with each other or witnesses in the special security facility that is being constructed by the court security officer. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> prescribed a type of word processing equipment, which is apparently resistant to electronic eavesdropping, to be used by the defense for preparing court pleadings based on the materials. All pleadings dealing with classified information must be prepared in the facility and filed under seal with the court security officer, who will delete classified references before the briefs are placed in the public file, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> ordered. Before any classified document is introduced into evidence at the trial, it must be declassified by the government agencies that produced it. If the government refuses to declassify a document, the Classified Information Procedures Act empowers the court to substitute a statement of facts that the material would prove. The court could also agreed to delete certain classified markings that reveal intelligence methods but were not pertinent to the case. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> gave the defense until April 29 to file a challenge to the application fo the classified information statute to the case. The defense complained that the law requires procedures that inhibit their ability to prepare their case.
