Women's Studies 200 a stimulating, exciting course and it did not engage in male-bashing or racism,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Daugherty </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Seward </PERSON>, another of <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON>'s fellow students, said: `` When I asked a question about where a guest lecturer got her information on Indians in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, I was told that I was a racist. I was told that all white people are racists and those who say they are n't are practicing denial.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Zehnder </PERSON>, another fellow student, said he did not find <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON> either disruptive or disrespectful in class. `` The problem arose because he was perceived as a threat to unusual teaching techniques. `` The instructors presented erroneous or misleading statistics and personal opinions as fact,'' <PERSON> Zehnder </PERSON> asserted. He also said he was told by an instructor that he would be flunked if he ever used the words lady or girl in written work.
