<DATELINE>MARSHFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury recommended Friday that a southwestern <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> dairy farmer be put to death for killing his wife and two nephews, including a teen-ager whom he had originally blamed for the killings. The jury which convicted <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> of Elkland of three counts of first-degree murder had the alternative of recommending life in prison. If a judge accepts the jury's recommendation, <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> would become the 57th person on death row at the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penitentiary </LOCATION>, where there has not been an execution since 1965. The <LOCATION> Webster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> jury Thursday found Schnick guilty in the deaths of his wife, <PERSON> Julie </PERSON>, and two nephews, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, 14, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, 2. On Friday, they recommended the death penalty on all three counts. <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> also is accused but was not tried in the deaths of his brother-in-law, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>; <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Jeannette </PERSON>; and the Buckners' two other sons, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, 8, and <PERSON> Timmy </PERSON>, 6. <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> were brother and sister. All the victims died in an early morning shooting spree Sept. 25 at the Buckner and Schnick families' dairy farms in nearby <LOCATION> Elkland </LOCATION>. The Schnicks' two young children were not injured. Schnick originally blamed the slayings on his nephew <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, and claimed he killed the boy in self-defense. The allegation shocked members of the community who knew the teen-ager, who was described as quiet and hard-working. Within days, however, <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> himself was charged in connection with the seven deaths. Police said he confessed during questioning, but he claimed during the trial that the confession was not freely given. <LOCATION> Webster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheever </PERSON> said the crimes were aggravated by the fact that <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> may have killed his wife in order to collect life insurance. The number of victims, and the youth of many of them, also prompted <PERSON> Cheever </PERSON> to seek the death penalty. `` It's difficult to imagine anything more defenseless and more helpless in this world than a 2-year-old asleep in his bed,'' <PERSON> Cheever </PERSON> said in his closing arguments. `` Anyone who would kill an infant in those circumstances deserves the most severe punishment possible under the law.'' <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON>'s attorney pleaded for her client's life, on behalf, she said, of his two surviving children. `` No one is minimizing the terribleness or the horror of what has occurred ...,'' <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> said. `` Healing comes with time and love and compassion. It's not going to come with vengence.'' Ms. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> had called <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON>'s friends and family members to attest that he had been a helpful neighbor and caring father. She said their testimony proved that `` there is the possibility of redemption.'' <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, chief of psychology at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, testified that after evaluating <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> and interviewing many of his friends, he concluded that <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON> strove all his life to please others and was frustrated by his inability to satisfy those closest to him when he lost control Sept. 25. `` The acting out that he did ... is very unlikely ever to be repeated,'' <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> said. The defense contended during the trial that <PERSON> Schick </PERSON>'s confession was gained under pressure, and that he had been under the influence of medication on the day of the shootings. <PERSON> Schnick </PERSON>'s long-time physician, Dr. <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON>, said he examined Schnick Oct. 2, three days before his confession, and prescribed a painkiller. `` It dulls the awareness,'' Presley said. `` It tends tp make a patient sleepy and impair his intellectual function.'' But county coroner Dr. <PERSON> J.D </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Blinn </ORGANIZATION>, called as a rebuttal witness, said he prescribed the same painkiller often during his 41 years as a general practitioner, and rarely noted that his patients reacted with drowsiness.
