<HEAD>Yeutter Says U.S. Trade Bill Will be Vetoed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will veto the omnibus trade bill before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> because <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders insist on plant closure safeguards, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said Friday. He said the dispute could delay and possibly jeopardize congressional approval of the historic U.S.-Canada Fee Trade Agreement. `` The labor unions got their way,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Vancouver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in a luncheon speech prior to a weekend meeting with the trade ministers of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. He credited <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with the `` almost unprecedented'' deletion of dozens of protectionist portions of the trade bill, to the point where <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> might be able to sign it. But he said the Democratic leadership informed the administration on Thursday that they would not discard a section requiring owners to give substantive notice before any plant closures. `` That legislation is objected to vigorously by the American business community and the administration,'' <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said. `` Therefore, the trade bill is going to be vetoed. We believe we can sustain the veto, which means we're back to ground zero after two or three years' work on a trade bill. `` That could have implications for the Free Trade Agreement.'' He said at the very least, the trade bill battle will delay consideration of the trade accord for about 30 days, and `` bruised feelings'' in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could erode support for it. The trade deal was negotiated with Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSO