ourt said prosecutors `` lost sight of the fact that coronary artery bypass surgery is an inherently risky business.'' Prosecutors had argued that <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> used questionable surgical techniques, but they never produced evidence or testimony to demonstrate his work constituted criminal conduct, the appeals court said. `` We shall set aside all findings of guilty based on this factual insufficiency of the evidence,'' the court said. Prosecutors described <PERSON> Billig </PERSON> as an egocentric man who hid the fact that he was nearly blind in one eye and continued performing complex operations despite warnings that he was killing patients. The appeals court said it was troubled by <PERSON> Billig </PERSON>'s conviction because his court-martial involved criminal charges as opposed to civil claims for damages based on negligence. `` We are not convinced beyond a reasonable doubt that the deaths that formed the basis of the appellant's conviction were due to any negligence, simple or otherwise, on his part,'' the appeals court said.
