ation threw in free sandwiches. More than 7,000 tax returns were processed between 5 p.m. and 7 p.m., according to <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartford </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the post office. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazer </PERSON>, communications manager for the postal service in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said no extra workers were called in Friday though some employees would work overtime. `` Believe it or not, with automation, we can handle this additional volume of mail with no problems,'' <PERSON> Mazer </PERSON> said. `` It is really not that difficult for us. We do this every year as a public service. ... We live in a world of people who do things at the last minute.'' In <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Westin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peachtree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> concocted an 800-pound cake decorated like an 11-foot-long Form 1040 and invited people to `` take a bite'' out of the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. Deadline Day publicity stunts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> included free samples of antacid which were distributed outside the main post office, and an `` IRS Stress Relief Clinic'' opened by a toy company, which invited taxpayers to come in and yell at a dummy. In <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, 15 protesters from <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> displayed a missile made of income tax forms outside a federal office building. They also erected a structure of cans of food they said they would donate to the poor in lieu of paying taxes for military purposes. State tax officials in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> reported a pleasant surprise in their mail Friday _ cashiers' checks totaling $ 82,000 from a penitent but anonymous tax evader. `` Please forgive our mistakes and shortcomings,'' said a short not