be 15. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> planes grounded by safety violations grew to at least 15 Friday as a federal crackdown found problems including a fuel leak, a missing maintenance log and a cracked wing flap, the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union said. The airline and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> refused to confirm the number, saying they will detail no violations until the inspection is complete. As of Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> had put the number of planes grounded at six. `` They did n't want to see a running box score,'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said of his agency's policy change after two days. The unprecedented inspection of all Eastern planes began after the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> slapped the company with a $ 823,000 fine for safety violations. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said officials have been unsatisfied with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s performance since its 1986 takeover by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which also will undergo a 30-day inspection of its operating practices. Eight planes were found to have safety violations Friday according to reports from union members around the country, said a union spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of company retaliation. The latest groundings were in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, the union spokesman said. Planes grounded by safety violations can be returned to service once they are repaired. In addition, union officials said a 757 in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> was grounded on Wednesday and its passengers ordered off minutes before the flight was to take off for <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> because the airline had failed to repair fire-detection wiring in an engine a week and two warnings after it was reported by an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> inspector. Four planes were briefly sidelined Friday in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> for violations ranging from a seat on a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 that reclined to block an emergency exit to a wheel well leak on a DC-9, the union said. In <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> an A-300 <ORGANIZATION> AirBus </ORGANIZATION> was sidelined Friday with a wing flap dent and a fuel leak in an engine. The plane was fixed later in the day, the union said. A <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> flight to <LOCATION> Miamia </LOCATION> was held for repairs Friday morning, the union said. The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 was found to have a cracked wing flap. Late Thursday, DC-9 bound for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, was taken out of service after <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors found it lacked a flight maintenance log and was missing landing bumper pads. In <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>, the battery relay switch on a DC-9 was found not to be working. The switch turns on the plane's electrical equipment, the union spokesman said. A DC-9 taken out of service at <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> when inspectors discovered a duct in the tail section was overheating, the union spokesman said. The eight Friday groundings were in addition to six the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> reported on Thursday and the one reported to have taken place Wednesday. <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said about 20 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s 267-plane fleet had been looked over by <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors in 23 cities when the agency stopped reporting its findings Friday morning. Inspections were expected to continue as flights arrived in those cities during the 30-day review that began Wednesday. Eastern spokewoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceremsak </PERSON> said news of the sidelined planes was being overblown. Some mechanical problems occur daily, she said.
