<HEAD>LaserPhotos staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Colors,'' the much criticized movie about <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' out-of-control street gangs, opened nationwide Friday at 425 theaters amid protests and tight security following predictions of audience violence. It also drew mixed reviews. About 15 theaters nationwide dropped plans to show the film, according to reports, and at some <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> theaters, police frisked young people as they entered. Afternoon showings went off without incident at the busy <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> theater. `` It has just been business as usual,'' said manager <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnell </PERSON>. The theater added security guards for the film's opening, but that was more in anticipation of the crowds than out of fear of violence, <PERSON> Schnell </PERSON> said. The line for an afternoon show snaked a block down <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, police said they planned to assign at least a dozen officers to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> Warner Theater. <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> is just a few miles from <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION>, home area of several gangs. `` There could be some fights inside the theater,'' said <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> police Lt. <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>. `` We're taking this seriously. We'll have officers inside the theater and officers outside.'' `` There will be gang members there,'' <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> said. `` Definitely. No doubt about it.'' Between Jan. 1 and April 4, there were 89 gang-related deaths in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Last year, there were 387 gang-related deaths in the area. The management of the Laemmle Grand theater near the Sheraton Grand Hotel, just a short distance from gang turf, decided not to show the film after staffers pleaded for their safety. A <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> spokesman who asked not to be identified told the <LOCATION> Pomona </LOCATION> Progress-Bulletin a decision was made several weeks ago to pull the movie from some UA theaters, including one in <LOCATION> Montclair </LOCATION>, where police in the past two years have staged two major raids against drugs and gangs. Two real <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> gangs, the Crips and Bloods, and their respective colors of blue and red, are depicted in the movie that stars <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON> as two officers assigned to fight the gangs. The Orion movie was directed by <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON>, who spent the week defending the film against critics such as the Hollywood-Beverly Hills Chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Councilman <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, who suggested it should not be shown anywhere. `` I'm showing you a real problem that exists,'' <PERSON> Hopper </PERSON> said Friday on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show. `` When you show a real problem that exists, you do n't go to the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and try to get the movie dismissed.'' Hopper's home in the <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> area was picketed during the week by the <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angels </ORGANIZATION>, the New York-based civilian crime-fighting organization. The Guardian <PERSON> Angels </PERSON> also handed out pamphlets Friday to theater-goers at the UA Cor