<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A psychologist was indicted Friday on charges of submitting false data to win a $ 200,000 federal research grant. A federal prosecutor said the charges were the first of their kind in the nation. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON>, 35, was charged in connection with a grant received in 1982 from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION> while he was a faculty member at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. The money already has been repaid by the university, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Breckinridge </PERSON> <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said in a statement. <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON>, now director of psychological services and behavorial treatment at the Polk Center in <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, submitted a 1981 grant request for a study titled `` Stimulant Drug Use with Mentally Retarded Children'' while at the university from 1982 to 1984, the statement said. The indictment said <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON>'s applications cited the results of seven studies of hyperactive mentally retarded children. <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON> `` knew the ... studies had not been completed at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> as described,'' and that `` the studies that were ongoing were not obtaining the results as described,'' the indictment said. <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said that the indictment is believed to be first time criminal charges have been brought against an individual in connection with falsified research. `` We have ... addressed a problem that I suspect is more widespread than we think: fraudulent research data in the medical field,'' <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said. `` Let this investigation send a clear message to doctors and researchers who play fast and loose with their research that they will have to deal with the criminal justice system in addition to their peer review panels.'' In addition to two counts of making false statements, <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON> was charged with obstructing a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> investigation by falsely testifying at a 1985 hearing that he had submitted a `` corrected version'' of his grant request. `` We vehemently deny the allegations and think they're patently untrue,'' <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON> said by telephone from his <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> home Friday night. If convicted, <PERSON> Breuning </PERSON>, who holds a doctorate in psychology from the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, could receive up to 10 years in prison and $ 20,000 in fines on the false statement counts, and five years and $ 250,000 in fines on the obstruction count, officials said. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Huber </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>, was not available for comment, a university employee said Friday night.
