<HEAD>`Last Emperor' Sparks Legal Controversy in Chinese Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Debate over whether the Oscar-winning film, `` The Last Emperor,'' was filmed illegally in the Imperial Palace was a hot topic in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature this week. Delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> called on Vice Minister of Culture <PERSON> Ying </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruocheng </PERSON> to give his account of the affair, according to a report earlier this week in the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Evening News -LRB- <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Wanbao -RRB-. Ying, an accomplshed actor, was closely involved with the film directed by <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ying </PERSON> played the supporting role of warden in the war criminals prison where the emperor is sent for `` remolding and education.'' The film crew used Imperial Palace buildings to shoot interior scenes, but filming is forbidden in the palace under <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s historical preservation law The law, which took effect in April 1985, is aimed at protecting wooden structures from irreparable fire damage. During the 1 -LCB- - hour question-and-answer session held Monday, <PERSON> Ying </PERSON> told delegates that the contract with the Italian film company was signed in March 1984, before the preservation law was issued, the daily said In addition, he cited the value of propagating <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s cultural heritage through film and assurances that the film company would use fire prevention measures, the paper said. The director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimin </PERSON>, also defended the filming in the palace. `` In light of the contract being signed first and, moreover, a letter from officials of the Italian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> requesting help and cooperation, we decided to make this a special case.'' Some congressional delegates complained that the treatment of the foreign film makers was an affront to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s attempts to develop a modern legal system and establish `` rule by law.'' `` In the final analysis, did the contract obey the law or overturn it?'' <LOCATION> Hebei </LOCATION> province delegate <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhuang </PERSON> was quoted as asking. The debate was triggered when producers of an all-Chinese film crew making a television series, also entitled `` The Last Emperor,'' wrote a letter to a government advisory body in March complaining that they had been denied access to palace buildings. `` Is law greater in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, or is power? Do foreigners have to obey our laws or not?'' the letter asked. The letter appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consultative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> to `` criticize and halt unhealthy tendencies and to reaffirm the integrity of Chinese lawmaking.'' According to the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Evening News report, <PERSON> Ying </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruocheng </PERSON> and his colleagues promised that film or television crews would not be given special privileges again. The delegates ended their annual session on Wednesday. The Chinese media has reported with little comment the awarding of nine Academy Awards, including best picture, to `` The Last Emperor.'' The film has not reached Chinese theaters.
