<HEAD>A Belter Gives Her All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A belter, says singer <PERSON> Nell </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, is one who gives his or her all. `` You're afraid you might hyperventilate or crack, but you do it for the excitement of it,'' the Tony award-winning performer said. `` Head singers have to hold everything tight to get the note. I like belters, people who have that noncontrol but control.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> is also an Emmy winner who spent six seasons delighting TV audiences on the sitcom `` Gim me a Break.'' She was interviewed while in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for a nine-day engagement at the Village Gate. `` I have a Las Vegas show,'' she said. `` One critic said on a scale of one to 10 we were 11. I'm not doing that show.'' The dinner show in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, she said, is easy. `` They like anything as long as it's recognizable. You get a chance to really wail a song, do something with a great arrangement. The late show, you have a lot of drunks. You sing whatever they want to hear. Torch songs seem to go over.'' She's choosing from among 60 songs in her <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> show, which opened April 15. `` I wanted to sing <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> this time and some country songs and I'm learning ` One of Us Was Wrong' from 1899 and some <PERSON> Sophie </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> songs. If you were to put this show on canvas, it would be very abstract.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> won a Tony for best featured actress in a musical for her performance in `` Ai n't Misbehavin','' the revue of Fats <PERSON> Waller </PERSON> songs which opened on Broadway in 1978, and she will be in the revival this August. She sings <PERSON> Waller </PERSON>'s `` Keepin' Out of Mischief Now'' in her show. She left `` Ai n't Misbehavin''' after nine months to have her tonsils out, sang <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON> at the King Cole Room of the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION>, was in `` Black Broadway'' at <ORGANIZATION> Town </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> and then returned to `` Ai n't Misbehavin''' in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to fulfill her contract. `` They've always cast the part to look like me,'' she said. `` People will say they saw me in St. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON>.'' In those days, and until about four years ago, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said she did not appreciate her talent. `` I was hanging out with the wrong crowd, participating in things I would n't choose to do now,'' she said. `` Now when I'm on stage I know why they're applauding. I know what I just said. I remember what I did last night. `` I'm not saying I was a loose woman. I did have my episode with drugs. `` I was able to have a good career while I was doing terrible things to myself. I do n't see why I did not die. I think it must have been a death wish for me to even be involved in the things I was doing. Thank God I did n't die. Now I do n't want to. It's a different world for me now.'' Growing up in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> listened to her mother's recordings of Dinah <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and B.B King, and her brother's <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Presley </PERSON> records She liked <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, the Andrews Sisters, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Mathis </PERSON>, and mentions <PERSON> Cleo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laine </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Barbra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Streisand </LOCATION> as singers she admires. `` If <PERSON> Liza </PERSON> <PERSON> Minnelli </PERSON> wants to sing with me, I wo n't turn her down _ I'll give the poor kid a break,'' she said. `` I would love to sing with <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cocker </PERSON>. His soul is so bare.'' However, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> would like to have been an opera singer. `` When I was growing up, it was not something you aspired to. I was a weirdo to want to be in show business. Most kids wanted to be teachers or nurses.'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has a daughter from a previous union and has been married for six years. `` I'm not going to tell you anything about him,'' she said. `` He is a very private person, a very nice man. His family does not understand publicity. They do n't like it.'' She collects crystal and antique silver picture frames and is an avid reader, favoring biographies and history. She hopes to work with the producers of `` Gim me a Break'' again and wants to get back on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
