<NOTE>For Release Monday April 18</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lagging Utilities Worry Market Analysts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Many analysts who are still skittish about the investment outlook these days point to the uninspired behavior lately of utility stocks. Last week, while the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials briefly touched a new high since the October crash, <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION>'s average of 15 utilities lagged behind. When it dipped below 170 late last week, the utility average stood more than 10 percent below where it was on Jan. 29. The performance of utility stocks as a group is `` a good gauge of the interest-rate environment,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Sorrentino </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, in the firm's weekly advisory publication The Outlook. It is also, he added, `` often a leading indicator of stock prices in general.'' Utility stocks tend to respond quickly to changing expectations about the interest-rate outlook for a couple of well-known reasons. For one thing, since utilities are heavy borrowers to finance their capital needs, interest rates are an important element of their costs of doing business. Besides that, most investors in utility stocks are very yield-conscious, and thus tend to push the stocks' prices up and down in close alignment with fluctuations in the bond market. In the great bull market, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> utility average was the first of the widely recognized indicators to peak out, at 227.83 on Jan. 22, 1987. Any investors who used that as a `` sell signal'' missed out on the dramatic gains in industrial stock prices that continued through August of last year. But they also would have been safely out of the way when interest rates surged upward last spring, and when stock prices crashed in the fall. The recent weakness in utilities, <PERSON> Sorrentino </PERSON> says, `` is reason for concern, as it suggests that investors believe interest rates are headed higher.'' Of course, interest-rate expectations can change, sometimes very quickly. The <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> maintains that `` utility stocks generally appear to be oversold. We think they could do better in the months ahead.'' Even if utilities do not come on strong, argues <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, they are not an infallible guide to what the rest of the market might do. Utilities fell in 1977, he points out, and then industrial stocks rose for the next three years. `` The poor performance of the utility averages signals bad problems for the overall stock market to many investors, especially since the divergence developed prior to the crash of last year,'' he said. `` They're waiting for another shoe to fall. I think it's a mistake to look for a matching shoe. `` To mix metaphors a little, I would point out that the same lightning rarely strikes the stock market twice in a row.'' In <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s view, the market's early-1988 rally drew its force not from value considerations based on such things as interest rates, but rather from strong corporate earnings. `` Utilities wo n't work, but not because another crisis is in the making,'' he said. `` They wo n't work because this is n't a valuation-driven market anymore. `` The bottom in interest rates is very well established now. As a result, the industrial averages, the utility averages and interest rates are no longer going to move together. `` This is a more advanced stage of the stock market cycle. And I do n't know of any reliable tool to predict its duration.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday Editions, April 18</NOTE>
