<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHN: more accountable.</HEAD>
<HEAD>HEALTH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> promises a national health care program covering all Americans `` no matter what their income.'' It would cover nursing home costs and be funded `` by earmarked health taxes and general revenues.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has promised to make universal health insurance a basic right, but proposes to do it without `` creating a big new bureaucratic program'' or spending `` a dime'' by requiring most employers to offer health insurance as a fringe benefit. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has just become the first state to move in that direction, and similar legislation is already pending in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> plan, which exempts firms with five or fewer employees, will cost that state $ 550 million or more through 1992. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has been instrumental in legislation creating an organ transplant network and tougher regulation of companies that make infant formula. He says, `` We must provide compassionate, affordable health care so that hospital costs are not driven to unbearable levels by the need to care for individuals who can not pay.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WELFARE, JOBS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> promises an overhaul of welfare programs along the lines of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' successful effort to place welfare recipients in jobs. Both <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> support raising the $ 3.35-an-hour minimum wage and to require future raises to keep pace with inflation. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also has called for a national minimum welfare benefit, with two-parent families eligible. States are now free to set their own Aid to Families with Dependent Children benefits, and to bar payments to intact families. All three Democrats have vowed to step up federal efforts to stop drugs. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> says he would boost the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> budget on drug enforcement, prevention and treatment from $ 3.9 billion to $ 6.7 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
