<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Israel _ The Changing Numbers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Population of West Bank and Gaza section to 850,000
in West Bank and 650,000 in Gaza, sted 836,000 and 545,000.
CORRECTS Immigration section to 1987, sted 1988. CORRECTS economy
section to 1987, sted 1988. CORRECTS military section to 1987, sted
1988.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some comparative facts about <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, when the country was founded and now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> ISRAEL </LOCATION>'S POPULATION <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s population in 1948, according to government statistics, was 872,700, including 716,700 Jews, and in 1949 was 1,173,900, including 1,013,900 Jews. The population in 1988 is 4,331,300, of whom 3,561,400 are Jews.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 POPULATION OF WEST BANK AND GAZA There were 585,900 in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured it from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in 1967, and the population is 850,000 in 1988. In <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, which belonged to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, the population was 380,800 in 1967 and is 650,000 in 1988.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 IMMIGRATION The number of immigrants to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was 170,200 in 1950, but by 1987 had declined to 9,500.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 ECONOMY <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s gross national product was $ 1.28 billion in 1950 and $ 31.37 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 AREA Including East Jerusalem and the <LOCATION> Golan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, which have been annexed, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s area is 13,330 square miles. There are 2,126 square miles in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and 140 in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 MILITARY Defense expenditures have increased from $ 10.25 million in 1948 to $ 4.3 billion in 1987. The military has grown in size from 34,000 personnel to 170,000 with 370,000 reservists.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 LEADERS <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s prime ministers have been <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Gurion </PERSON> 1948-54, <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharett </PERSON> 1954-55, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Gurion </PERSON> 1955-63, <PERSON> Levi </PERSON> <PERSON> Eshkol </PERSON> 1963-69, <PERSON> Golda </PERSON> <PERSON> Meir </PERSON> 1969-74, <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> 1974-77, <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON> 1977-83, <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> 1983-84, <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> 1984-1986, and <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> since 1986. Those who have served as president are <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizman </PERSON> 1948-52, <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Zvi </PERSON> 1952-63, <PERSON> Zalman </PERSON> <PERSON> Shazar </PERSON> 1963-73, <PERSON> Ephraim </PERSON> <PERSON> Katzir </PERSON> 1973-78, <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> 1978-83, and <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> since 1983.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
