<HEAD>Magnum Finale Promises No Reunions</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In what was billed as the series ender, `` Magnum, P.I.'' concluded last season with our hero getting gunned down and walking off into an ethereal landscape that looked suspiciously like heaven. But star <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> agreed to do 13 more episodes, and <PERSON> Magnum </PERSON>'s walk through the clouds was explained as an out-of-body experience On Sunday, `` Magnum'' ends its eight-year run on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> with a special two-hour episode. This time, there will be no catch, no reincarnation, no next season. `` After this episode, the audience would have a very hard time figuring out how we could ever do a reunion show,'' said <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> on a break in filming. `` There's a finality to this show. We wanted to do something that would threaten the franchise.'' <PERSON> Chas </PERSON>. <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, the show's co-executive producer, would n't give away the ending, but did say the finale will answer some questions `` It will touch on the issue of whether <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> is really <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Masters </PERSON>. It will deal with every one of the characters in at least looking at what their lives will be like after ` Magnum,''' he said. <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnum </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> intelligence officer turned private eye, perpetually on the brink of poverty but living in high style, thanks to the largesse of never-seen wealthy mystery writer <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Masters </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hillerman </PERSON> plays <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON>, the British major domo who runs Masters' estate and antagonizes Magnum, even as he comes to his aid. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Manetti </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosley </PERSON> are Magnum's <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> buddies, <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> and T.C Set against the exotic backdrop of the islands, `` Magnum, P.I.'' plots ran from silly to deadly serious. The show made <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> an international star. In its early years, the CBS series consistently landed in the top 10 of the Nielsen ratings. But in 1984, it was scheduled against <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` The Cosby Show'' and its ratings sagged. After some juggling by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, `` Magnum'' moved to Wednesday night and regained much of its audience. `` It's important to me that we go out while people still want us,'' <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> said. `` This show is too special to me to let it die a natural death. No matter what the rest of my films did, or even the success of ` Three Men and a Baby,' it all came to me by way of this show, and I've always tried to take care of ` Magnum.''' `` Three Men and a Baby'' marked <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON>'s first major screen success after several starring roles. <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON>'s reputation as an actor was initially overshadowed by his image as a pin-up. But he eventually won an Emmy award as best actor in a dramatic series. Working in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, he said, protected him from the buffeting of sudden fame. `` I've been lucky over here, I've been sheltered from a lot of the stuff tht goes on on the mainland,'' <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> said. `` It's great to be chosen favorite this or that, but a whole lot of baggage goes with all those titles. And then what happens when you're not at the top of the opinion polls? That's why, even though I appreciate it, I try not to buy into that stuff and being in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> has just made that easier. Plus, I love it here.'' He said he will maintain his ties to the islands. He has formed a production company with <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> and `` Magnum'' supervising producer <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> and hopes to produce a new series here, though without <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> as star. <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON>'s dual role of producing and starring in `` Magnum'' the past two years resulting in an `` unnatural existence,'' he said. `` It just takes up too large a part of my life _ which is all my waking hours _ and in the long run I just do n't think that's very healthy, physically or emotionally,'' said <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON>, who last year married actress <PERSON> Jillie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>. He planned to begin working in July on `` Her Alibi,'' a romantic comedy directed by <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Beresford </PERSON>. Until then, he said, he'll relax `` I asked for the time off because I just do n't know how I'm gon na feel after Magnum ends,'' <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> said `` I think I really need to take the time off to just see what happens. That's why I really have very few kinds of goals or direction right now.'' Saying goodbye wo n't be easy, <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> said. `` There's a huge part of me that would love ` Magnum' to go on forever,'' he said. `` I really do believe that it'll be about the best job I'll ever have.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 29-May 1</NOTE>
