<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government's report that the monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened by more than 11 percent to $ 13.8 billion in February sparked a nosedive in stock prices and the dollar. The gap between the nation's imports and exports expanded by $ 1.4 billion from January's imbalance of $ 12.4 billion _ its second straight jump after having fallen from a record $ 17.6 billion deficit last October, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Dow Jones industrial average plunged more than 100 points, the dollar sank and interest rates jumped after the government announced a higher-than-expected trade deficit in February. The Dow skidded 101.46 points to 2,005.64, a 4.8 percent decline, making Thursday's plunge the year's second worst drop after a 140.58-point slide on Jan. 8. Most traders had convinced themselves the imbalance between imports and exports would be less than $ 12 billion, and were disappointed at the actual results.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A restriction on computerized stock trading that went into effect when the Dow Jones average tumbled more than 50 points did little to halt the drop and may have worsened it, according to some brokers. Under the collar rule, traders are banned from using the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s automated order system to execute index-arbitrage program trades when the Dow average moves up or down 50 points from the previous close. Thursday marked the second time the so-called `` collar'' was used since it was created in the wake of October's stock market crash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebounding sales helped dampen growth of business inventories in February to a slight 0.1 percent after four big monthly increases, the government says. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that inventories increased by only $ 825 million, pushing the total of unsold items on store shelves and backlots to a seasonally adjusted $ 715.9 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted not to allow an extra $ 50 million in spending for health care as it moved toward passing a $ 1.1 trillion federal budget for fiscal 1989. The lawmakers voted 57-38 Thursday against a proposal that would have taken the money from expenditures planned for the superconducting super collider, a physics research program planned by the government and expected to cost about $ 4.4 billion ultimately.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` average'' American will have to work 126 days this year _ two more than in 1987 _ just to pay federal, state and local taxes, the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Tax Freedom Day'' will fall on May 5, the latest ever. The best taxpayers have fared in the past decade was in 1984 _ when most of the big 1981 federal income-tax reduction had taken effect _ when Tax Freedom Day fell on April 28, the foundation said Thursday.
</TEXT>
