<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the backing of its own shareholders secured, <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> now turns its full attention to convincing <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stockowners that its hostile $ 1 billion-plus takeover bid is a good deal. Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> said he had met privately with some of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s biggest stockholders, and that bank officials would continue soliciting others via telephone and mail until <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s annual meeting next Thursday `` It's a unique fit,'' <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> shareholders at their yearly gathering Thursday. `` Virtually all their businesses blend well into our's. We believe no other merger could make as much sense ...'' <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> is offering $ 15 in cash and 1.575 of its common shares for each of <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>'s roughly 18.1 million common shares outstanding, a proposal <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> has rejected as inadequate during their extended and bitter takeover fight. At <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting, <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> said preliminary tabulations showed shareholders solidly backed the company by granting it permission to issue as many additional common shares and convertible securities as needed to complete the Irving acquisition. The exact result of the vote on the stock question is to be released April 22. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, which holds a 4.9 percent stake in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, is seeking to gain control of that company's board of directors and has nominated a slate of 16 nominees. Analysts said they could not predict whether <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> could succeed. `` I ca n't take bets on that one ... though I'm sure <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> is feeling very bullish'' following Thursday's meeting, said <PERSON> Rosemarie </PERSON> <PERSON> Conforte </PERSON>, a banking analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think that's a very close call,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, a banking analyst with <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think they -LRB- Irving shareholders -RRB- may be persuaded, but it's a coin flip almost.'' Many analysts agree that a combination of the two would not be such a bad idea because both <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> banks operate in a similar marketplace and offer similar services such as securities processing. But <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> repeatedly has spurned the company's takeover offers, which began about seven months ago, maintaining it wants to remain independent. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> representatives had urged <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> shareholders Thursday to ask management to abandon all efforts to merge the two banks. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> argued that combining the two would dilute the value of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> stock, hurting earnings and dividends. `` We are convinced that the cost of integrating the two companies would create a further drain on earnings and that any benefits of combining the two firms would not be recognized for three to five years,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Falise </PERSON>, an executive vice president for legal affairs at <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> maintained dilution was not a problem. He also said a takeover would not reduce <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s dividends, which have increased annually for the past 11 years. Bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> began its current tender offer last month after receiving regulatory approval. Both the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said a merger would n't hurt competition in the nation's biggest financial center <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> has asked the federal courts to overturn the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s decision. <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> has taken a number of other steps to tryto defeat Bank of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s advances, including instituting an anti-takeover `` poison pill'' defense that is designed to make any hostile buyout prohibitively expensive. Hostile takeover efforts are rare in the banking industry. A merger between <