<FIRST>r f PM-Stocks-Analysis Bjt   04-15 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stocks-Analysis, Bjt,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street Stumbles In Post-Crash Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebuilding confidence in the stock market after the crash last October is proving to be an elusive and time-consuming mission. The market's latest bid to rally collapsed on Thursday when the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, the best known measure of market trends, fell 101.46 points to 2,005.64, for its fifth-largest loss ever. From April 5 through Tuesday of this week, the Dow industrials had climbed nearly 130 points, largely on anticipation of a continuing flow of favorable news on the nation's trade balance and the outlook for the dollar in foreign exchange. But the word from the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday morning was that the trade deficit widened in February, with imports exceeding exports by $ 13.83 against $ 12.44 billion the month before. In effect, that wiped out with a single stroke the basic premise behind the recent rally. Stock market analysts said persistent strength in imports, in particular, raised fears that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> soon might feel the need to tighten credit to restrain the economy as well as to support the dollar. `` You got a nasty bit of news,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` The market is saying that the economy is too strong.'' <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> also said the withdrawal from the market since last fall of many investors frightened away by the crash had left stocks in a fragile position, vulnerable to volatile swings. `` It's really a day-trader's market,'' he said. `` When we were rallying, there was n't a lot of volume. `` And when the market started to come down, there were no buffers on the downside _ no small investors, no pension managers, no foreign investors.'' That leaves Wall Street in a paradoxical plight. Investors large and small seem inclined to stay clear of the stock market until it shows signs of greater stability. But it looks as though those investors' presence may be needed if that stability is going to be attained. In the meantime, market analysts and professional money managers still are groping for some indication of where the market ought to settle out, and of what level of stock prices `` makes sense'' in the aftermath of the crash. As <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnaruma </PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Albany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, put it in his latest market commentary: `` In the current environment, all the normal road signs that usually provide one with direction appear to have been stolen by vandals.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE: <PERSON> Chet </PERSON> <PERSON> Currier </PERSON> has reported on Wall Street for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> since 1974.
</TEXT>
