<FIRST>r f PM-Stocks-Collar Bjt   04-15 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stocks-Collar, Bjt,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Drop Tests 50-Point Collar, Revives Debate Over Program
Trading Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first major test of Wall Street's computerized trading `` collar'' in braking a big fall in stock prices is getting mixed reviews, with some calling the limit helpful and others saying it may have worsened the drop `` The collar has got some holes in it,'' <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> strategist, said Thursday after the Dow Jones average tumbled 101.46 points, its fifth-worst daily decline ever. The slide represented more than double the 50-point swing necessary to activate the collar, which when triggered bans the use of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> computers for so-called index arbitrage program trading for the rest of the day. The drop marked the first time since the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> imposed the restriction on Feb. 4 that a decline activated the 50-point trigger. The collar took effect once before on April 6 when the average rose 64.16 points. `` At the present time, it's not working,'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> DaPuzzo </PERSON>, head of retail equities at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said as selling swept the market even once the collar took effect at about 1:55 p.m. EDT. The limit is part of an <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> effort to restore stability to a market still suffering after-effects of the epic crash nearly six months ago. Some crash studies have suggested program trading aggravated the October plunge, and the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has expressed concern that the practice is undermining investor and regulator confidence. `` It's really premature to assess whether the collar works,'' said <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamsin </PERSON>. `` It was n't designed to stop the Dow average from moving. We only have evidence of two days. When we get more data, we'll analyze it. If it's necessary to take further action, we might.'' Some traders said they believed the collar lessened the impact of what would have been a heavy selloff under any circumstances. Investors rushed to dump stocks largely because of economic worries linked to the government's report of a wider-than-expected trade deficit for February. But others said the braking effects of the collar were overwhelmed by big brokerage houses that executed sell orders manually or used forms of program trading not covered by the restraint. A few traders said they believed the collar actually worsened the drop because it only left sellers in the market. `` Once this thing goes below 50, nobody shows up to do any buying,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthel </PERSON>, a technical strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In index arbitrage, brokers use computers to buy or sell massive amounts of stocks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and the equivalent stock-index futures in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, in order to profit from price disparities. Although many brokerages have applauded the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s limit on the technique, others have been critical because they say it severs an important relationship between the stock and futures markets. Studies of the stock crash have concluded the relationship between financial markets was an important element in the October crash. A presidential panel's crash study, for example, suggested that a system of `` circuit breakers'' applying simultaneously to all markets trading stocks or stock-index futures would help prevent another crisis. `` I have a couple of problems with the whole collar concept,'' said <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON>, a futures-market expert and securities lawyer who is critical of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s post-crash strategy. `` Clearly, you ca n't disconnect the stock exchange from the futures market. They're all one big ball of wax,'' <PERSON> Schneider </PERSON> said. `` If you have only the stock exchange with a circuit breaker, it does n't do a damn thing.''
</TEXT>
