<FIRST>r f PM-CornBread     04-15 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Corn Bread,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Hope New Corn Bread Appeals to Consumers, Helps
Farmers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new kind of corn bread that combines down-home color and flavor with a firmness that stands up to slicing could help shrink the nation's corn surplus if it goes over well with consumers, government researchers say. This is not old-fashioned corn bread that crumbles into the ham and beans. This firm new loaf _ made from flour that's half wheat and half finely ground corn _ can be sliced, buttered, toasted and used for sandwiches. `` It gives people a new bread product, and it could enable farmers to sell more of their corn at a higher price,'' said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> food technologist <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>. The bread was developed at the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said the goal was to develop a bread that used as much corn flour as possible `` so it would make a big impact on using up surplus corn supplies.'' As it turned out, the ideal flour formulation was half corn and half wheat, with extra wheat gluten to improve its structure. The dough is leavened with yeast. Traditional corn bread is made mainly from coarser cornmeal and baking powder. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said the new corn bread resembles a home-baked or specialty bakery loaf rather than typical supermarket sandwich bread. But she said wholesale bakers could modify the formula `` to make it lighter and fluffier'' if that is the kind of loaf their customers want. `` The next step is to encourage industry to try this and find a market for it,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said. The $ 16 billion-a-year wholesale bread - and cake-baking industry uses about 100 million pounds of flour annually, according to <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, editor of the Milling and Baking News `` I ca n't even predict what consumer interest would be'' for the new corn bread, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baking </ORGANIZATION>. `` I like corn bread, so if it has that flavor it might appeal to some of the public.'' <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> noted that sales of a new product usually reflect the amount of money spent on marketing and advertising. Bakers would have to believe the new corn bread is `` delightfully good tasting'' to make a major investment in promoting it, he said. During the 1970s, <ORGANIZATION> Purity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> marketed a product called Country Corn Bread, using a smaller percentage of corn flour. President <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Webb </PERSON> said that version had a rich golden color, and because corn flour holds moisture well it also stayed fresh longer. `` It is just one of those items that was very successful at the time, but tastes change and it eventually was replaced,'' said <PERSON> Webb </PERSON>. `` People today are searching for new varieties'' and this could be a good time to offer a new kind of corn bread, he said. A popular new corn bread also could help the nation's dry millers, who use about 2 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn crop, said <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Faga </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Millers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>. `` The industry certainly is looking for new uses for dry milled corn _ every possible outlet,'' said <PERSON> Faga </PERSON>. `` This certainly could be a new one for them.''
</TEXT>
