<SECOND>PM-Societe Generale,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Stall De Bendetti's Bid For Societe Generale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> shareholders have dealt <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> a setback in his attempted takeover of the giant holding company, but the Italian financier still wields some clout over the enterprise. At a 12-hour special shareholders meeting on Thursday, shareholders spurned the bid by <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> and two allies to win seats on the <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> board of directors. The trio got votes from only 44.5 percent of the shares registered, and needed 51 percent to win election to the board. But because he commands a huge block of shares, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> retains much clout within the company and may win yet a board seat. `` Today's votes will not be for the long term,'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> told the more than 1,150 shareholders before the vote, which was taken at a meeting held in a tent next to <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>'s head office. `` In one week, one month, six months or one year, we will play a major role in <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>. Without me ... no stable management of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> is possible.'' Management of <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s biggest holding company, was relieved after the marathon meeting. `` We fought it out. There was a winner and a loser,'' said Director <PERSON> Etienne </PERSON> <PERSON> Davignon </PERSON>. Shareholders added 12 members _ all rivals of <LOCATION> De </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Benedetti </LOCATION> _ to the board of directors with a majority of 55 percent of the vote. The previous board had 11 directors. Right up through the start of the meeting, <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> had met with his rivals to seek a compromise. But the talks failed when <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON> continued insisting on control over day-to-day management of the venerable, 166-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION>, which has stakes in some 1,300 companies worldwide. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>, who sparked the heated takeover battle for <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> three months ago, had sought election along with two allies, including <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Leysen </PERSON>, chairman of <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Gevaert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NV </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> nominated the remaining 12 candidates, allies of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Cie. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financiere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Groupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>. The two companies, heading an alliance of smaller Belgian, French, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> and Swiss interests, led the fight against <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>. The vote indicated how many shares each faction controls. Under Belgian law, shareholders are not required to disclose the amount of their holdings, leaving only speculation over which group holds a majority. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Benedetti </PERSON>, who spent some $ 1.7 billion to raise his <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> holdings, claims he and his allies control 48 percent of the company. <OR