<FIRST>d f PM-MercedesIncentives     04-15 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mercedes Incentives,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mercedes Offers Trip Tix For Car Pickups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> wants you to have a nice vacation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. So the luxury automaker is offering free plane tickets on one condition: that the trip include the purchase of a Mercedes in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Since March 30, Mercedes has been giving two round-trip economy plane tickets, or one business-class ticket, on <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> flights to customers who purchase and pick up autos from its factory near <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION>. As under most European pick-up programs, the company pays for shipment of the car back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and for a 2.5 percent import duty. The net savings, according to spokesman A.B. <PERSON> Schuman </PERSON> at Mercedes' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Montvale </LOCATION>, is about 8 percent off the retail price. <PERSON> Schuman </PERSON> said the free offer caters to overseas buyers who frequently combine a European tour with their auto purchase, which in turn saves the cost of renting an automobile. European delivery has been part of luxury-car marketing since the early 1960s, <PERSON> Schuman </PERSON> said, and Mercedes' current gimmick is part of a long-term marketing strategy. Mercedes sold 2,090 cars to Americans in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> last year, out of a total 89,900 purchased for use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In an increasingly competitive luxury car market, Mercedes' ticket offer has more to do with gaining a competitive edge than with boosting European delivery sales, said spokesman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGurn </PERSON> at rival BMW of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Montvale </LOCATION> <PERSON> Schuman </PERSON> said it was too early to tell the results of the Mercedes' program, but a sales manager at the nation's largest Mercedes dealership said he was pleased. `` It's done the job here,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> at Downtown <ORGANIZATION> L.A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Four buyers lured by the ticket offer made deals on Wednesday and one called last weekend, when advertisements for the program began appearing, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. The ticket offer is one example of how luxury car makers are competing for buyers, who have become reluctant because of confusion over the new tax laws that went into effect in 1987, the October stock market crash and the continuing decline of the dollar, which has boosted foreign car prices, said <ORGANIZATION> BMW </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> McGurn </PERSON>. BMW, for instance, has boosted its advertising and is offering a lower percentage financing on leasing rates. Of 87,800 domestic sales, 1,610 BMWs were picked up in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <PERSON> McGurn </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Saab-Scania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, reported 741 European deliveries for 1987 from four European locations, said spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ventrilio </PERSON>.
