<FIRST>r f PM-National-Fairchild     04-15 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National-Fairchild,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sporck Says National-Fairchild Merger A Huge Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hard rain that fell on <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> ceremonies honoring <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> pioneer <ORGANIZATION> Fairchild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been practically the only thing to dampen the recent merger of the two companies. The union of the two chipmakers has come off much more smoothly than many analysts and rivals thought it would, without the bloodbath of personnel cuts and violent organizational disruptions predicted by some. National acquired struggling Fairchild on Oct. 1 for $ 122 million, after political pressure nixed a $ 200 million buyout by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fujitsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, and found a silicon treasure trove, according to National boss <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON>. There were layoffs as the combined companies trimmed from 38,000 to 36,000 workers and there were `` ruffled feathers,'' <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON> admits, as employees made adjustments and, in some cases, switched jobs. But he says that a dynamic company has emerged from the merger, with a broad range of products, solid research departments and worldwide clout. `` I'm unaware of any other combination of two companies where a merger's been pulled off so well in such a short period of time,'' <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON> said Thursday in his first interview on the merger since last fall. <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON> said National will post revenue of about $ 2.5 billion when its 1988 fiscal year ends May 31, enabling the company to leap from 11th to fifth among world chip companies. He also estimated National would surpass the 12 percent growth rate he thinks the industry will post over the next year as it continues its recovery from a severe slump. `` The sum of the two companies is exceeding the parts involved,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boss </PERSON>, analyst for San Jose-based market research firm <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It was n't apparent from the figures for 1987,'' <PERSON> Boss </PERSON> said, `` but we really expect this to be a very good year for National. We see some very good blending together of technologies and markets.'' <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON> said National got more than it bargained for. `` Our estimates were conservative, both in terms of the financial impact and technology,'' he said. `` There was a perception on our part, as well as the industry's that Fairchild had a somewhat empty basket in terms of product. It was n't until after we truly started looking seriously that we realized that was a misconception.'' <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON> said he particularly is impressed with Fairchild's high speed and custom chips used for supercomputers and military applications. Added to National's other lines of chips, the combined company can offer customers a wide range of technologies. `` There is a trend among customers to reduce the number of suppliers,'' he said. `` It saves money dealing with fewer people, and they realize, as we do, that more profitable relations occur when the two engineering organizations work closely together. `` It's a benefit we really did n't understand when we first started the Fairchild involvement.'' Huddled under golf umbrellas, Fairchild's eight founders gathered among about 2,000 guests Thursday as <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON> praised it as `` the granddaddy of all semiconductor companies'' and dedicated the new $ 75 million Fairchild Research Center. It was National's way of preserving the name and spirit of the company that spawned <LOCATION> Silicon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>'s biggest chipmakers, including <ORGANIZATION> Intel </ORGANIZATION>, Advanced Micro Devices and National. `` Fairchild had tremendously talented people and an unusual, free-swinging environment,'' said <PERSON> Sporck </PERSON>, who joined Fairchild as a production manager and rose to head of the semiconductor division before he left to join National in 1967. `` They were prepared to accept unusual behavior from people given they have talent,'' he said. `` One of the negatives of that, of course, is we bred a lot of entrepreneurs and they went out and started a lot of companies, which was n't necessarily in the best interests of Fairchild. But all of us have a tinge of nostalgia for Fairchild.''
