<HEAD>Steel Imports Down In February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel imports declined in February to the target set by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for its quota program, except for metal imported by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies for rolling on their own mills. But American producers said Thursday that the 1.9 million tons imported in February in both categories represented the highest single-month level since November 1986. `` Increasing volume of semi-finished steel imports, badly needed by domestic rolling mills themselves, continues a trend evident since the beginning of 1988,'' said <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, president of the New York-based <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Imported </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION>. The AIIS is composed largely of European steelmakers who sell products in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> represents domestic companies. Both intepret <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Commerce Department data separately. The importers said February steel imports, excluding 284,900 tons of semi-finished metal headed for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mills, totaled 1.6 million tons, or 18.8 percent of the domestic market. They said that's close to the 18.5 percent goal set by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in launching the quota program in late 1984. Including semi-finished steel, February imports represented 22.1 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. That was up from 21.8 percent in January, when 1.8 million tons entered the country, but down from 25 percent in February 1987, when 1.8 million tons entered a smaller domestic market, the <ORGANIZATION> AIIS </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers calculate the administration's goal as 20.2 percent of the market, including semi-finished steel. The importers said semi-finished steel represented 15 percent of February's total imports. `` Even these sharply increased semi-finished steel imports are still unable to satisfy demand, as indicated by escalating petitions of American rolling mills to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for short-supply allocation,'' said <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, vice chairman of the import firm <ORGANIZATION> STEELINTER </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The short supply petitions are requests for permission to import steel in excess of the quotas, which the administration negotiated at the request of the domestic producers. Unless extended, the quotas will expire in September 1989.
