<HEAD>Retail Prices Up 0.4 Percent, Unemployment Down in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> rose 0.4 percent in March from the previous month, while the country's unemployment rate declined by 0.1 percent, the government announced Friday. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> attributed the rise in its retail price index to increases spread over a large range of goods and services, mostly for foods, motor vehicles, household goods, clothing and footwear. The index was 3.5 percent higher than in March 1987, the department said. Meanwhile, unemployment fell to a seasonally adjusted 9 percent of the work force last month from 9.1 percent in February. The figure was down from 10.9 percent in March 1987, the department said. Total seasonally adjusted unemployment was estimated at 2.505 million people in March, down from a revised 2.533 million in February and 3.037 million in March 1987.
