<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> say they expect agreement soon on a plan to halt trading in stocks and stock-index futures when the markets rise or fall 200 to 300 points in one day. The heads of the two fiercely competitive exchanges _ <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for stocks and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for futures _ on Thursday told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel examining the October stock market collapse that they hoped to agree on the plan within the next month. However, <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchange's executive committee, and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, differed on just how far the markets should move before trading is interrupted <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said the trading should not be halted until the Dow Jones Industrial Average moves 250 to 300 points, while <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> said the limits should be in the range of 200 to 250 points. <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said since October they have met several times in an effort to achieve greater coordination. <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> leaders _ particularly <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> finance subcommittee Chairman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass _ had been complaining about the lack of progress in talks among the exchanges and among federal regulatory agencies. `` You've got to let the market seek its own level, but there comes a time when a systematic halt _ a safety net _ that is known in advance is helpful,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said. `` In the futures market, we are not uncomfortable with price limits; we already have them,'' <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> said. `` It just depends on where you draw the line.'' He said short halts in trading `` are a necessary evil, perhaps, but something we could live with.'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said the purpose of the halts would be to allow the market `` to stop and take a look at itself.'' He said they should be more than 30 minutes but should not last all day. Both chairmen told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> finance subcommittee that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s new working group on the markets has indicated a circuit-breaker plan is a high priority. Currently, the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> limits a form of computerized trading known as index arbitrage _ which links the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> stock markets with the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> futures markets _ once the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> moves 50 points, either up or down. The <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchange has set daily price limits on its <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock index future, which is based on stocks traded on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. There is an opening price limit that restricts any move during the first l0 minutes of trading to the equivalent of roughly 40 points on the Dow and a daily price limit equivalent to between 120 and 150 Dow points. But such circuit breakers are not coordinated between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> also said regulation of the nation's financial markets by a single federal agency would do `` a great disservice'' to the marketplace and that it `` is neither warranted nor wise.'' Currently, the <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> oversees the nation's futures markets and the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> regulates securities trading. <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said he believes one regulator should eventually be in charge of all the markets. `` We believe ... that ultimately there should be a unified regulator for all equity-related products,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> testified. `` But more immediately, it is much more important that we strengthen the clearing and settlement process as well as put in place an all-market circuit breaker in the event of a major market decline.'' <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> said the roles of the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> are so different that they should not be combined. `` The number of true intermarket issues are few and limited in scope,'' <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> told the panel. `` Moreover, they must be resolved now, not when the next crisis occurs.''
