<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower But Above Worst Levels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices closed lower Friday, but well above their worst levels of the day as bargain-hunting and takeover rumors helped the market regain some lost ground. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 selected stocks fell 8.6 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,778.6. The index fell 24.1 points at the opening, but dealers said the real low for the day came in trading before the official opening, when the index was down as much as 38 points. Volume was moderate at 472.9 million shares, down from 517.3 million on Thursday. Share prices were marked down sharply from the outset of trading, following Thursday's plunge on Wall Street, when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average lost more than 100 points. But British institutional buyers were attracted by the low prices and the market rose steadily in the morning until it was down 4.6 points in the early afternoon. Weakness in the early going on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> took <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> prices down from their best levels. However, dealers were heartened by the market's resilience in the face of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s sell-off Thursday. `` We're coming into the area where the market is looking attractive to fund managers,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON>, European equities strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
