<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv16-17   04-15 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 16-17,0725</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 16-17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bond Market Jolted by Unexpected Economic Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bond market got an earful of economic news this past week, and did n't like a lot of what it heard. `` It was a week of surprises, all of them negative,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Griggs </PERSON> of the financial consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Griggs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Santow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The reports on March retail sales and wholesale prices and the February trade deficit indicated the economy is growing faster than post-stock market crash pessimists had expected and that inflation may be accelerating. Faster economic growth and rising prices are the enemy in the bond market, and prices slumped on the news, pushing long-term yields toward their highest levels since they exceeded 9 percent in mid-January. By midafternoon Friday, the prices of some long-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds were priced to yield 8.93 percent, up from 8.68 percent at the end of the previous week and from 8.3 percent in early February. The government reported Wednesday that retail sales rose 0.8 percent in March, stronger than most analysts had expected. `` It was another indication that the consumer has the ability to spend and is doing it,'' <PERSON> Griggs </PERSON> said. More disconcerting was news the next day that the nation's trade deficit had widened to $ 13.8 billion in February. Most analysts had expected a contraction in the deficit to the $ 11 billion to $ 12 billion range. Continued strength in imports raised the possibility that inflation would accelerate, possibly prompting the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to tighten credit conditions in an effort to ward off higher prices. Adding to inflation concerns was Friday's report that wholesale prices rose 0.6 percent in March or about twice as fast as most analysts had expected. `` That was one more bit of bad news that the market could have done without,'' said <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, research director for <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He said next month's wholesale price figure could be even worse if oil prices continue their recent rise. Most economists caution against reading too much into any single economic report, noting that they are often subject to revision. But <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandross </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the rise in wholesale prices nonetheless indicates `` something is going on, on the inflation front that is pretty negative.'' `` I had thought April was going to be difficult, and this raises the likelihood that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> will have to tighten further,'' he said. `` They may not do it right away but if we get some strong employment figures for April, it would leave them no alternative.'' <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Won </PERSON> <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Norwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, said the series of economic reports `` was extremely disappointing'' because the consensus estimates were wrong in each case. <PERSON> Sohn </PERSON> said he had expected long-term rates would decline in May, but said the latest reports prompted him to delay that projection. He is now looking for long-term rates to edge up to 9 percent and not begin falling until July or August. He expects long-term rates will be as low as 8.3 percent by November. <ORGANIZATION> DLJ </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> expects long-term rates will rise as high as 9.25 percent by the end of the month, but then decline as low as 8 percent by early summer. But <PERSON> Griggs </PERSON> is decidedly more pessimistic. He said the gyrations in the dollar have introduced a new element of risk for foreign buyers of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> securities, and that rates will rise to compensate them for that. Combined with the federal government's continuing strong borrowing demands and an expected acceleration of inflation, <PERSON> Griggs </PERSON> said he expects long-term rates will rise to 10 percent or more by the end of the year. <PERSON> Chandross </PERSON> is looking for long-term rates to stay in a narrow range, rising to 9 percent before slipping to 8.75 percent during May. `` There is enough skittishness in the economy right now that there is a self-correcting mechanism at work under which rising rates dampen certain kinds of economic activity and that leads rates to fall,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 16-17</NOTE>
