<HEAD>Texaco Reinstates Dividend; To Sell $2 Billion More in Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Friday it will resume paying a quarterly dividend and will sell off an additional $ 2 billion in assets as part of its restructuring. At its first meeting since <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> emerged from Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy court reorganization on April 7, the oil giant's board of directors authorized a 75-cent quarterly dividend, a move analysts said is intended to bolster shareholder support for the current management team In closing trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> jumped $ 1.62 -LCB- to $ 48.75. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> had been barred from paying dividends after it filed for bankruptcy protection on April 12, 1987, in the wake of its epic legal battle with <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The dividend will be paid June 10 to shareholders of record May 3. In addition to authorizing the dividend, directors said they planned to sell off $ 5 billion in assets to help reduce the company's debt load. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> said in its 1987 annual report that it hoped to raise at least $ 3 billion through the sale of assets, but Friday's action increased that amount by $ 2 billion. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive officer, said in a statement that the resumption of dividends `` at a substantial rate demonstrates <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s confidence that this expanded restructuring will enable us to build a more profitable company on a solid core of our most productive assets.'' While <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> can afford the roughly $ 726 million a year in dividend payments, experts noted that the extra expense will eat up nearly 100 percent of the company's projected earnings for the year. The $ 3-a-share annual dividend `` is not justified by <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s current earnings prospects,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lazier </PERSON>, vice president for energy investments at <ORGANIZATION> Prescott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ball </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` They probably will not earn much more than the $ 3 -LRB- a share -RRB- rate. <PERSON> Lazier </PERSON> called the dividend decision a `` defensive move'' designed to offer shareholders an incentive to `` ride along with current management'' rather than side with corporate raider <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholder and sharpest critic. `` For shareholders hoping for liquidation, this is a nail in that coffin,'' <PERSON> Lazier </PERSON> said, referring to rumors that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> would have been dismembered if <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> won control. He unsuccessfully sought a board seat. Speculation had been brewing in recent weeks that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> would take some action to boost the value of its stock, so Friday's announcement was not a complete surprise `` I think -LRB- the dividend -RRB- will quell a lot of shareholder'' dissent, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Alen </PERSON>, an oil analyst at <PERSON> Janney </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. As part of its asset sale, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> said it would dispose of unidentified `` producing, manufacturing and marketing assets, both domestic and overseas.'' Last week <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> confirmed it is negotiating to sell its <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, which operates 1,903 gas stations in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Officials said the operation could fetch as much as $ 1.7 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> previously announced plans to sell 60 million barrels of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil and natural gas reserves. <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON> said in a statement issued from <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s headquarters in <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, that the asset sales would serve to `` de-emphasize our presence in manufacturing and marketing.'' He said the company also would `` pursue rigorous programs to streamline management and to set and achieve strict operating and financial objectives.'' Under a reorganization plan approved March 23 by a federal bankruptcy court judge, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> transferred $ 3 billion to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> on April 7 to settle its 4-year legal battle with the Houston-based company. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> had filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws to avoid having to post a potentially ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond while appealing a $ 10 billion damage judgment awarded to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION> by a <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> jury in November 1985. The award stemmed from <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Getty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after <PERSON> Getty </PERSON> had agreed to sell part of its assets to <ORGANIZATION> Pennzoil </ORGANIZATION>. Also at the board meeting, former <ORGANIZATION> PPG </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> was elected to the board of directors to replace <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, who resigned <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> is the managing partner of <ORGANIZATION> Mason </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Best </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a privately held merchant banking company based in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
