<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed on New Economic Data, Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar closed mixed against major foreign currencies Friday amid speculation that interest rates would soon rise. Gold prices increased. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 455.25 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $ 452.65 late Thursday. The government's announcement of a 0.6 percent increase in wholesale prices for March was viewed as mildly bullish and had a stabilizing influence on the dollar, said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Discount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Traders believed the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might be moved to tighten credit _ thereby raising interest rates _ to counter a surge in inflation Higher interest rates would have a calming effect on the dollar, which fell sharply on Thursday after the government released disappointing balance of trade figures. Another government report Friday, of a 0.1 percent in industrial production, produced market speculation that companies were buying foreign machinery to increase their output, <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. Traders believe higher output would lead to increased exports, and eventually a shrinkage in the nation's trade deficit. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the deficit widened to $ 13.8 billion in February. Financial markets had expected the gap to narrow. <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> described trading Friday as quiet. In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the dollar fell, but central bank intervention tempered its slide, dealers said. While American markets interpreted Friday's economic figures as positive for the dollar, overseas traders saw them in a negative light and sold dollars. The wholesale price figure was larger than expected and the industrial output number was lower than anticipated. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ended before the figures were released, the dollar fell 2.02 yen to a closing 124.13. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 123.90 yen and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it rose to 123.80 yen from 123.725 yen late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.8890 to buy one pound, higher than $ 1.8755 Thursday. In later <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading, sterling rose to $ 1.9003 from $ 1.8739. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday's prices, included: 1.66095 West German marks, down from 1.66275; 1.3725 Swiss francs, up from 1.3720; 5.6345 French francs, up from 5.6325; 1,232.625 Italian lire, down from 1,233.00; and 1.2333 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2365. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Thursday: 1.6605 West German marks, down from 1.6635; 1.3720 Swiss francs, down from 1.3745; 5.6325 French francs, down from 5.6390; 1.8630 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8680; 1,232.50 Italian lire, down from 1,244.00; and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2368. Gold rose on the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, closing at $ 455.90 a troy ounce, compared with $ 452.65 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, bullion rose to a late bid price of $ 456.25 an ounce, compared with late Thursday's $ 451. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was higher, closing at a bid $ 455.50 an ounce, compared with $ 450.50 late Thursday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 5.45 to close at a bid $ 454.93 an ounce. Silver rose on the Comex in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. It closed at $ 6.455 a troy ounce, up from $ 6.325 late Thursday. Silver also rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.49 an ounce, compared with Thursday's $ 6.43.
</TEXT>
