<HEAD>Stevens Board Backs Odyssey Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sheet and towel giant <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stevens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday its board has backed a $ 1.22 billion buyout bid from a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment firm, spurning a lower offer from rival fabric maker <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point-Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In the continuing takeover battle for the textile giant, <ORGANIZATION> Odyssey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> was offering $ 68.50 a share in cash for <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' outstanding shares under a tender offer due to expire April 22 The company sweetened its offer to that level in a frenzied auction Monday, just hours after <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> boosted its own tender offer to $ 67 a share in cash, or about $ 1.19 billion. The current bids represent the third time each company has sweetened its bid for <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> fell 50 cents a share to close at $ 67.62 -LCB- Friday in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading. In recommending that shareholders tender to Odyssey, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said its board had considered and rejected <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION>'s competing offer. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lanier </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>'s chairman and chief executive officer, had said in an interview he considered <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>'s current bid fair, but he did not rule out another round of bidding. A spokesman for <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> had no comment on what action the company might take. The board's decision to spurn <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> came after the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, company was able to remove major antitrust concerns by agreeing with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to sell certain <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> assets if its offer succeeds. <PERSON> Pepperell </PERSON> said earlier in the week that the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> agreed to permit <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION>'s previously announced plans to sell half of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' bath lines and 20 percent of its sheet lines for about $ 170 million to <ORGANIZATION> NTC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, parent of the textile manufacturer <ORGANIZATION> Bibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> also waived waiting requirements under federal disclosure laws but could require <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> to sell a sheeting mill, a yarn plant, certain designer licenses and a brand name if the deal were consummated, <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> would have six months to decide whether <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> must divest those <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> assets. Among the top brand names in <LOCATION> Stevens </LOCATION> towel and sheet arsenal are <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Gloria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON>, among others. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>'s brands include Arrow, Martex, <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepperell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Burberry </PERSON>. Bidding for <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> began after it received a leveraged buyout offer earlier this year from a group led by its own senior management, including Chairman <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, a fifth-generation member of the family that founded the company in 1813. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> launched a $ 62.50-a-share tender offer last month after <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> agreed to a buyout by Odyssey at $ 61.50 a share. Odyssey subsequently sweetened its offer to $ 64. On Monday, <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> increased its tender offer to $ 67 a share, but <ORGANIZATION> Odyssey </ORGANIZATION> topped that by $ 1.50 a share just hours before its own tender was about to expire.
