<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices pulled out of Thursday's steep slide with an uneven showing Friday marked by strength in some blue-chip issues. But analysts said investors' spirits were still dampened by worries over inflation and the nation's international trade problems. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 101.46 on Thursday for its fifth largest point loss ever, rose 8.29 to 2,013.93. It finished the week with a net loss of 76.26 points. Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 9 to 5 in the daily tally on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 573 up, 990 down and 420 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume came to 234.16 million shares, up from 211.81 million in the previous session. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index slipped .14 to 147.00. Analysts said blue-chip stocks attracted some buying by traders looking for `` bargains'' after the big drop on Thursday. But they also noted that stocks faced some formidable obstacles in any bid to rebound. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday morning that the producer price index of finished goods rose 0.6 percent in March. That put added emphasis on recent worries about a possible revival of inflationary pressures. At the same time, interest rates rose in the credit markets, pushing yields on long-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds close to the 8.95 percent level. Brokers said the bond and stock markets were still feeling the ill effects of the unexpected news Thursday that the nation's trade deficit widened in February. Gainers among the blue chips that contributed to the Dow Jones industrials' gain included <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION>, up 2 -RCB- at 114 -LRB-, and <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, up 1 -RCB- at 48 | Earlier this week, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> reported a first-quarter earnings gain that drew high marks from most analysts. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, which recently emerged from bankruptcy protection, voted a 75-cents-a-share quarterly dividend and expanded the plans for its restructuring program. Other big-name issues attracting buyers included <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, up 1 -LRB- at 72 -RCB-; <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, up 1 at 78 ~, and <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION>, up ~ at 34 <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>, by contrast, fell 1 | to 101 -LCB-, hitting a new 52-week low The company, with a very large following among investing institutions, recently reported first-quarter earnings that were essentially flat against comparable year-ago figures. As measured by <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market lost $ 1.06 billion, or 0.04 percent, in value. Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 265.05 million shares. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's industrial index rose .36 to 302.68, and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index was up .02 at 259.77 The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market dropped .62 to 373.90. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 