<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that its board of directors amended a shareholders' rights `` poison pill'' plan to a make it even tougher for a hostile takeover of the media giant. The board also authorized a stock buyout of up to 5 million common shares, four months after it approved the purchase of up to 2 million shares. Spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said the stock was needed for several reasons, including employee share and option plans. More than 40 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> stock is owned or controlled by directors, officers, employees or founding families. Under the poison pill amendment, shareholders would be able to buy additional common shares at a discount should someone acquire up to 20 percent of the company's outstanding stock, said <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>. `` The effect of that is to make a hostile takeover attempt extremely dilutive,'' he said. Meanwhile Friday, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Batten </PERSON>, 52, was elected chief executive officer. <PERSON> Batten </PERSON>, a 31-year veteran newsman of <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>, replaces <PERSON> Alvah </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 67, who remains as chairman. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> publishes 30 daily newspapers, including the <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION>, owns and operates eight television stations and is a joint venture partner in cable television and newsprint manufacturing operations. It also owns 49.5 percent of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>.
