<HEAD>Bond Prices Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices tumbled and interest rates jumped Friday for the second consecutive session as new worries emerged about inflation. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond fell | point, or $ 6.25 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price, climbed to 8.94 percent from 8.86 percent late Thursday. The 30-year bond dropped about $ 10 for every $ 1,000 in face value moments after the government reported wholesale prices jumped 0.6 percent in March _ the biggest increase in 11 months. But prices later recoverered as buyers appeared when yields on the longest issues edged closer to 9 percent, a height last touched in January. The latest price decline came on the heels of Thursday's sharp slide in stock and bond prices sparked by news of an unexpected widening in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. Most analysts had been looking for a more moderate gain in wholesale prices than the 0.6 percent rise reported by the government. `` It catered to the market's recent fears about whether the economy is expanding too rapidly, and is facing demand pressures and bottlenecks that would tend to move prices higher,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, director of money market research for the investment fir <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Inflation erodes the value of fixed-income securities, and increases the chances that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> will encourage higher interest rates to curb rising prices In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds, prices of short-term issues fell -LRB- point, intermediates lost 5-16 point and 20-year governments fell -RCB- point, according to the financial information service <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Index </ORGANIZATION>, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, had declined 0.42 to 110.83. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> composite index, which makes a similar measurement, fell 3.76 at 1,159.06. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, fell 0.98 to 278.90. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, meanwhile, soared 17 basis points to 5.89 percent, while six-month bills jumped 19 basis points to 6.22 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. One-year bills jumped 12 basis points to 6.58 percent. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 6 -RCB- percent, up from 611-16 percent late Thursday. In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyers Municipal Bond Index of 40 long-term bonds fell 11-32 point to 8718-32 while its yield rose to 8.21 percent from 8.17 percent.
