<HEAD>Former Xerox Employees Charge Age Discrimination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers for some 1,300 former <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employees, claiming they lost their jobs because of age discrimination, asked a federal appeals court Friday to allow them to sue for damages in a class action. The case has bounced around the federal court system for five years and now it has bounced back to the Third U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, where two judges said they were troubled that a lower court, without considering statistical evidence, had decertified a class of victims of an alleged pattern or practice of age discrimination. According to briefs filed in the case, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> terminated, forced to retire or denied promotion to at least 1,300 people between May 1980 and April 1983 in order to reduce its work force. The lower court held they were not part of a class action because they had different jobs and different risks. `` That is error,'' said Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietz </PERSON>, representing 13 former salesmen of <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> facsimile devices who brought the appeal seeking to reinstate a 1984 order by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> that had created a conditional class. After nearly an hour of oral argument, Judges <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Scirica </PERSON> took the case under advisement. A decision is not expected until sometime this summer. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, another lawyer representing the employees, said: `` We are fighting the procedural barriers erected by a well-financed firm who have consistently denied that the reduction in force imposed by <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> targeted older workers even though the evidence we provided conclusively supports it.'' `` You say the lower court failed to consider the statistical evidence, or even company documents -LRB- that supported it -RRB-, when it denied a class action designation?'' asked <PERSON> Rosenn </PERSON>. `` Right,'' responded <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>. `` We ask you to instruct the trial court to consider that. We say <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> conducted fraud on its older workers. The undisputed facts of discrimination come from the company's own records. What the lower court did was a clear error of law.'' Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Tufo </PERSON>, representing <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>, disagreed, and contended that charges of discrimination must be proved, separately, by each claimant. <PERSON> Rosenn </PERSON> interjected that `` what troubles me is that in the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> opinion there is no discussion of the evidence.'' <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON> said he, too, `` was troubled -LRB- because the judge -RRB- didn ` t say what he found, and that appears to be clear error.'' <PERSON> Rosenn </PERSON> added, `` He ignored the statistical evidence, and said it was n't relevant. Should he have disregarded it? That's what we have to decide.'' <PERSON> Del </PERSON> <PERSON> Tufo </PERSON> argued that `` the statistical evidence is wrong, and is irrelevant.'' The federal <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, in a friend of the court brief, noted: `` It is difficult to prove specific acts of discrimination'' and that `` statistics may often be the only available evidence of clandestine and covert discrimination.'' It joined the plaintiffs in asking that the class be certified contending that the lower court `` committed legal error.''
