<HEAD>Closing Arguments Heard In West Publishing Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two computerized legal research services squared off in federal court Friday for closing arguments in a two-week copyright infringement trial a defense lawyer called a case of `` the emperor's new clothes.'' <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> filed suit against one of its competitors in 1985, alleging copyright infringement. West, based in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, accused <ORGANIZATION> Mead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> of illegally using West's copyright material in Lexis, their computerized legal research service <ORGANIZATION> MDC </ORGANIZATION>, which distributes Lexis, is a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Mead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a paper products manufacturer based in <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. `` A case of the ` emperor's new clothes' is how I referred to this in my opening statement,'' <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> lawyer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> told the court. `` The arrangements in this case are nothing more than legal finery which have been rigged up by some tailor.'' Last year, <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> sued West, claiming that West is an illegal monopoly. West also has filed an antitrust suit against <PERSON> Mead </PERSON>, bringing to three the number of lawsuits in which the two are engaged. The copyright infringement trial, heard by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenbaum </PERSON>, is part of an 11-count complaint. The remaining 10 counts will be resolved by judicial order once <PERSON> Rosenbaum </PERSON> issues his ruling on the copyright issue. West's National Reporter System publishes judicial opinions for every state and federal court, and the company's Key Number Index System organizes and classifies case law. West asks that <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Mead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> be permanently enjoined from continuing to copy <PERSON> West </PERSON>'s materials and that the court impound and destroy all infringing materials. `` <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> took -LRB- our materials -RRB-. They knew it. And they expected to derive great revenue from it,'' West lawyer <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Opperman </PERSON> argued. `` We have both the right to copy and the right to display. Both have been infringed.'' But <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> claims there's been no infringement because West is not entitled to a copyright. `` In no case does copyright protection from an original work or authority extend to an idea ... And if we have anything here, all we have is an idea or concept,'' <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> argued. <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> only wanted to make `` fair use'' of the materials and should have access to them. `` West, I submit, confused access to the law with access to West books ... But West does n't own the law,'' <PERSON> Greer </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Opperman </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> West </PERSON>'s system reflects originality and is therefore protected by copyright. `` This is the product of great intellectual effort, great creativity,'' <PERSON> Opperman </PERSON> said.
