<HEAD>Judge Blocks Koppers Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Friday blocked investors led by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> from proceeding with a $ 1.7 billion hostile takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, but the judge left the door open for <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> to salvage the proposed deal. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said that the novel role played by <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in the takeover apparently requires the investment banking firm to file financial disclosure statements just like any other bidder. <PERSON> Shearson </PERSON> did not make the filings. <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> said that `` since ... there is a great probability that the defendants have violated the Williams Act,'' he was suspending the takeover until a trial can be held or the violations in the $ 60-per-share tender offer are corrected. The Williams Act is intended to prevent manipulation of the stock markets. The Beazer group did not immediately indicate whether it would appeal <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON>'s order or attempt to correct the technical defects and continue soliciting shares. The tender offer was due to expire at midnight Friday, but the suitors are expected to extend the offer during the weekend. <PERSON> Beazer </PERSON> wants to combine his British and American holdings in construction and building materials with the Pittsburgh-based <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>, a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer of building materials and chemicals. <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> maintained that its partial ownership of <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s takeover company, <ORGANIZATION> BNS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is merely an extension of traditional lending practices in corporate acquisitions `` The Shearson interests appear to be somewhat stealthily pioneering the brave new world of equity financing,'' the judge said in his 95-page opinion and order. `` As the legendary camel once got his nose in the tent, intending to follow with its entire body, so Shearson seems to be pursuing an agenda of its own.'' <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s new approach prompted members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to propose legislation against the takeover and to call for investigations. <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> said, `` this is a difficult case'' made all the more complex by <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION>'s `` quite novel'' role as `` broker-dealer-investment banker-adviser-owner. `` The facts are intricate and complicated; the law is fuzzy,'' he said. <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to borrow $ 864 million from a bank syndicate led by <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> likely violate <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> rules about posting stock as collateral on loans used to buy the stock. The order is the second against the tender offer in a federal court. A judge in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> has blocked it on antitrust grounds. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 9th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuirt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> will hear arguments May 13 on <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to overturn the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> ruling. <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to sell <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>' chemical operations stoked fears of losing 1,100 jobs in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> said the takeover should be halted for now because `` the potential ramifications ... to the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> community are uncertain and possibly adverse.'' In a countersuit, the <ORGANIZATION> Beazer </ORGANIZATION> group said <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION>'s filings in response to the tender offer also violated securities laws. But <PERSON> Cohill </PERSON> said the tender offer apparently `` is invalid under federal securities laws'' and `` until ... a valid tender offer is made, <ORGANIZATION> Koppers </ORGANIZATION> is not obligated'' to file the proper disclosures.
