<HEAD>GM Chairman Receives At Least $2.2 Million For 1987</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT time element in stock issuance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> received at least $ 2.2 million for 1987 in salary, exercised stock options and stock grants, the nation's largest automaker reported Friday in its proxy statement <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> received $ 867,000 in salary, earned $ 513,121 exercising stock options and was awarded a stock bonus worth $ 800,000 when it was granted on Dec. 7. The stock, issued in blocks over a three-year period that began in January, is worth considerably more now. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON> received at least $ 1.2 million for 1987: $ 517,000 in salary, $ 73,523 on exercised stock options and $ 600,000 in the stock bonus. <PERSON> Stempel </PERSON> became president in August, when he replaced the retired <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>. In all, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> paid $ 13.6 million in 1987 salaries to its top 58 executives and gave stock awards worth $ 16.2 million on Dec. 7 and $ 21.1 million on Friday to 4,961 executives. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 2 automaker, paid $ 247.9 million in bonuses for 1987 to 5,166 executives, it reported in a proxy statement mailed Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Vice Chairman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Poling </PERSON> earned nearly $ 11 million in 1987: $ 808,697 in salary, $ 2 million in cash bonuses and nearly $ 8.1 million on exercised stock options. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, who exercised no stock options, received $ 2.8 million in cash bonuses and $ 929,934 in salary. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s profit rose to $ 3.6 billion in 1987 from $ 2.95 billion in 1986, but for the second year in a row it earned too little on its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaking business to pay profit-sharing to its 350,000 hourly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> workers. The outcry over the millions of dollars executives received in bonuses for 1986 prompted <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors in 1987 to switch to an all-stock bonus and spread each stock grant over several years. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ephlin </PERSON> said the 1987 compensation received by top <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> executives `` still ca n't be justified rationally and constitutes an insult to common sense and fairness.'' During a time when <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s automaking business is earning so little, they said in a statement, `` we will leave the executives to forego all increases and supplementary awards in the spirit of shared sacrifice.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> distributed a record $ 636 million in profit-sharing checks in March to more than 156,000 hourly and salaried employees, an average of more than $ 4,000 each. On Friday, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s common stock closed at $ 72.75 a share, up from $ 71.62 -LCB-. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> Class E stock, based on earnings of its <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, declined to $ 41 a share from $ 41.62 -LCB-. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> Class H stock, based on earnings of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, closed at $ 30.25 a share, up from $ 30. When the stock bonuses were granted Dec. 7, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> common stock was worth $ 56.19 a share, Class E stock was worth $ 31.19 a share and Class H stock was worth $ 23.22 a share.
